22. Jonathan Harker's Journal. October 3. As I must do something or go mad,

12:26:32.130 --> 12:26:48.050
I write this diary. It is now six o'clock, and we are to meet in the study in half an hour and take something to eat, for Dr. Valhalla Singh and Dr. Seward are agreed that if we do not eat we cannot work our best. Our best will be, God knows, required to-day.

12:26:48.050 --> 12:27:06.770
I must keep writing at every chance, for I dare not stop to think. All, big and little, must go down. Perhaps at the end the little things may teach us most. The teaching, big or little, could not have landed Mina or me anywhere worse than we are to-day. However, we must trust and hope.

12:27:06.770 --> 12:27:23.970
Poor Mina told me just now, with tears running down her dear cheeks, that it is in trouble and trial that our faith is tested, that we must keep on trusting, and that God will aid us up to the end. The end! Oh my God, what end! To work! To work!

12:27:23.970 --> 12:27:45.810
When Dr. Valhalla Singh and Dr. Seward had come back from seeing poor Renfield, we went gravely into what was to be done. First, Dr. Seward told us that when he and Dr. Van Helmsing had gone down to the room below, they had found Renfield lying on the floor, all in a heap. His face was all bruised and crushed in, and the bones of the neck were broken.

12:27:46.350 --> 12:28:12.470
Dr. Seward asked the attendant who was on duty in the passage if he had heard anything. He said that he had been sitting down, he confessed to half-dosing, when he heard loud voices in the room, and that Renfield had called out loudly several times, God, God, God! After that there was the sound of falling. When he entered the room he found him lying on the floor, face down, just as the doctors had seen him.

12:28:12.470 --> 12:28:32.070
Van Helmsing asked if he had heard voices, or a voice, and he said he could not say, that at first it had seemed to him as if there were two, but as there was no one in the room, it could have been only one. He could swear to it, if required, that the word God was spoken by the patient.

12:28:32.650 --> 12:28:59.150
Dr. Seward said to us, when we were alone, that he did not wish to go into the matter. The question of an inquest had to be considered, and it would never do to put forward the truth, as no one would believe it. As it was, he thought that on the attendant's evidence he could give a certificate of death by misadventure in falling from bed. In case the coroner should demand it, there would be a formal inquest, necessarily to the same result.

12:28:59.150 --> 12:29:21.430
When the question began to be discussed as to what should be our next step, the very first thing we decided was that Mina should be in full confidence, that nothing of any sort, no matter how painful, should be kept from her. She herself agreed to its wisdom, and it was pitiful to see her so brave and yet so sorrowful and in such depth of despair.

12:29:22.150 --> 12:29:40.210
There must be no concealment, she said. Alas, we have had too much already, and besides, there is nothing in all the world that can give me more pain than I have already endured, than I suffer now. Whatever may happen, it must be of new hope or of new courage to me.

12:29:40.970 --> 12:29:46.710
Van Helsing was looking at her fixately as she spoke, and said, suddenly but quietly,

12:29:46.710 --> 12:29:54.770
But dear Madam Mina, are you not afraid? Not for yourself, but for others from yourself, after what has happened?

12:29:55.550 --> 12:30:01.430
Her face grew set in its lines, but her eyes shunned with the devotion of a martyr as she answered,

12:30:01.830 --> 12:30:04.190
Ah, no, for my mind is made up.

12:30:05.090 --> 12:30:13.770
To what? he asked gently, whilst we were all very still, for each in our own way, we had a sort of vague idea of what she meant.

12:30:14.350 --> 12:30:19.530
Her answer came with direct simplicity, as though she were simply stating a fact.

12:30:20.210 --> 12:30:28.470
Because, if I find it in myself, and I shall certainly watch keenly for it, a sign of harm to any that I love, I shall die.

12:30:29.490 --> 12:30:32.550
You would kill yourself? he asked hoarsely.

12:30:32.870 --> 12:30:39.250
I would, if there were no friend who loved me, who would save me from such a pain and so desperate an effort.

12:30:39.250 --> 12:30:50.370
She looked at him meaningly as she spoke. He was sitting down, but now he rose and came close to her and put his hand on her head, as he said solemnly,

12:30:50.830 --> 12:30:55.330
My child, there is such a one, if it were for your good, for myself.

12:30:55.550 --> 12:31:04.290
I could hold it in my account with God to find such a euthanasia for you, even at this moment, if it were best, nay, if it were safe.

12:31:04.290 --> 12:31:12.650
But my child, for a moment he seemed choked, and a great sob rose in his throat. He gulped down and went on.

12:31:13.350 --> 12:31:22.010
There are here some who would stand between you and death. You must not die. You must not die by any hand, but least of all your own.

12:31:22.510 --> 12:31:28.730
Until the other, who has fouled your sweet life, is true dead, you must not die.

12:31:28.730 --> 12:31:35.250
For if he is still with the quick undead, your death would make you even as he is.

12:31:35.810 --> 12:31:42.070
No, you must live. You must struggle and strive to live, though death would seem a boon unspeakable.

12:31:42.470 --> 12:31:47.050
You must fight death himself, though he come to you in pain or in joy.

12:31:47.430 --> 12:31:56.450
By the day or the night, in safety or in peril, on your living soul I charge you that you do not die, nay, nor think of death.

12:31:56.450 --> 12:31:58.910
Till this great evil be past.

12:32:00.210 --> 12:32:08.510
The poor dear grew white as death, and shook and shivered as I have seen a quicksand shiver and shake at the incoming of a tide.

12:32:09.250 --> 12:32:20.210
We were all silent. We could do nothing. At length she grew more calm, and turning to him said sweetly, but oh, so sorrowfully as she held out her hand,

12:32:20.210 --> 12:32:31.390
I promise you, my dear friend, that if God will let me live I shall strive to do so, till if it may be in his good time this horror may have passed from me.

12:32:32.210 --> 12:32:40.930
She was so good and brave that we all felt that our hearts were strengthened to work and endure for her, and we began to discuss what we were to do.

12:32:40.930 --> 12:32:53.890
I told her that she was to have all the papers in the safe, and all the papers or diaries and phonographs that we might hereafter use, and was to keep the record as she had done before.

12:32:54.510 --> 12:33:01.210
She was pleased with the prospect of anything to do, if pleased could be used in connection with so grim an interest.

12:33:02.070 --> 12:33:08.870
As usual, Van Helsing had thought ahead of everyone else, and was prepared with an exact ordering of our work.

12:33:08.870 --> 12:33:18.730
It is perhaps well, he said, that at our meeting after our visit to Carfax we decided not to do anything with the earth-boxes that lay there.

12:33:19.290 --> 12:33:29.030
Had we done so, the Count must have guessed our purpose, and would doubtless have taken measures in advance to frustrate such effort as regard to the others.

12:33:29.030 --> 12:33:42.950
But now he does not know our intentions. Nay, more in all probability he does not know that such a power exists to us as can sterilize its layers, so that he cannot use them as of old.

12:33:43.430 --> 12:33:52.070
We are now so much further advanced in our knowledge as to their disposition, that when we have examined the house in Piccadilly we may track the very last of them.

12:33:52.070 --> 12:33:59.510
Today then is ours, and in it rests our hope. The sun that rose on our sorrow this morning guards us in its course.

12:33:59.850 --> 12:34:07.970
Until it sets tonight that monster must retain whatever form he now has. He is confined within the limitations of his earthly envelope.

12:34:08.710 --> 12:34:18.310
He cannot melt into thin air, nor disappear through cracks or chinks or crannies. If he goes through a doorway he must open the door like a mortal.

12:34:18.310 --> 12:34:32.630
And so we have this day to hunt down all his layers and sterilize them. So we shall, if we have not yet catch him and destroy him, drive him to bay in some place where the catching and the destroying shall be in time, sure.

12:34:34.010 --> 12:34:46.410
Here I started up, for I could not contain myself of the thought that the minutes and seconds so preciously laden with Nina's life and happiness were flying from us, since whilst we talked action was impossible.

12:34:46.410 --> 12:34:49.970
But Van Helsing held up his hand warningly.

12:34:49.970 --> 12:34:57.350
Nay, friend Jonathan, he said, in this the quickest way home is the longest way, so your Proverbs say.

12:34:58.090 --> 12:35:08.310
We shall all act and act with desperate quick when the time has come. But think, in all probable the key of the situation is in that house in Piccadilly.

12:35:08.310 --> 12:35:21.210
The Count may have many houses which he has bought. Of them he will have deeds of purchase, keys and other things. He will have paper that he write on. He will have his books of checks.

12:35:22.070 --> 12:35:36.530
There are so many belongings that he must have somewhere. Why not in this place so central, so quiet, where he come and go by the front or the back at all hours, when in the very vast of the traffic there is none to notice?

12:35:36.530 --> 12:35:50.830
We shall go there and search that house, and when we learn what it holds, then we do what our friend Arthur calls, in his praises of hunt, stop the earth, and so we run down our old fox. So, is it no?

12:35:51.730 --> 12:35:56.710
Then let us come at once, I cried. We are wasting the precious precious time.

12:35:57.550 --> 12:36:03.870
The Professor did not move, but simply said, And how are we to get into that house in Piccadilly?

12:36:05.190 --> 12:36:08.430
Anyway, I cried, we shall break in if need be.

12:36:09.410 --> 12:36:13.490
And your police? Where will they be, and what will they say?

12:36:14.410 --> 12:36:22.790
I was staggered, but I knew that if he wished to delay, he had a good reason for it. So I said as quietly as I could,

12:36:23.630 --> 12:36:28.070
Don't wait more than need be. You know I am sure what torture I am in.

12:36:28.070 --> 12:36:39.170
Ah, my child, that I do, and indeed there is no wish of me to add to your anguish. But just think what can we do until all the world be at movement?

12:36:39.550 --> 12:36:46.310
Then will come our time. I have thought and thought, and it seems to me the simplest way is the best of all.

12:36:46.930 --> 12:36:52.510
Now, we wish to get into the house, but we have no key. Is it not so? I nodded.

12:36:52.510 --> 12:37:04.630
Now, suppose that you were in truth the owner of the house, and could not still get in, and think there was to you no conscience of the house-breaker, what would you do?

12:37:05.370 --> 12:37:10.090
I should get me a respectable locksmith, and set him to work to pick the luck for me.

12:37:11.050 --> 12:37:17.170
And your police, they would interfere, would they not? Oh no, not if they knew the man was properly employed.

12:37:18.030 --> 12:37:32.370
Then, he looked at me as keenly as he spoke, all that is in doubt is the conscience of the employer, and the belief of your policeman as to whether or not that employer has a good conscience or a bad one.

12:37:32.910 --> 12:37:40.590
Your police must indeed be zealous men and clever, oh, so clever in reading the heart that they trouble themselves in such matter.

12:37:40.590 --> 12:37:50.130
No, no, my friend Jonathan, you go take the luck of a hundred empty houses in this year London, or of any city in the world.

12:37:50.590 --> 12:37:58.330
And if you do it, as such things are rightly done, and at the time such things are rightly done, no one will interfere.

12:37:58.330 --> 12:38:12.510
I have read of a gentleman who owned a so fine house in London, and when he went for months of summer to Switzerland, and locked up his house, some burglar come, and broke window at back, and got in.

12:38:12.850 --> 12:38:20.470
Then he went, and made open the shutters in front, and walked out and in through the door, before the very eyes of the police.

12:38:21.030 --> 12:38:34.750
Then he had an auction in that house, and advertised it, and put up big notice, and when the day come, he sell off by a great auctioneer all the goods of that other man who owned them.

12:38:35.490 --> 12:38:48.010
Then he go to a builder, and he sell him that house, making an agreement that he pull it down and take all away within a certain time, and your police and other authorities helped him all they can.

12:38:48.650 --> 12:38:55.030
And when that owner come back from his holiday in Switzerland, he find only an empty hole where his house had been.

12:38:55.730 --> 12:39:00.250
This was all done in wrong way, and in our work we shall be on wrong way too.

12:39:01.070 --> 12:39:06.310
We shall not go so early that policemen who have little to think of, shall deem it strange.

12:39:06.910 --> 12:39:13.950
But we shall go after ten o'clock, when there are many about, and such things would be done were we indeed owners of the house.

12:39:13.950 --> 12:39:22.270
I could not but see how right he was, and the terrible despair of Mina's face became relaxed in thought.

12:39:22.810 --> 12:39:24.610
There was hope in such good counsel.

12:39:25.410 --> 12:39:26.790
Then Helsing went on,

12:39:27.330 --> 12:39:30.610
When once within the house we may find more clues.

12:39:31.130 --> 12:39:39.850
At any rate, some of us can remain there, whilst the rest find the other places where there be more earth-boxes, at Bermondsey and Miles End.

12:39:40.810 --> 12:39:42.350
Lord Godlimbering stood up.

12:39:42.870 --> 12:39:44.990
I can be of some use here, he said.

12:39:45.330 --> 12:39:50.250
I shall wire to my people to have horses and carriages where they will be most convenient.

12:39:51.070 --> 12:39:53.210
Look here, old fellow, said Morris.

12:39:53.970 --> 12:39:58.290
It is a capital idea to have already in case you want to go horse-packing.

12:39:58.350 --> 12:40:07.950
But don't you think that one of your snappy carriages, with its heraldic adornments, in a by-way of Walsworth or Miles End, would attract too much attention for our purpose?

12:40:07.950 --> 12:40:15.950
It seems to me we ought to take cabs when we go south or east, or even leave them somewhere near the neighbourhood where we are going to.

12:40:16.810 --> 12:40:19.150
Friend Quincy is right, said the Professor.

12:40:19.610 --> 12:40:23.150
His head is what you call in plain with the horizon.

12:40:23.970 --> 12:40:29.310
It is a difficult thing that we go to do, and we do not want no peoples to watch us, if so it may.

12:40:30.450 --> 12:40:40.150
Mina took a growing interest in everything, and I was rejoiced to see that the exigencies of affairs was helping her to forget for a time the terrible experience of the night.

12:40:40.650 --> 12:40:49.090
She was very, very pale, almost ghastly, and so thin that her lips were drawn away, showing her teeth in somewhat of prominence.

12:40:49.090 --> 12:41:03.150
I did not mention this last, lest it should give her needless pain, but it made my blood run cold in my veins to think of what had occurred with poor Lucy when the Count had sucked her blood.

12:41:03.730 --> 12:41:11.490
As yet there was no sign of the teeth growing sharper, but the time was as yet short, and there was time for fear.

12:41:11.490 --> 12:41:19.510
When we came to the discussion of the sequence of our efforts and of the disposition of our forces, there were new sources of doubt.

12:41:19.950 --> 12:41:25.970
It was finally agreed that before starting for Piccadilly we should destroy the Count's lair close at hand.

12:41:26.310 --> 12:41:38.290
In case he should find it out too soon, we would thus still be ahead of him in our work of destruction, and his presence in his purely material shape and at his weakest might give us some new clue.

12:41:38.290 --> 12:41:58.030
As to the disposition of forces, it was suggested by the Professor that after our visit to Carfax we should all enter the house in Piccadilly, that the two doctors and I should remain there whilst Lord Godamring and Quincy found the lairs at Wallsworth and Miles End and destroyed them.

12:41:58.030 --> 12:42:12.110
It was possible, if not likely, the Professor urged, that the Count may appear in Piccadilly during the day, and that if so, we might be able to cope with him there and then. At any rate, we might be able to follow him in force.

12:42:12.830 --> 12:42:20.390
To this plan I strenuously objected, and so far as my going was concerned, for I said that I intended to stay and protect Mina.

12:42:20.390 --> 12:42:44.530
I thought that my mind was made up on this subject, but Mina would not listen to my objections. She said that that might be some law matter in which I could be useful, that amongst the Count's papers might be some clue which I could understand out of my experience in Transylvania, and that, as it was, all the strength we could muster was required to cope with the Count's extraordinary power.

12:42:44.530 --> 12:42:53.050
I had to give in, for Mina's resolution was fixed. She said that it was the last hope for her that we should all work together.

12:42:53.970 --> 12:43:10.550
As for me, she said, I have no fear. Things have been as bad as they can be, and whatever may happen must have in it some element of hope or comfort. Go, my husband, God can, if He wishes it, guard me as well alone as with any one present.

12:43:10.550 --> 12:43:20.310
So I started up crying out, Then in God's name let us come at once, for we are losing time. The Count may come to Piccadilly earlier than we think.

12:43:21.230 --> 12:43:26.590
Not so, said Van Helsing, holding up his hand. But why, I asked.

12:43:27.590 --> 12:43:34.590
Do you forget, he said, with actually a smile, that last night he banqueted heavily and will sleep late?

12:43:34.590 --> 12:43:44.090
Did I forget? Shall I ever? Can I ever? Can any of us ever forget that terrible scene?

12:43:44.810 --> 12:43:53.750
Mina struggled hard to keep her brave countenance, but the pain overmastered her, and she put her hands before her face and shuddered whilst she moaned.

12:43:53.750 --> 12:44:09.830
Van Helsing had not intended to recall her frightful experience. He had simply lost sight of her and her part in the affair in his intellectual effort. When it struck him what he said, he was horrified at his thoughtlessness and tried to comfort her.

12:44:09.830 --> 12:44:22.250
Oh, Madame Mina, he said, dear, dear Madame Mina, alas, that I, of all who so reverence you, should have said anything so forgetful.

12:44:22.690 --> 12:44:32.750
These stupid old lips of mine and the stupid old head do not deserve so, but you will forget it, will you not? He bent low beside her as he spoke.

12:44:33.390 --> 12:44:48.770
She took his hand, and looking at him through her tears, said hoarsely, No, I shall not forget, for it is well that I remember, and with it I have so much in memory of you that is sweet that I take it all together.

12:44:49.330 --> 12:44:55.030
Now, you must all be going soon. Breakfast is ready, and we must all eat, that we may be strong.

12:44:56.290 --> 12:45:05.370
Breakfast was a strange meal to us all. We tried to be cheerful and encourage each other, and Mina was the brightest and most cheerful of us.

12:45:05.770 --> 12:45:21.430
When it was over, Van Helsing stood up and said, Now, my dear friends, we go forth to our terrible enterprise. Are we all armed, as we were on that night when first we visited our enemy's lair, armed against ghostly as well as carnal attacks?

12:45:21.430 --> 12:45:33.890
We all assured him, Then it is well. Now, Madam Mina, you are in any case quite safe here until the sunset, and before then we shall return, if, we shall return.

12:45:34.690 --> 12:45:45.950
But before we go, let me see you armed against personal attack. I have myself, since you came down, prepared your chamber by the placing of things of which we know, so that he may not enter.

12:45:45.950 --> 12:45:59.430
Now let me guard yourself. On your forehead I touched this piece of sacred wafer in the name of the father, the son, and there was a fearful scream which almost froze our hearts to hear.

12:46:00.090 --> 12:46:08.910
As he had placed the wafer on Mina's forehead, it had seared it, had burnt into the flesh, as though it had been a piece of white-hot metal.

12:46:08.910 --> 12:46:22.490
My poor darling's brain had told her the significance of the fact as quickly as her nerves received the pain of it, and the two so overwhelmed her that her overwrought nature had its voice in that dreadful scream.

12:46:23.550 --> 12:46:35.910
But the words to her thought came quickly. The echo of the scream had not ceased to ring on the air when there came the reaction, and she sank on her knees on the floor in an agony of abasement.

12:46:36.790 --> 12:46:42.990
Pulling her beautiful hair over her face, as the leper of all his mantles she wailed out,

12:46:44.410 --> 12:46:52.910
Unclean, unclean! Even the Almighty shuns my polluted flesh. I must bear this mark of shame on my forehead until Judgment Day.

12:46:53.970 --> 12:47:02.930
They all paused. I had thrown myself beside her in an agony of helpless grief, and putting my arms around her, held her tight.

12:47:02.930 --> 12:47:12.390
For a few moments our sorrowful hearts beat together, while the friends around us turned away their eyes that ran tears silently.

12:47:13.430 --> 12:47:24.470
Then, when Helsing turned and said gravely, so gravely that I could not help feeling that he was in some way inspired, and was stating things outside himself,

12:47:25.190 --> 12:47:39.760
It may be that you shall have to bear that mark till God himself sees fit, as he most surely shall on that Judgment Day, to redress all wrongs of the earth and of his children that he has placed thereon.

12:47:39.760 --> 12:47:56.420
And, O Madamina, my dear, my dear, may we who love you be there to see when that red scar, the sign of God's knowledge of what has been, shall pass away, and leave your forehead as pure as the heart we know.

12:47:56.420 --> 12:48:10.260
For so surely as we live, that scar shall pass away when God sees right to lift the burden that is hard upon us. Till then we bear our cross, as his son did in obedience to his will.

12:48:10.260 --> 12:48:26.600
It may be that we are chosen instruments of his good pleasure, and that we ascend to his bidding as that other through stripes and shame, through fears and blood, through doubts and fear, and all that makes the difference between God and man.

12:48:27.180 --> 12:48:40.380
There was hope in his voice, and comfort, and the need for resignation. Mina and I both felt so, and simultaneously we each took one of the old man's hands, bent over it, and kissed it.

12:48:41.160 --> 12:49:02.280
Then, without a word, we all knelt down together, and all holding hands, swore to be true to each other. We men pledged ourselves to raise the veil of sorrow from the head of her whom each in his own way we loved, and we prayed for help and guidance in the terrible task which lay before us.

12:49:02.280 --> 12:49:11.840
It was then time to start. So I said farewell to Mina, a parting which neither of us shall forget to our dying day, and we set out.

12:49:12.580 --> 12:49:35.960
To one thing I have made up my mind. If we find out that Mina must be a vampire in the end, then she shall not go into that unknown and terrible land alone. I suppose it is thus that in old times one vampire meant many. Just as their hideous bodies could only rest in sacred earth, so the holiest love was the recruiting sergeant for their ghastly ranks.

12:49:37.240 --> 12:49:53.460
We entered Carfax without trouble, and found all things the same as on that first occasion. It was hard to believe that amongst so prosaic surroundings of neglect and dust and decay there was any ground for such fear as already we knew.

12:49:53.460 --> 12:50:12.040
Had not our minds been made up, and had there not been terrible memories to spur us on, we could hardly have proceeded with our tasks. We found no papers or any sign of use in the house, and in the old chapel the great boxers looked just as we had seen them last.

12:50:13.220 --> 12:50:16.960
Dr. Van Helsing said to us solemnly as we stood before him,

12:50:44.560 --> 12:51:02.820
As he spoke, he took from his bag a screwdriver and a wrench, and very soon the top of one of the cases was thrown open. The earth smelled musty and close, but we did not somehow seem to mind, for our attention was concentrated on the professor.

12:51:03.520 --> 12:51:15.200
Taking from his box a piece of the sacred wafer, he laid it down reverently on the earth, and then shutting down the lid began to screw it home, we aiding him as he worked.

12:51:16.160 --> 12:51:26.640
One by one we treated in the same way each of the great boxes, and left them as we had found them to all appearances, but in each was a portion of the host.

12:51:26.640 --> 12:51:30.680
When we closed the door behind us, the professor said solemnly,

12:51:31.620 --> 12:51:45.520
So much is already done. It may be that with all the others we can be so successful. Then the sunset of this evening may shine of Madame Mina's forehead all white as ivory and with no stain.

12:51:46.740 --> 12:51:57.240
As we passed across the lawn, on our way to the station to catch our train, we could see the front of the asylum. I looked eagerly, and in the window of my own room saw Mina.

12:51:57.920 --> 12:52:06.880
I waved my hand to her, and nodded to tell that our work there was successfully accomplished. She nodded in reply to show that she understood.

12:52:06.880 --> 12:52:20.520
The last I saw her she was waving her hand in farewell. It was with a heavy heart that we sought the station and just caught the train, which was steaming in as we reached the platform. I have written this in the train.

12:52:36.880 --> 12:52:47.280
Under the circumstances, it wouldn't seem so bad for us to break into an empty house. But you are a solicitor, and the Incorporated Law Society might tell you that you should have known better.

12:52:48.120 --> 12:53:03.040
I demurred as to my not sharing any danger, even of odium. But he went on, Besides, it will attract less attention if there are not too many of us. My title will make it all right with the locksmith, and with any police that might come along.

12:53:03.040 --> 12:53:18.700
You had better go with Jack and the Professor and stay in Green Park, somewhere in sight of the house. And when you see the door opened and the Smith has gone away, do you all come across? We shall be on the lookout for you, and shall let you in.

12:53:18.700 --> 12:53:33.760
The advice is good, said Van Helsing, so we said no more. Gordon Ling and Morris hurried off in a cab, we following in another. At the corner of Arlington Street, our contingent got out and strolled into the Green Park.

12:53:34.700 --> 12:53:46.000
My heart beat as I saw the house on which so much of our hope was centered, looming up grim and silent in its deserted condition amongst its more lively and spruced-up neighbours.

12:53:46.700 --> 12:53:59.800
We sat down on a bench within good view, and began to smoke cigars so as to attract as little attention as possible. The minutes seemed to pass with leaden feet as we waited for the coming of the others.

12:54:00.740 --> 12:54:14.640
At length we saw a four-wheeler drive up. Out of it, in leisurely fashion, got Lord Godumring and Morris, and down from the box descended a fixed-set working man with his rush-woven basket of tools.

12:54:14.640 --> 12:54:25.020
Morris paid the cabman, who touched his hat, and drove away. Together the two ascended the steps, and Lord Godumring pointed out what he wanted done.

12:54:25.880 --> 12:54:34.060
The workman took off his coat leisurely and hung it on one of the spikes of the rail, saying something to the policeman who just then sauntered by.

12:54:34.060 --> 12:54:47.260
The policeman nodded acquaince, and the man kneeling down placed his bag beside him. After searching through it, he took out a selection of tools, which he proceeded to lay beside him in orderly fashion.

12:54:47.880 --> 12:54:54.880
Then he stood up, looked in the keyhole, blew into it, and turning to his employers, made some remark.

12:54:56.100 --> 12:55:05.960
Lord Godumring smiled, and the man lifted a good-sized bunch of keys. Selecting one of them, he began to probe the lock, as if feeling his way with it.

12:55:06.600 --> 12:55:16.680
After fumbling about for a bit, he tried a second and then a third. All at once the door opened under a slight push from him, and he and the two others entered the hall.

12:55:16.680 --> 12:55:28.160
We sat still. My own cigar burned furiously, but Van Helsing's went cold altogether. We waited patiently, as we saw the workman come out and bring his bag.

12:55:29.260 --> 12:55:40.180
Then he held the door partly open, steadying it with his knees, whilst he fitted a key to the lock. This he finally handed to Lord Godumring, who took out his purse and gave him something.

12:55:40.180 --> 12:55:49.180
The man touched his hat, took his bag, put on his coat, and departed. Not a soul took the slightest notice of the whole transaction.

12:55:50.260 --> 12:56:00.600
When the man had fairly gone, we three crossed the street and knocked at the door. It was immediately opened by Quincy Morris, besides whom stood Lord Godumring lighting a cigar.

12:56:00.600 --> 12:56:15.800
The place smelled so vilely, said the latter as we walked in. It did indeed smell vilely, like the old chapel at Carfax, and with our previous experience it was plain to us that the Count had been using the place pretty freely.

12:56:16.640 --> 12:56:29.460
We moved to explore the house, all keeping together in case of attack, for we knew we had a strong and wily enemy to deal with, and as yet we did not know whether the Count might not be in the house.

12:56:29.460 --> 12:56:43.860
In the dining-room, which lay at the back of the hall, we found eight boxes of earth. Eight boxes only, out of the nine which we sought. Our work was not over, and would never be until we had found the missing box.

12:56:43.860 --> 12:57:00.480
First we opened the shutters of a window, which looked out across a narrow stone-flagged yard at the blank face of a stable, pointed to look like the front of a miniature house. There were no windows in it, so we were not afraid of being overlooked.

12:57:00.480 --> 12:57:18.940
We did not lose any time in examining the chests. With the tools which we had brought with us, we opened them one by one, and treated them as we had treated those others in the old chapel. It was evident to us that the Count was not at present in the house, and we proceeded to search for any of his effects.

12:57:19.540 --> 12:57:33.360
After a curse-free glance at the rest of the rooms, from basement to attic, we came to the conclusion that the dining-room contained any effects which might belong to the Count, and so we proceeded to minutely examine them.

12:57:33.360 --> 12:57:54.320
They lay in a sort of orderly disorder on the great dining-room table. There were title deeds of the Piccadilly House in a great bundle, deeds of the purchase of the houses at Miles End and Bermondsey, note-paper envelopes and pens and ink, all were covered up in a thin wrapping paper to keep them from the dust.

12:57:54.320 --> 12:58:12.900
There was also a clothes-brush, a brush and comb, and a jug and basin, the latter containing dirty water which was ridden, as if with blood. Last of all was a little heap of keys of all sorts and sizes, probably those belonging to the other houses.

12:58:12.900 --> 12:58:28.280
When we had examined this last find, Lord Godelming and Quincy Morris, taking accurate notes of the various addresses of the houses in the East and South, took with them the keys in a great bunch and set out to destroy the boxes in these places.

12:58:28.920 --> 12:58:35.160
The rest of us are, with what patience we can, waiting their return, or the coming of the Count.

12:58:56.660 --> 12:58:57.640
October 3.

12:58:58.620 --> 12:59:02.260
The time seemed terribly long whilst we were waiting for the coming of our Gottemling and

12:59:02.260 --> 12:59:03.000
Quincy Morris.

12:59:03.580 --> 12:59:06.960
The professor tried to keep our minds active by using them all the time.

12:59:07.360 --> 12:59:12.100
I could see his beneficent purpose by the side glances which he threw from time to time

12:59:12.100 --> 12:59:12.620
at Harker.

12:59:13.220 --> 12:59:16.400
The poor fellow was overwhelmed in a misery that is appalling to see.

12:59:17.040 --> 12:59:21.400
Last night he was a frank, happy-looking man with a strong, youthful face, full of energy

12:59:21.400 --> 12:59:22.540
and with dark brown hair.

12:59:23.140 --> 12:59:28.120
Today he is a drawn, haggard old man, whose white hair matches well with the hollow burning

12:59:28.120 --> 12:59:30.060
eyes and grief-written lines of his face.

12:59:30.540 --> 12:59:32.020
His energy is still intact.

12:59:32.020 --> 12:59:33.880
In fact, he is like a living flame.

12:59:34.440 --> 12:59:39.300
This may yet be his salvation, for if all go well, it will tide him over the despairing

12:59:39.300 --> 12:59:39.680
period.

12:59:40.420 --> 12:59:44.180
He will then, in a kind of way, wake again to the realities of life.

12:59:44.760 --> 12:59:45.440
Poor fellow!

12:59:45.660 --> 12:59:49.740
I thought my own trouble was bad enough, but his...

12:59:49.740 --> 12:59:54.020
The professor knows this well enough, and is doing his best to keep his mind active.

12:59:54.680 --> 12:59:58.300
What he has been saying was, under the circumstances of absorbing interest.

12:59:58.920 --> 13:00:00.900
So well as I can remember, here it is.

13:00:01.580 --> 13:00:06.600
I have studied, over and over again since they came into my hands, all the papers relating

13:00:06.600 --> 13:00:11.260
to this monster, and the more I have studied, the greater seems the necessity to utterly

13:00:11.260 --> 13:00:12.120
stamp him out.

13:00:12.640 --> 13:00:17.300
All through there are signs of his advance, not only of his power, but of his knowledge

13:00:17.300 --> 13:00:17.760
of it.

13:00:18.080 --> 13:00:23.800
As I learned from the researches of my friend Armanus of Budapest, he was in life a most

13:00:23.800 --> 13:00:28.860
wonderful man, soldier, statesman, and alchemist, which latter was the highest development of

13:00:28.860 --> 13:00:30.260
science knowledge of his time.

13:00:31.020 --> 13:00:36.240
He had a mighty brain, a learning beyond compare, and a heart that knew no fear and no remorse.

13:00:36.980 --> 13:00:41.420
He dared even to attend the Schlossmanns, and there was no branch of knowledge of his

13:00:41.420 --> 13:00:42.700
time that he did not assay.

13:00:43.720 --> 13:00:48.400
Well, in him the brain-power survived the physical death, though it would seem that

13:00:48.400 --> 13:00:49.780
memory was not all complete.

13:00:50.420 --> 13:00:54.200
In some faculties of mind he has, and is, only a child.

13:00:54.940 --> 13:00:59.740
But he is growing, and some things that were childish at the first are now of man's stature.

13:01:00.140 --> 13:01:02.180
He is experimenting, and doing it well.

13:01:02.640 --> 13:01:08.120
And if it had not been that we had crossed his path, he would be yet—he may be yet

13:01:08.120 --> 13:01:13.960
if we fail—the father or furtherer of a new life of beings, whose road must lead through

13:01:13.960 --> 13:01:15.320
death, not life.

13:01:16.260 --> 13:01:22.240
Harker groaned and said, And this is all a raid against my darling, but how is he experimenting?

13:01:22.240 --> 13:01:24.180
The knowledge may help us to defeat him.

13:01:24.900 --> 13:01:29.640
He has all along, since his coming, been trying his power, slowly but surely.

13:01:30.260 --> 13:01:32.160
That big child-brain of his is working.

13:01:32.720 --> 13:01:35.700
Well for us it is as yet a child-brain.

13:01:36.240 --> 13:01:40.560
For had he dared, at the first, to attempt certain things, he would long ago have been

13:01:40.560 --> 13:01:41.440
beyond our power.

13:01:42.060 --> 13:01:46.500
However, he means to succeed, and a man who has centuries before him can afford to wait

13:01:46.500 --> 13:01:47.220
and go slow.

13:01:47.860 --> 13:01:49.760
Festina lente may well be his motto.

13:01:50.440 --> 13:01:52.500
I fail to understand, said Harker wearily.

13:01:52.900 --> 13:01:54.420
Oh, do be more plain to me.

13:01:54.540 --> 13:01:56.600
Perhaps grief and trouble are dulling my brain.

13:01:57.280 --> 13:02:00.060
The professor laid his hand tenderly on his shoulder as he spoke.

13:02:00.660 --> 13:02:02.560
Ah, my child, I will be plain.

13:02:03.240 --> 13:02:07.520
Do you not see how, of late, this monster has been creeping into knowledge experimentally?

13:02:08.040 --> 13:02:14.620
He has been making use of the Zophagous patient to affect his entry into friend John's home.

13:02:15.140 --> 13:02:20.540
For your vampire, though in all afterwards he can come how and when he will, must at

13:02:20.540 --> 13:02:23.560
the first make entry only when asked thereto by an inmate.

13:02:24.400 --> 13:02:27.460
But these are not his most important experiments.

13:02:28.140 --> 13:02:33.120
Do we not see how at the first all these great boxes were moved by others?

13:02:33.660 --> 13:02:36.200
He knew not then, but that must be so.

13:02:37.320 --> 13:02:42.820
But all the time that so great child-brain of his was growing, and he began to consider

13:02:42.820 --> 13:02:49.180
whether he might not himself move the box, so he began to try to help, and then, when

13:02:49.180 --> 13:02:54.240
he found that this be all right, he tried to move them all alone, and so he progress,

13:02:54.740 --> 13:02:58.720
and he scattered these graves of him, and none but he know where they are hidden.

13:02:59.840 --> 13:03:04.740
He may have intended to bury them deep in the ground, so that only he may use them in

13:03:04.740 --> 13:03:07.420
the night, or at such time as he can change his form.

13:03:07.980 --> 13:03:12.800
They do him equal well, and none may know these are his hiding-place, but my child do

13:03:12.800 --> 13:03:15.360
not despair, this knowledge came to him just too late.

13:03:15.840 --> 13:03:20.820
Already all of his lairs but one be sterilized as for him, and before the sunset this shall

13:03:20.820 --> 13:03:21.380
be so.

13:03:22.000 --> 13:03:24.300
Then he have no place where he can move and hide.

13:03:24.740 --> 13:03:27.100
I delayed this morning, so that we might be sure.

13:03:27.600 --> 13:03:29.940
Is there not more at stake for us than for him?

13:03:30.580 --> 13:03:32.380
Then why not be more careful than him?

13:03:32.700 --> 13:03:38.200
By my clock it is one hour already, and, if all be well, our friend Arthur and Quincy

13:03:38.200 --> 13:03:39.180
are on their way to us.

13:03:39.680 --> 13:03:43.680
Today is our day, and we must go sure, if slow, and lose no chance.

13:03:44.120 --> 13:03:47.020
See, there are five of us when those absent ones return.

13:03:48.140 --> 13:03:52.540
Whilst we were speaking we were startled by a knock at the hall door, the double postman's

13:03:52.540 --> 13:03:53.620
knock of the telegraph boy.

13:03:54.320 --> 13:03:59.180
We all moved out to the hall with one impulse, and Van Helsing, holding up his hand to us

13:03:59.180 --> 13:04:01.960
to keep silence, stepped to the door and opened it.

13:04:02.200 --> 13:04:03.780
The boy handed in a dispatch.

13:04:04.200 --> 13:04:08.140
The professor closed the door again, and after looking at the direction opened it and read

13:04:08.140 --> 13:04:10.140
Look out for Dee.

13:04:10.440 --> 13:04:14.820
He has just now, twelve forty-five, come from Carfax hurriedly and hasten towards the south.

13:04:15.360 --> 13:04:19.660
He seems to be going the round and may want to see you, Mina."

13:04:19.660 --> 13:04:22.700
There was a pause, broken by Jonathan Harker's voice.

13:04:23.080 --> 13:04:25.480
Now, God be thanked, we shall soon meet.

13:04:26.320 --> 13:04:30.340
Van Helsing turned to him quickly and said, God will act in his own way and time.

13:04:30.840 --> 13:04:35.700
Do not fear and do not rejoice as yet, for what we wish for at the moment may be our

13:04:35.700 --> 13:04:36.600
own undoings.

13:04:37.120 --> 13:04:41.280
I care for nothing now, he answered hotly, except to wipe out this brute from the face

13:04:41.280 --> 13:04:41.900
of creation.

13:04:42.120 --> 13:04:43.800
I would sell my soul to do it.

13:04:44.160 --> 13:04:46.820
O, hush, hush, my child, said Van Helsing.

13:04:47.220 --> 13:04:51.420
God does not purchase souls in this wise, and the devil, though he may purchase, does

13:04:51.420 --> 13:04:52.160
not keep faith.

13:04:52.660 --> 13:04:56.980
But God is merciful and just, and knows your pain and your devotion to that dear Madam

13:04:56.980 --> 13:04:57.220
Mina.

13:04:57.920 --> 13:05:01.340
Think you how her pain would be doubled did she but hear your wild words.

13:05:01.820 --> 13:05:03.280
Do not fear any of us.

13:05:03.280 --> 13:05:06.940
We are all devoted to this cause, and to-day shall see the end.

13:05:07.480 --> 13:05:09.060
The time is coming for action.

13:05:09.520 --> 13:05:12.100
To-day this vampire is limit to the powers of man.

13:05:12.500 --> 13:05:14.100
Until sunset he may not change.

13:05:14.560 --> 13:05:16.640
It will take him time yet to arrive here.

13:05:17.040 --> 13:05:21.820
See it is twenty minutes past one, and there are yet some times before he can hither come,

13:05:22.220 --> 13:05:23.520
be he ever so quick.

13:05:24.260 --> 13:05:28.100
What we must hope for is that my Lord Arthur and Quincy arrive first.

13:05:28.680 --> 13:05:33.400
About half an hour after we received Mrs. Harker's telegram there came a quiet, resolute

13:05:33.400 --> 13:05:34.340
knock at the hall door.

13:05:34.820 --> 13:05:39.540
It was just an ordinary knock, such as is given hourly by thousands of gentlemen, but

13:05:39.540 --> 13:05:41.620
it made the Professor's heart and mind beat loudly.

13:05:42.040 --> 13:05:44.560
We looked at each other, and together moved out into the hall.

13:05:45.120 --> 13:05:49.820
We each held ready to use our various armaments, the spiritual in the left hand, the mortal

13:05:49.820 --> 13:05:50.360
in the right.

13:05:50.920 --> 13:05:55.060
Van Helsing pulled back the latch, and holding the door half open, stood back, having both

13:05:55.060 --> 13:05:56.100
hands ready for action.

13:05:56.600 --> 13:06:01.180
The gladness of our hearts must have shone upon our faces, when on the step, close to

13:06:01.180 --> 13:06:04.100
the door, we saw Lord Gadamaling and Quincy Morris.

13:06:04.400 --> 13:06:08.600
They came in quickly and closed the door behind them, the former saying, as they moved along

13:06:08.600 --> 13:06:09.080
the hall.

13:06:09.880 --> 13:06:10.640
It is all right.

13:06:10.700 --> 13:06:14.180
We found both places, six boxes in each, and we destroyed them all.

13:06:14.640 --> 13:06:15.080
Destroyed?

13:06:15.100 --> 13:06:15.740
asked the Professor.

13:06:15.960 --> 13:06:16.500
For him?

13:06:16.860 --> 13:06:18.240
We were silent for a minute.

13:06:18.480 --> 13:06:21.380
And then Quincy said, There's nothing to do but wait here.

13:06:21.700 --> 13:06:25.860
If, however, he doesn't turn up by five o'clock, we must start off, for it won't do to leave

13:06:25.860 --> 13:06:27.420
Mrs. Harker alone after sunset.

13:06:28.080 --> 13:06:32.620
He will be here before long now, said Van Helsing, who had been consulting his pocketbook.

13:06:33.300 --> 13:06:36.520
Not to bene, in Madame's telegram he went south from Carfax.

13:06:37.120 --> 13:06:41.540
That means he went to cross the river, and he could only do so at slack of tide, which

13:06:41.540 --> 13:06:43.080
should be something before one o'clock.

13:06:43.560 --> 13:06:45.480
That he went south has a meaning for us.

13:06:45.760 --> 13:06:49.860
He is as yet only suspicious, and he went from Carfax first to the place where he would

13:06:49.860 --> 13:06:51.400
suspect interference leased.

13:06:51.940 --> 13:06:54.860
You must have been at Bermondsey only a short time before him.

13:06:54.860 --> 13:06:58.640
That he is not here already shows that he went to Mile End next.

13:06:58.980 --> 13:07:03.100
This took him some time, for he would then have to be carried over the river in some

13:07:03.100 --> 13:07:03.440
way.

13:07:03.920 --> 13:07:06.540
Believe me, my friends, we shall not have long to wait now.

13:07:06.980 --> 13:07:10.620
We should have ready some plan of attack, so that we may throw away no chance.

13:07:11.140 --> 13:07:12.420
Hush, there is no time now.

13:07:12.580 --> 13:07:13.300
Have all your arms.

13:07:13.340 --> 13:07:13.820
Be ready.

13:07:14.160 --> 13:07:18.720
He held up a warning hand as he spoke, for we all could hear a key softly inserted into

13:07:18.720 --> 13:07:19.840
the lock of the hall door.

13:07:20.380 --> 13:07:25.140
I could not but admire, even at such a moment, the way in which a dominant spirit asserts

13:07:25.140 --> 13:07:25.540
itself.

13:07:26.180 --> 13:07:30.440
In all our hunting parties and adventures in different parts of the world, Quincy Morris

13:07:30.440 --> 13:07:34.780
had always been the one to arrange the plan of action, and Arthur and I seemed to be accustomed

13:07:34.780 --> 13:07:36.200
to obey him implicitly.

13:07:36.700 --> 13:07:39.420
Now the old habits seemed to be renewed instinctively.

13:07:39.760 --> 13:07:44.620
With a swift glance round the room he at once laid out our plan of attack, and without speaking

13:07:44.620 --> 13:07:47.100
a word with a gesture placed each of us in position.

13:07:47.100 --> 13:07:51.980
Then Helsing, Harker, and I were just behind the door, so that when it opened the Professor

13:07:51.980 --> 13:07:54.900
could guard it whilst we two stepped between the intercomer and the door.

13:07:55.820 --> 13:07:59.860
Gottemling behind and Quincy in front stood just out of sight, ready to move in front

13:07:59.860 --> 13:08:00.420
of the window.

13:08:01.020 --> 13:08:04.620
We waited in a suspense that made the seconds pass with nightmare slowness.

13:08:05.060 --> 13:08:07.760
The slow, careful steps came along the hall.

13:08:08.320 --> 13:08:10.660
The Count was evidently prepared for some surprise.

13:08:10.940 --> 13:08:12.240
At least he feared it.

13:08:12.800 --> 13:08:15.320
Suddenly with a single bound he leapt into the room.

13:08:15.980 --> 13:08:19.160
Winning away past us before any of us could raise a hand to stay him.

13:08:19.740 --> 13:08:23.760
There was something so panther-like in the movement, something so unhuman, that it seemed

13:08:23.760 --> 13:08:25.760
to sober us all from the shock of his coming.

13:08:26.440 --> 13:08:30.460
The first to act was Harker, who with a quick movement threw himself before the door leading

13:08:30.460 --> 13:08:32.520
into the room in front of the house.

13:08:32.980 --> 13:08:37.560
As the Count saw us a horrible sort of snarl passed over his face, showing the eye-tooth

13:08:37.560 --> 13:08:43.280
long and pointed, but the evil smile is quickly passed into a cold stare of lion-like disdain.

13:08:43.280 --> 13:08:47.780
His expression again changed, as, with a single impulse, we all advanced upon him.

13:08:48.240 --> 13:08:52.920
It was a pity that we had not some better yet organized plan of attack, for even at

13:08:52.920 --> 13:08:54.620
the moment I wondered what we were to do.

13:08:55.020 --> 13:08:58.860
I did not myself know whether our lethal weapons would avail of us anything.

13:08:59.340 --> 13:09:03.840
Harker evidently meant to try the matter, for he had ready his great Kukuri-knife and

13:09:03.840 --> 13:09:05.300
made a fierce and sudden cut at him.

13:09:05.700 --> 13:09:10.560
The blow was a powerful one, only the diabolical quickness of the Count's leap back saved him.

13:09:10.560 --> 13:09:14.000
A second less, and the trenchant blade had shorn through his heart.

13:09:14.520 --> 13:09:18.820
As it was, the point just cut the cloth of his coat, making a wide gap whence a bundle

13:09:18.820 --> 13:09:20.940
of bank-notes and stream of gold fell out.

13:09:21.320 --> 13:09:25.660
The expression of the Count's face was so hellish that for a moment I feared for Harker,

13:09:25.960 --> 13:09:29.060
though I saw him throw the terrible knife aloft again for another stroke.

13:09:29.680 --> 13:09:35.660
Instinctively I moved forward with a protective impulse, holding the crucifix and wafer in

13:09:35.660 --> 13:09:36.360
my left hand.

13:09:36.360 --> 13:09:41.360
I felt a mighty power fly along my arm, and it was without surprise that I saw the monster

13:09:41.360 --> 13:09:45.240
cower back before a similar movement made spontaneously by each one of us.

13:09:45.640 --> 13:09:50.660
It would be impossible to describe the expression of hate and baffled malignity, of anger and

13:09:50.660 --> 13:09:53.100
hellish rage which came over the Count's face.

13:09:53.640 --> 13:09:58.060
His waxen hue became greenish-yellow by the contrast of his burning eyes, and the red

13:09:58.060 --> 13:10:01.540
scar on the forehead showed on the pallid skin like a palpitating wound.

13:10:01.940 --> 13:10:06.760
The next instant, with a sinuous dive, he swept under Harker's arm ere his blow could

13:10:06.760 --> 13:10:11.380
fall and, grasping a handful of the money from the floor, dashed across the room, threw

13:10:11.380 --> 13:10:12.320
himself at the window.

13:10:12.900 --> 13:10:16.840
Amid the crash and glitter of the falling glass he tumbled into the flagged area below.

13:10:17.800 --> 13:10:21.580
Through the sound of the shivering glass I could hear the ting of the gold as some of

13:10:21.580 --> 13:10:22.960
the sovereigns fell on the flagging.

13:10:23.680 --> 13:10:26.520
We ran over and saw him spring, unhurt from the ground.

13:10:27.000 --> 13:10:31.360
He, rushing up the stairs, crossed the flagged yard and pushed open the stable door.

13:10:31.640 --> 13:10:33.180
There he turned and spoke to us.

13:10:33.560 --> 13:10:37.800
You think to baffle me, you with your pale faces all in a row, like sheep in a butcher's.

13:10:38.080 --> 13:10:39.800
You shall be sorry yet, each one of you.

13:10:40.140 --> 13:10:43.620
You think that you have left me without place to rest, but I have more.

13:10:44.000 --> 13:10:45.320
My revenge has just begun.

13:10:45.700 --> 13:10:48.800
I spread it over centuries, and time is on my side.

13:10:49.200 --> 13:10:54.280
Your girls that you all love are mine already, and through them you and others shall yet

13:10:54.280 --> 13:10:58.420
be mine, my creatures, to do my bidding and be my jackals when I want to feed.

13:10:58.980 --> 13:10:59.460
Bah!

13:11:00.220 --> 13:11:04.820
With a contemptuous sneer he passed quickly through the door, and we heard the rusty bolt

13:11:04.820 --> 13:11:06.560
creak as he fastened it behind him.

13:11:07.140 --> 13:11:08.760
A door beyond opened and shut.

13:11:09.060 --> 13:11:10.940
The first of us to speak was the professor.

13:11:11.400 --> 13:11:14.960
Realizing the difficulty of following him through the stable we moved towards the hall.

13:11:15.560 --> 13:11:17.080
We have learned something, much.

13:11:17.400 --> 13:11:19.440
Notwithstanding his brave words he fears us.

13:11:19.680 --> 13:11:20.520
He fears time.

13:11:20.600 --> 13:11:21.260
He fears want.

13:11:21.800 --> 13:11:23.260
For if not, why hurry so?

13:11:23.780 --> 13:11:26.280
His very tone betray him, or my ears deceive.

13:11:26.780 --> 13:11:27.680
Why take that money?

13:11:28.000 --> 13:11:28.800
You follow quick.

13:11:29.080 --> 13:11:31.480
You are hunters of the wild beast, and understand it so.

13:11:31.840 --> 13:11:35.880
For me I make sure that nothing here may be of use to him, if so that he returns.

13:11:36.780 --> 13:11:41.680
As he spoke he put the money remaining in his pocket, took the title deeds in the bundle

13:11:41.680 --> 13:11:46.000
as Harker had left them, and swept the remaining things into the open fireplace where he set

13:11:46.000 --> 13:11:47.220
fire to them with a match.

13:11:48.060 --> 13:11:53.680
Godemling and Morris rushed out into the yard, and Harker lowered himself from the window

13:11:53.680 --> 13:11:55.020
to follow the count.

13:11:55.560 --> 13:12:00.280
He had, however, bolted the stable door, and by the time they had forced it open there

13:12:00.280 --> 13:12:01.380
was no sign of him.

13:12:01.820 --> 13:12:05.920
Van Helsing and I tried to make inquiry at the back of the house, but the muse was deserted

13:12:05.920 --> 13:12:07.300
and no one had seen him depart.

13:12:08.020 --> 13:12:11.200
It was now late in the afternoon, and sunset was not far off.

13:12:11.600 --> 13:12:13.640
We had to recognize that our game was up.

13:12:13.640 --> 13:12:16.660
With heavy hearts we agreed with the professor when he said,

13:12:17.020 --> 13:12:18.780
Let us go back now to Madame Mina.

13:12:19.140 --> 13:12:20.960
Poor, poor dear Madame Mina.

13:12:21.460 --> 13:12:26.160
All we can do just now is done, and we can there at least protect her.

13:12:26.720 --> 13:12:27.900
But we need not despair.

13:12:28.320 --> 13:12:31.420
There is but one more earth box, and we must try to find it.

13:12:31.760 --> 13:12:33.820
When that is done all may yet be well.

13:12:34.280 --> 13:12:37.720
I could see that he spoke as bravely as he could to comfort Harker.

13:12:38.140 --> 13:12:39.880
The poor fellow was quite broken down.

13:12:40.080 --> 13:12:43.000
Now and again he gave a low groan which he could not suppress.

13:12:43.000 --> 13:12:44.720
He was thinking of his wife.

13:12:45.460 --> 13:12:48.860
With sad hearts we came back to my house where we found Mrs. Harker waiting us,

13:12:49.140 --> 13:12:53.600
with an appearance of cheerfulness which did honor to her bravery and unselfishness.

13:12:53.880 --> 13:12:56.540
When she saw our faces her own became as pale as death.

13:12:57.020 --> 13:13:00.320
For a second or two her eyes were closed as if she were in secret prayer,

13:13:00.660 --> 13:13:01.980
and then she said cheerfully,

13:13:02.260 --> 13:13:05.260
I can never thank you all enough, oh my poor darling.

13:13:05.680 --> 13:13:09.060
As she spoke she took her husband's gray head in her hands and kissed it.

13:13:09.060 --> 13:13:11.300
May your poor head hear and rest it.

13:13:11.600 --> 13:13:12.640
All will be well, dear.

13:13:12.960 --> 13:13:15.640
God will protect us if he so will it in his good intent.

13:13:16.240 --> 13:13:17.460
The poor fellow groaned.

13:13:17.600 --> 13:13:19.800
There was no place for words in his sublime misery.

13:13:20.540 --> 13:13:22.840
We had a sort of perfunctory supper together,

13:13:23.000 --> 13:13:25.000
and I think it cheered us all up somewhat.

13:13:25.580 --> 13:13:28.960
It was perhaps the mere animal heat of food to hungry people,

13:13:29.380 --> 13:13:31.980
for none of us had eaten anything since before breakfast,

13:13:32.580 --> 13:13:34.840
or the sense of companionship may have helped us.

13:13:35.100 --> 13:13:36.780
But anyhow we were all less miserable,

13:13:36.780 --> 13:13:39.480
and we saw the morrow was not altogether without hope.

13:13:40.280 --> 13:13:43.340
True to our promise we told Mrs. Harker everything which had passed,

13:13:43.840 --> 13:13:45.780
and although she grew snowy white at times

13:13:45.780 --> 13:13:47.780
when danger had seemed to threaten her husband,

13:13:48.300 --> 13:13:50.980
and read at others when his devotion to her was manifested,

13:13:51.460 --> 13:13:53.280
she listened bravely and without comment.

13:13:54.300 --> 13:13:57.580
When we came to the part where Harker had rushed at the council recklessly,

13:13:58.440 --> 13:14:00.800
she clung to her husband's arm and held it tight

13:14:00.800 --> 13:14:03.780
as though her clinging could protect him from any harm that might come.

13:14:04.160 --> 13:14:07.040
She said nothing, however, till the narration was all done,

13:14:07.400 --> 13:14:09.520
and matters had been brought up to the present time.

13:14:10.300 --> 13:14:12.420
Then, without letting go her husband's hand,

13:14:12.460 --> 13:14:14.200
she stood up amongst us and spoke.

13:14:14.640 --> 13:14:16.980
Oh, that I could give any idea of the scene,

13:14:17.300 --> 13:14:19.880
of that sweet, sweet, good, good woman

13:14:19.880 --> 13:14:22.440
and all the radiant beauty of her youth and animation,

13:14:22.860 --> 13:14:25.620
with the red scar on her forehead, of which she was conscious,

13:14:26.140 --> 13:14:28.300
and which we saw with grinding of our teeth,

13:14:28.520 --> 13:14:30.040
remembering whence and how it came,

13:14:30.440 --> 13:14:32.520
her loving kindness against our grim hate,

13:14:32.520 --> 13:14:35.980
her tender faith against all our fears and doubting,

13:14:36.240 --> 13:14:39.480
and we, knowing that so far as symbols went,

13:14:39.860 --> 13:14:42.100
she, with all her goodness and purity and faith,

13:14:42.220 --> 13:14:43.580
was outcast from God.

13:14:44.360 --> 13:14:47.500
Jonathan, she said, and the word sounded like music on her lips,

13:14:47.620 --> 13:14:49.080
it was so full of love and tenderness.

13:14:49.880 --> 13:14:52.680
Jonathan dear, and you all my true, true friends,

13:14:53.100 --> 13:14:56.080
I want you to bear something in mind through all this dreadful time.

13:14:56.360 --> 13:14:59.100
I know that you must fight, that you must destroy,

13:14:59.180 --> 13:15:00.960
even as you destroyed the false Lucy,

13:15:00.960 --> 13:15:03.160
so that the true Lucy might live hereafter,

13:15:03.600 --> 13:15:05.140
but it is not a work of hate.

13:15:05.520 --> 13:15:07.800
That poor soul who has wrought all this misery

13:15:07.800 --> 13:15:09.340
is the saddest case of all.

13:15:09.780 --> 13:15:13.200
Just think what will be his joy when he too is destroyed

13:15:13.200 --> 13:15:15.400
in his worser part, that his better part

13:15:15.400 --> 13:15:17.000
may have spiritual immortality.

13:15:17.540 --> 13:15:19.420
You must be pitiful to him too,

13:15:19.760 --> 13:15:22.000
though it may not hold your hands from his destruction.

13:15:22.740 --> 13:15:25.460
As she spoke, I could see her husband's face darken

13:15:25.460 --> 13:15:27.740
and draw together, as though the passion in him

13:15:27.740 --> 13:15:30.320
were shriveling his being to its core,

13:15:30.940 --> 13:15:33.360
instinctively the clasp on his wife's hand grew closer,

13:15:33.480 --> 13:15:34.580
till his knuckles looked white.

13:15:35.040 --> 13:15:36.460
She did not flinch from the pain

13:15:36.460 --> 13:15:37.740
which I knew she must have suffered,

13:15:38.080 --> 13:15:40.680
but looked at him with eyes that were more appealing than ever.

13:15:41.660 --> 13:15:43.620
As she stopped speaking, he leapt to his feet,

13:15:43.700 --> 13:15:45.660
almost tearing his hand from hers as he spoke.

13:15:46.120 --> 13:15:48.620
May God give him into my hand just for long enough

13:15:48.620 --> 13:15:51.820
to destroy that earthly life of him which we are aiming at.

13:15:52.140 --> 13:15:54.080
If beyond it I could send his soul forever

13:15:54.080 --> 13:15:56.040
and never to burning hell, I would do it.

13:15:56.420 --> 13:15:59.520
Oh hush, oh hush in the name of good God.

13:15:59.520 --> 13:16:02.060
Don't say such things, Jonathan, my husband,

13:16:02.080 --> 13:16:04.020
or you will crush me with fear and horror.

13:16:04.480 --> 13:16:08.480
Just think, my dear, I have been thinking all this long, long day of it,

13:16:09.620 --> 13:16:13.520
that perhaps some day I too may need such pity,

13:16:13.920 --> 13:16:15.560
and that some other like you,

13:16:15.560 --> 13:16:18.060
and with equal cause for anger, may deny it me.

13:16:18.540 --> 13:16:20.720
Oh my husband, my husband indeed,

13:16:20.880 --> 13:16:24.160
I would pray have spared you such a thought had there been another way,

13:16:24.400 --> 13:16:27.500
but I pray that God may not have treasured your wild words

13:16:27.500 --> 13:16:31.180
except as the heartbroken wail of a very loving and sorely stricken man.

13:16:31.820 --> 13:16:35.680
Oh God, let these poor white hairs go in evidence of what he has suffered,

13:16:36.060 --> 13:16:39.720
who all his life has done no wrong and on whom so many sorrows have come.

13:16:40.660 --> 13:16:44.740
We men all were in tears now, there was no resisting them, and we wept openly.

13:16:45.280 --> 13:16:48.340
She wept too, to see that her sweeter counsels had prevailed.

13:16:48.820 --> 13:16:51.360
Her husband flung himself on his knees beside her,

13:16:51.580 --> 13:16:54.480
and putting his arms round her hid his face in the folds of her dress.

13:16:55.120 --> 13:16:57.480
Van Helsing beckoned to us, and we stole out of the room.

13:16:57.500 --> 13:16:59.800
Leaving the two loving hearts alone with their God.

13:17:00.820 --> 13:17:04.840
Before they retired, the professor fixed up the room against any coming of the vampire,

13:17:04.960 --> 13:17:07.680
and assured Mrs. Harker that she might rest in peace.

13:17:08.260 --> 13:17:10.160
She tried to school herself to the belief,

13:17:10.200 --> 13:17:13.100
and manifestly for her husband's sake tried to seem content.

13:17:13.800 --> 13:17:18.180
It was a brave struggle, and was, I think and believe, not without its reward.

13:17:18.760 --> 13:17:20.580
Van Helsing had placed at hand a bell,

13:17:20.640 --> 13:17:23.200
which either of them was to sound in case of any emergency.

13:17:23.560 --> 13:17:28.120
When they had retired, Quincy, Gautamling, and I arranged that we should sit up,

13:17:28.260 --> 13:17:31.940
dividing the night between us, and watch over the safety of the poor stricken lady.

13:17:32.520 --> 13:17:37.220
The first watch falls to Quincy, so the rest of us shall be off to bed as soon as we can.

13:17:37.800 --> 13:17:40.620
Gautamling has already turned in, for his is the second watch.

13:17:41.300 --> 13:17:44.200
Now that my work is done, I too shall go to bed.

13:17:45.260 --> 13:17:48.880
Jonathan Harker's Journal 3-4 October, close to midnight.

13:17:49.380 --> 13:17:51.000
I thought yesterday would never end.

13:17:51.000 --> 13:17:54.960
There was over me a yearning for sleep, and some sort of blind belief

13:17:54.960 --> 13:17:57.080
that to wake would be to find things changed,

13:17:57.360 --> 13:17:59.120
that any change must now be for the better.

13:17:59.740 --> 13:18:02.800
Before we parted, we discussed what our next step was to be,

13:18:03.100 --> 13:18:04.600
but we could arrive at no result.

13:18:05.060 --> 13:18:07.680
All we knew was that there was one earth box remaining,

13:18:08.160 --> 13:18:10.280
and that the Count alone knew where it was.

13:18:10.860 --> 13:18:13.720
If he chooses to lie hidden, he may baffle us for years.

13:18:14.360 --> 13:18:18.560
And in the meantime, the thought is too horrible, I dare not think of it even now.

13:18:19.120 --> 13:18:23.080
This I know, that if ever there was a woman who was all perfection,

13:18:23.720 --> 13:18:25.540
that one is my poor wronged darling.

13:18:26.320 --> 13:18:29.600
I loved her a thousand times more for her sweet pity of last night,

13:18:29.780 --> 13:18:32.420
a pity that made my own hate of the monster seem despicable.

13:18:33.100 --> 13:18:37.020
Surely God will not permit the world to be the poorer by the loss of such a creature.

13:18:37.740 --> 13:18:39.000
This is a hope to me.

13:18:39.500 --> 13:18:43.000
We are all drifting reefwards now, and faith is our only anchor.

13:18:43.580 --> 13:18:44.400
Thank God!

13:18:44.680 --> 13:18:46.760
Mina is sleeping, and sleeping without dreams.

13:18:46.760 --> 13:18:51.340
I fear what her dreams must be like, with such terrible memories to ground them in.

13:18:51.740 --> 13:18:54.880
She has not been so calm within my seeing since the sunset.

13:18:55.540 --> 13:18:59.080
Then, for a while, there came over her face a repose which was like

13:18:59.080 --> 13:19:00.760
the spring after the blasts of March.

13:19:01.340 --> 13:19:04.880
I thought at the time that it was the softness of the red sunset on her face,

13:19:05.240 --> 13:19:07.640
but somehow now I think it has a deeper meaning.

13:19:08.400 --> 13:19:12.320
I am not sleepy myself, though I am weary, weary to death.

13:19:13.000 --> 13:19:16.240
However, I must try to sleep, for there is tomorrow to think of,

13:19:16.240 --> 13:19:19.480
and there is no rest for me until later.

13:19:19.980 --> 13:19:22.840
I must have fallen asleep, for I was awakened by Mina,

13:19:23.160 --> 13:19:25.680
who was sitting up in bed with a startled look on her face.

13:19:26.100 --> 13:19:28.680
I could see easily, for we did not leave the room in darkness.

13:19:29.200 --> 13:19:32.840
She had placed a warning hand over my mouth, and now she whispered in my ear,

13:19:33.180 --> 13:19:34.880
Hush, there is someone in the corridor.

13:19:35.580 --> 13:19:38.580
I got up softly, and crossing the room gently opened the door.

13:19:39.140 --> 13:19:42.440
Just outside, stretched on a mattress, lay Mr. Morris wide awake.

13:19:42.800 --> 13:19:45.420
He raised a warning hand for silence as he whispered to me,

13:19:45.420 --> 13:19:46.880
Hush, go back to bed.

13:19:47.300 --> 13:19:48.140
All is all right.

13:19:48.200 --> 13:19:49.500
One of us will be here all night.

13:19:49.960 --> 13:19:51.420
We don't mean to take any chances.

13:19:52.160 --> 13:19:55.300
His look and gesture forbade discussion, so I came back and told Mina.

13:19:55.840 --> 13:20:00.540
She sighed and positively, a shadow of a smile stole over her poor pale face,

13:20:00.760 --> 13:20:02.860
and she put her arms round me and said softly,

13:20:03.360 --> 13:20:05.260
Oh, thank God for good brave men.

13:20:05.920 --> 13:20:08.320
With a sigh she sank back again into sleep.

13:20:08.880 --> 13:20:12.100
I write this now, as I am not sleepy, though I must try again.

13:20:12.820 --> 13:20:14.380
4 October Morning

13:20:14.900 --> 13:20:17.660
Once again during the night I was wakened by Mina.

13:20:18.180 --> 13:20:19.960
This time we had all had a good sleep,

13:20:20.060 --> 13:20:23.420
for the gray of the coming dawn was making the windows into sharp oblongs,

13:20:23.460 --> 13:20:26.340
and the gas flame was like a speck rather than a disk of light.

13:20:26.740 --> 13:20:27.900
She said to me hurriedly,

13:20:27.900 --> 13:20:30.120
Go, call the professor, I want to see him at once.

13:20:30.460 --> 13:20:31.280
Why, I asked.

13:20:31.540 --> 13:20:32.400
I have an idea.

13:20:32.720 --> 13:20:35.860
I suppose it must have come in the night, and matured without my knowing it.

13:20:36.080 --> 13:20:39.420
He must hypnotize me before the dawn, and then I shall be able to speak.

13:20:39.820 --> 13:20:41.900
Go quick, dearest, the time is getting close.

13:20:41.900 --> 13:20:43.240
I went to the door.

13:20:43.420 --> 13:20:46.700
Dr. Seward was resting on the mattress, and seeing me he sprang to his feet.

13:20:46.920 --> 13:20:47.800
Is anything wrong?

13:20:47.860 --> 13:20:48.620
He asked an alarm.

13:20:49.280 --> 13:20:52.160
No, I replied, but Mina wants to see Dr. Van Helsing at once.

13:20:52.620 --> 13:20:55.380
I will go, he said, and hurried into the professor's room.

13:20:55.980 --> 13:20:59.040
Two or three minutes later Van Helsing was in the room in his dressing gown,

13:20:59.140 --> 13:21:03.380
and Mr. Morris and Lord Gadamling were there with Dr. Seward at the door asking questions.

13:21:03.780 --> 13:21:06.700
When the professor saw Mina, a smile, a positive smile,

13:21:06.880 --> 13:21:08.440
ousted the anxiety off his face.

13:21:09.060 --> 13:21:10.720
He rubbed his hands as he said,

13:21:10.720 --> 13:21:13.720
Oh, my dear Madam Mina, this is indeed a change.

13:21:14.200 --> 13:21:18.760
See, friend Jonathan, we have got our dear Madam Mina as old back to us today.

13:21:19.360 --> 13:21:21.220
Then turning to her, he said cheerfully,

13:21:21.500 --> 13:21:23.080
And what am I to do for you?

13:21:23.400 --> 13:21:25.340
For at this hour you do not want me for nothing.

13:21:26.080 --> 13:21:27.980
I want you to hypnotize me, she said.

13:21:28.400 --> 13:21:32.280
Do it before the dawn, for I feel that that is when I can speak, and speak freely.

13:21:33.000 --> 13:21:34.560
Be quick, for time is short.

13:21:34.900 --> 13:21:37.160
Without a word he motioned for her to sit up in bed.

13:21:37.780 --> 13:21:41.320
Looking fixedly at her, he commenced to make passes in front of her,

13:21:41.360 --> 13:21:44.600
from over the top of her head downward, with each hand in turn.

13:21:45.440 --> 13:21:47.480
Mina gazed at him fixedly for a few minutes,

13:21:47.640 --> 13:21:49.760
during which my own heart beat like a trip hammer,

13:21:50.160 --> 13:21:52.000
for I felt that some crisis was at hand.

13:21:52.500 --> 13:21:55.200
Gradually her eyes closed, and she sat, stock still.

13:21:55.780 --> 13:21:59.180
Only by the gentle heaving of her bosom could one know that she was alive.

13:21:59.580 --> 13:22:02.000
The professor made a few more passes and then stopped,

13:22:02.240 --> 13:22:05.740
and I could see that his forehead was covered with great beads of perspiration.

13:22:06.360 --> 13:22:09.240
Mina opened her eyes, but she did not seem the same woman.

13:22:09.640 --> 13:22:11.280
There was a faraway look in her eyes,

13:22:11.280 --> 13:22:13.920
and her voice had a sad dreaminess which was new to me.

13:22:14.440 --> 13:22:18.580
Raising his hand to impose silence, the professor motioned to me to bring the others in.

13:22:18.980 --> 13:22:21.540
They came on tiptoe, closing the door behind them,

13:22:21.580 --> 13:22:23.440
and stood at the foot of the bed looking on.

13:22:23.940 --> 13:22:25.280
Mina appeared not to see them.

13:22:25.700 --> 13:22:29.500
This stillness was broken by Vran Helsing's voice speaking in a low level tone,

13:22:29.620 --> 13:22:31.340
which would not break the current of her thoughts.

13:22:31.900 --> 13:22:33.020
Where are you?

13:22:33.200 --> 13:22:34.780
The answer came in a neutral way.

13:22:34.780 --> 13:22:35.980
I do not know.

13:22:36.400 --> 13:22:38.440
Sleep has no place, I can call its own.

13:22:39.300 --> 13:22:40.900
For several minutes there was silence.

13:22:41.200 --> 13:22:44.140
Mina sat rigid, and the professor stood staring at her fixedly.

13:22:44.660 --> 13:22:46.260
The rest of us hardly dared to breathe.

13:22:46.600 --> 13:22:47.760
The room was growing lighter.

13:22:48.400 --> 13:22:50.220
Without taking his eyes from Mina's face,

13:22:50.400 --> 13:22:52.460
Dr. Vran Helsing motioned to me to pull up the blind.

13:22:52.900 --> 13:22:55.200
I did so, and the day seemed just upon us.

13:22:55.480 --> 13:22:59.100
A red streak shot up, and a rosy light seemed to diffuse itself through the room.

13:22:59.500 --> 13:23:01.660
On the instant the professor spoke again.

13:23:01.960 --> 13:23:02.980
Where are you now?

13:23:02.980 --> 13:23:05.440
The answer came dreamily, but with intention.

13:23:06.080 --> 13:23:08.140
There were as though she were interpreting something.

13:23:08.560 --> 13:23:11.420
I have heard her use the same tone when reading her short hints notes.

13:23:12.580 --> 13:23:13.300
I do not know.

13:23:13.440 --> 13:23:14.700
It is all strange to me.

13:23:15.200 --> 13:23:15.960
What do you see?

13:23:16.400 --> 13:23:17.200
I can see nothing.

13:23:17.580 --> 13:23:18.400
It is all dark.

13:23:19.060 --> 13:23:19.740
What do you hear?

13:23:20.260 --> 13:23:22.640
I could detect the strain in the professor's patient voice.

13:23:23.460 --> 13:23:24.440
The lapping of water.

13:23:24.760 --> 13:23:26.900
It is gurgling by, and little waves leap.

13:23:27.280 --> 13:23:28.840
I can hear them on the outside.

13:23:29.480 --> 13:23:30.520
Then you are on a ship.

13:23:31.200 --> 13:23:35.820
We all looked at each other, trying to glean something each from the other.

13:23:36.180 --> 13:23:37.320
We were afraid to think.

13:23:38.340 --> 13:23:39.620
The answer came quick.

13:23:39.760 --> 13:23:40.320
Oh, yes.

13:23:40.840 --> 13:23:41.820
What else do you hear?

13:23:42.400 --> 13:23:45.360
The sound of men stamping overhead as they run about.

13:23:45.840 --> 13:23:48.560
There is the creaking of a chain, and the loud tinkle as

13:23:48.560 --> 13:23:50.900
the check of the cap scan falls into the ratchet.

13:23:51.600 --> 13:23:52.500
What are you doing?

13:23:53.340 --> 13:23:54.760
I am still low still.

13:23:54.940 --> 13:23:55.760
It is like death.

13:23:56.440 --> 13:24:00.060
The voice faded away into the deep breath as of one sleeping,

13:24:00.060 --> 13:24:01.800
and the open eyes closed again.

13:24:02.260 --> 13:24:05.720
By this time the sun had risen, and we were all in the full light of day.

13:24:06.200 --> 13:24:08.660
Dr. Van Helsing placed his hands on Mina's shoulders,

13:24:08.740 --> 13:24:10.660
and laid her head down softly on her pillow.

13:24:11.300 --> 13:24:13.420
She lay like a sleeping child for a few moments,

13:24:13.580 --> 13:24:18.160
and then, with a long sigh, awoke and stared in wonder to see us all around her.

13:24:18.480 --> 13:24:21.240
Have I been talking in my sleep, was all she said.

13:24:21.780 --> 13:24:24.440
She seemed, however, to know the situation without telling,

13:24:24.980 --> 13:24:26.820
though she was eager to know what she had told.

13:24:27.320 --> 13:24:29.820
The professor repeated the conversation, and she said,

13:24:30.060 --> 13:24:31.580
Then there is not a moment to lose.

13:24:31.820 --> 13:24:33.900
It may not yet be too late.

13:24:34.800 --> 13:24:37.220
Mr. Morris and Lord Gottemling started for the door,

13:24:37.300 --> 13:24:39.300
but the professor's calm voice called them back.

13:24:39.820 --> 13:24:40.660
Stay, my friends.

13:24:40.820 --> 13:24:43.860
That ship, wherever it is, was weighing anchor at the moment

13:24:43.860 --> 13:24:45.920
in your so great port of London.

13:24:46.640 --> 13:24:48.680
Which of them is it that you seek?

13:24:49.300 --> 13:24:52.380
God be thanked that we once again have a clue,

13:24:52.840 --> 13:24:56.020
though somewhat wither that may lead us to know not.

13:24:56.740 --> 13:24:59.740
We have been blind somewhat, blind after the matter of men.

13:25:00.060 --> 13:25:03.380
Since we can look back and see what we might have seen looking forward,

13:25:03.460 --> 13:25:06.540
if we had been able to see what we might have seen.

13:25:07.340 --> 13:25:09.860
Alas, that sentence is a puzzle, is it not?

13:25:10.480 --> 13:25:14.100
We cannot know what was in the Count's mind when he seized that money,

13:25:14.420 --> 13:25:19.100
though Jonathan's so fierce knife put him in danger that even he dread.

13:25:19.640 --> 13:25:20.400
He meant escape.

13:25:20.900 --> 13:25:22.100
Hear me, escape.

13:25:22.720 --> 13:25:25.540
He saw that, but with one earth-box left,

13:25:25.600 --> 13:25:28.100
and a pack of men following like dogs after a fox,

13:25:28.100 --> 13:25:30.220
this London was no place for him.

13:25:30.500 --> 13:25:34.700
He have take his last earth-box on board a ship, and he leave the land.

13:25:35.160 --> 13:25:36.800
He think to escape, but no.

13:25:37.080 --> 13:25:38.000
We follow him.

13:25:38.100 --> 13:25:42.500
Tally-ho, as friend Arthur would say when he put on his red frock,

13:25:42.820 --> 13:25:44.400
to our old foxes wily.

13:25:45.080 --> 13:25:47.700
Oh, so wily, and we must follow with wile.

13:25:48.160 --> 13:25:51.960
I too am wily, and I think his mind in a little while.

13:25:52.700 --> 13:25:57.360
In mean time we may rest in peace, for there are between us

13:25:57.360 --> 13:26:00.740
which he do not want to pass, and which he could not if he would,

13:26:01.220 --> 13:26:05.440
unless the ship were to touch the land, and then only at full or slack tide.

13:26:06.140 --> 13:26:10.040
See, and the sun is just rose, and all day to sunset it is.

13:26:10.720 --> 13:26:13.920
Let us take bath and dress and breakfast which we all need,

13:26:14.220 --> 13:26:17.900
and which we can eat comfortably since he has not been in the same land with us.

13:26:19.020 --> 13:26:21.400
Mina looked at him appealingly as she said,

13:26:22.500 --> 13:26:25.760
but why need we seek him further when he is gone from us?

13:26:25.760 --> 13:26:28.700
He took her hand and patted it as he replied,

13:26:29.240 --> 13:26:30.440
Ask me nothing yet.

13:26:30.820 --> 13:26:34.140
When we have had breakfast, then I answer all questions.

13:26:34.720 --> 13:26:36.920
He would say no more, and we separated to dress.

13:26:37.720 --> 13:26:39.860
After breakfast, Mina repeated her question.

13:26:40.440 --> 13:26:43.200
He looked at her gravely for a minute, and then said sorrowfully,

13:26:43.860 --> 13:26:48.460
Because, my dear, dear Madame Mina, now more than ever we must find him,

13:26:48.500 --> 13:26:50.840
even if we have to follow him to the jaws of hell.

13:26:51.700 --> 13:26:54.640
She grew paler as she said faintly,

13:26:54.640 --> 13:26:57.700
Why? Because, he answered solemnly,

13:26:58.020 --> 13:27:01.100
He can live for centuries, and you are but a mortal woman.

13:27:01.660 --> 13:27:05.420
Time is now to be dreaded, since once he put that mark upon your throat.

13:27:06.160 --> 13:27:09.220
I was just in time to catch her as she fell forward in a faint.

13:27:40.260 --> 13:27:45.880
Dr. Seward's Phonograph Diary. Spoken by Van Helsing.

13:27:46.680 --> 13:27:48.700
This to Jonathan Harker.

13:27:49.400 --> 13:27:55.580
You are to stay with your dear Madame Mina. We shall go to make our search, if I can call

13:27:55.580 --> 13:28:02.800
it so, for it is not search but knowing, and we seek confirmation only. But do you stay

13:28:02.800 --> 13:28:09.260
and take care of her to-day? This is your best and most holiest office. This day nothing

13:28:09.260 --> 13:28:16.320
can find him here. Let me tell you so that you will know what we four know already, for

13:28:16.320 --> 13:28:22.760
I have tell them. He, our enemy, have gone away. He have gone back to his castle in Transylvania.

13:28:23.300 --> 13:28:30.300
I know it so well as if a great hand of fire wrote it on the wall. He have prepare for

13:28:30.300 --> 13:28:39.060
this in some way, and that last earth box was ready to ship somewheres. For this he

13:28:39.060 --> 13:28:46.060
must hurry at the last, lest we catch him before the sun go down. It was his last hope,

13:28:46.600 --> 13:28:51.740
save that he might hide in the tomb, that he think poor Miss Lucy, being as he thought

13:28:51.740 --> 13:28:58.780
like him, keep open to him. But there was not of time. When that fail he makes straight

13:28:58.780 --> 13:29:04.800
for his last resource, his last earth work, I might say, did I wish double entente. He

13:29:04.800 --> 13:29:11.380
is clever, oh so clever. He know that his game here was finish, and so he decide he

13:29:11.380 --> 13:29:19.060
go back home. He find ship going by the route he came, and he go in it. We go off now to

13:29:19.060 --> 13:29:25.060
find what ship and whither bound. When we have discover that, we come back and tell

13:29:25.060 --> 13:29:31.800
you all. Then we will comfort you and poor Madam Mina with new hope. For it will be hope

13:29:31.800 --> 13:29:38.460
when you think it over that all is not lost. This very creature that we pursue, he take

13:29:38.460 --> 13:29:44.880
hundreds of years to get so far as London, and yet in one day, when we know of the disposal

13:29:44.880 --> 13:29:51.560
of him, we drive him out. He is finite, though he is powerful to do much harm, and suffers

13:29:51.560 --> 13:29:58.860
not as we do. But we are strong, each in our purpose, and we are all more strong together.

13:29:59.620 --> 13:30:07.060
Take heart afresh, dear husband of Madam Mina. This battle is but begun, and in the end we

13:30:07.060 --> 13:30:14.960
shall win. So sure as that God sits on high to watch over his children. Therefore be of

13:30:14.960 --> 13:30:17.160
much comfort till we return.

13:30:19.240 --> 13:30:20.680
Van Helsing

13:30:21.700 --> 13:30:24.140
Jonathan Harker's Journal

13:30:24.900 --> 13:30:26.260
Fourth of October

13:30:27.720 --> 13:30:32.860
When I read to Mina Van Helsing's message in the phonograph, the poor girl brightened

13:30:32.860 --> 13:30:37.680
up considerably. Already the certainty that the Count is out of the country has given

13:30:37.680 --> 13:30:44.680
her comfort. And comfort is strength to her. For my own part, now that his horrible danger

13:30:44.680 --> 13:30:52.240
is not face to face with us, it seems almost impossible to believe in it. Even my own terrible

13:30:52.240 --> 13:30:57.980
experiences in Castle Dracula seem like a long-forgotten dream, here in the crisp autumn

13:30:57.980 --> 13:31:05.080
air in the bright sunlight. Alas, how can I disbelieve? In the midst of my thought my

13:31:05.080 --> 13:31:12.780
eye fell on the red scar on my poor darling's white forehead. Whilst that lasts there can

13:31:12.780 --> 13:31:20.060
be no disbelief. Mina and I fear to be idle, so we have been over all the diaries again

13:31:20.060 --> 13:31:26.920
and again. Somehow, although the realities seem greater each time, the pain and the fear

13:31:26.920 --> 13:31:32.920
seem less. There is something of a guiding purpose manifest throughout which is comforting.

13:31:34.540 --> 13:31:40.840
Mina says that perhaps we are the instruments of ultimate good. It may be. I shall try to

13:31:40.840 --> 13:31:46.820
think as she does. We have never spoken to each other yet of the future. It is better

13:31:46.820 --> 13:31:53.500
to wait till we see the Professor and the others, after their investigations. The day

13:31:53.500 --> 13:31:59.680
is running by more quickly than I ever thought a day could run for me again. It is now three

13:31:59.680 --> 13:32:00.300
o'clock.

13:32:03.680 --> 13:32:13.220
Mina Harker's Journal. 5th October. 5 p.m. Our meeting for report. Present. Professor

13:32:13.220 --> 13:32:21.880
Van Helsing. Lord Godalming. Dr. Seward. Mr. Quincy Morris. Jonathan Harker. Mina Harker.

13:32:23.320 --> 13:32:29.020
Van Helsing described what steps were taken during the day to discover on what boat and

13:32:29.020 --> 13:32:36.100
whither bound Count Dracula made his escape. As I knew that he wanted to get back to Transylvania,

13:32:36.740 --> 13:32:42.680
I felt sure that he must go by the Danube mouth, or by somewhere in the Black Sea, since

13:32:42.680 --> 13:32:52.160
by that way he come. It was a dreary blank that was before us. Omne ignotum pro magnifico,

13:32:52.300 --> 13:32:58.020
and so with heavy hearts we start to find what ships leave for the Black Sea last night.

13:32:59.180 --> 13:33:06.620
He was in sailing ship, since Madame Mina tell of sails being set. These not so important

13:33:06.620 --> 13:33:12.180
as to go in your list of the shipping in the times, and so we go, by suggestion of

13:33:12.180 --> 13:33:17.660
Lord Godalming, to your Lloyds, where are note of all ships that sail however so small.

13:33:18.800 --> 13:33:25.760
There we find that only one Black Sea bound ship go out with the tide. She is the Tsarina

13:33:25.760 --> 13:33:32.280
Catherine, and she sail from Doolittle's Wharf for Varna, and thence to other ports and up

13:33:32.280 --> 13:33:33.100
the Danube.

13:33:34.660 --> 13:33:42.080
So, said I, this is the ship whereon is the Count. So off we go to Doolittle's Wharf,

13:33:42.420 --> 13:33:48.520
and there we find a man in an office. From him we inquire of the goings of the Tsarina

13:33:48.520 --> 13:33:54.300
Catherine. He swear much, and he red face and loud of voice, but he good fellow all

13:33:54.300 --> 13:34:00.340
the same. And when Quincy give him something from his pocket which crackle as he roll it

13:34:00.340 --> 13:34:06.700
up, and put it in a so small bag which he have hid deep in his clothing, he still better

13:34:06.700 --> 13:34:12.180
fellow and humble servant to us. He come with us, and ask many men who are rough and hot.

13:34:13.160 --> 13:34:19.140
These be better fellows too, when they have been no more thirsty. They say much of blood

13:34:19.140 --> 13:34:25.860
and bloom, and of others which I comprehend not, though I guess what they mean. But nevertheless

13:34:26.160 --> 13:34:29.160
they tell us all things which we want to know.

13:34:30.500 --> 13:34:36.560
They make known to us among them how last afternoon at about five o'clock comes a man

13:34:36.560 --> 13:34:44.960
so hurry, a tall man, thin and pale, with high nose and teeth so white, and eyes that

13:34:44.960 --> 13:34:52.100
seem to be burning. That he be all in black, except that he have a hat of straw which suit

13:34:52.100 --> 13:34:59.100
not him or the time. That he scatter his money in making quick inquiry as to what ship sails

13:34:59.100 --> 13:35:05.680
for the Black Sea and for where. Some took him to the office and then to the ship, where

13:35:05.680 --> 13:35:11.040
he will not go aboard but halt at shore end of Gangplank, and ask that the captain come

13:35:11.040 --> 13:35:17.340
to him. The captain come when told that he will be pay well, and though he swear much,

13:35:17.740 --> 13:35:24.240
at the first he agree to term. Then the thin man go, and some one tell him where horse

13:35:24.240 --> 13:35:31.020
and cart can be hired. He go there, and soon he come again, himself driving cart on which

13:35:31.020 --> 13:35:39.060
a great box. This he himself lift down, though it takes several to put it on truck for the

13:35:39.060 --> 13:35:46.240
ship. He give much talk to captain as to how and where his box is to be place. But the

13:35:46.240 --> 13:35:51.760
captain like it not, and swear at him in many tongues, and tell him that if he like he can

13:35:51.760 --> 13:35:58.440
come and see where it shall be. But he say no, that he come not yet, for that he have

13:35:58.440 --> 13:36:04.540
much to do. Whereupon the captain tell him that he had better be quick, with blood, for

13:36:04.540 --> 13:36:11.060
that his ship will leave the place, of blood, before the turn of the tide, with blood. Then

13:36:11.060 --> 13:36:16.260
the thin man smile, and say that of course he must go when he think fit, but he will

13:36:16.260 --> 13:36:23.540
be surprised if he go quite so soon. The captain swear again, polyglot, and the thin man make

13:36:23.540 --> 13:36:29.120
him bow, and thank him, and say that he will so far intrude on his kindness as to come

13:36:29.120 --> 13:36:35.500
aboard before the sailing. Final the captain, more red than ever, and in more tongues, tell

13:36:35.500 --> 13:36:40.660
him that he doesn't want no Frenchmen, with bloom upon them, and also with blood, in his

13:36:40.660 --> 13:36:47.220
ship, with blood on her also. And so, after asking where he might purchase ship-forms,

13:36:47.340 --> 13:36:54.720
he departed. No one knew where he went, or bloomin' well cared, as they said, for they

13:36:54.720 --> 13:37:00.480
had something else to think of, well with blood again. For it soon became apparent to

13:37:00.480 --> 13:37:07.820
all that the Tsarina Catherine would not sail as was expected. A thin mist began to creep

13:37:07.820 --> 13:37:13.920
up from the river, and it grew, and grew, till soon a dense fog enveloped the ship,

13:37:14.140 --> 13:37:22.340
and all around her. The captain swore polyglot, very polyglot, polyglot with bloom and blood,

13:37:22.780 --> 13:37:28.980
but he could do nothing. The water rose and rose, and he began to fear that he would lose

13:37:28.980 --> 13:37:35.500
the tide altogether. He was in no friendly mood when, just at full tide, the thin man

13:37:35.500 --> 13:37:41.880
came up the gangplank again, and asked to see where his box had been stowed. Then the

13:37:41.880 --> 13:37:47.920
captain replied that he wished he and his box, old and with much bloom and blood, were

13:37:47.920 --> 13:37:54.540
in hell. But the thin man did not be offend, and went down with the mate, and saw where

13:37:54.540 --> 13:38:01.360
it was place, and came up, and stood awhile on deck in fog. He must have come off by himself,

13:38:01.360 --> 13:38:08.440
for none notice him. Indeed they thought not of him, for soon the fog began to melt away,

13:38:08.620 --> 13:38:15.160
and all was clear again. My friends of the thirst and the language that was of bloom

13:38:15.160 --> 13:38:22.340
and blood laughed, as they told how the captain's swears exceeded even his usual polyglot, and

13:38:22.340 --> 13:38:27.840
was more than ever full of picturesque, when on questioning other mariners who were on

13:38:27.840 --> 13:38:32.880
movement up and down the river that hour, he found that few of them had seen any of

13:38:32.880 --> 13:38:39.800
fog at all, except where it lay round the wharf. However, the ship went outs on the

13:38:39.800 --> 13:38:46.180
ebb tide, and was doubtless by morning far down the river mouth. She was then, when they

13:38:46.180 --> 13:38:54.300
told us, well out to sea. And so, my dear Madame Mina, it is that we have to rest for

13:38:54.300 --> 13:39:00.660
time, for our enemy is on the sea, with the fog at his command, on his way to the Danube

13:39:00.660 --> 13:39:08.180
mouth. To sail a ship takes time, goes she never so quick. And when we start to go on

13:39:08.180 --> 13:39:13.860
land more quick, and we meet him there, our best hope is to come on him when in the box

13:39:13.860 --> 13:39:19.400
between sunrise and sunset, for then he can make no struggle, and we may deal with him

13:39:19.400 --> 13:39:26.200
as we should. There are days for us in which we can make ready our plan. We know all about

13:39:26.200 --> 13:39:31.820
where he go, for we have seen the owner of the ship, who have shown us invoices and all

13:39:31.820 --> 13:39:38.580
papers that can be. The box we seek is to be landed in Varna, and to be given to an

13:39:38.580 --> 13:39:45.100
agent, one Ristics, who will there present his credentials. And so our merchant friend

13:39:45.100 --> 13:39:51.760
will have done his part. When he ask if there be any wrong, for that so he can telegraph

13:39:51.760 --> 13:39:58.100
and have inquiry made at Varna, we say no, for what is to be done is not for police or

13:39:58.100 --> 13:40:07.420
of the customs. It must be done by us alone, and in our own way. When Dr. Van Helsing had

13:40:07.420 --> 13:40:12.500
done speaking, I asked him if he were certain that the Count had remained on board the ship.

13:40:13.260 --> 13:40:20.360
He replied, We have the best proof of that, your own evidence, when in the hypnotic trance

13:40:20.360 --> 13:40:26.460
this morning. I asked him again if it were really necessary that they should pursue the

13:40:26.460 --> 13:40:32.660
Count, for, oh, I dread Jonathan leaving me, and I know that he would surely go if the

13:40:32.660 --> 13:40:39.620
others went. He answered in growing passion, at first quietly. As he went on, however,

13:40:39.620 --> 13:40:45.620
he grew more angry and more forceful, till in the end we could not but see wherein was

13:40:45.620 --> 13:40:51.260
at least some of that personal dominance which made him so long a master amongst men.

13:40:52.680 --> 13:40:59.680
Yes, it is necessary, necessary, necessary, for your sake in the first, and then for the

13:40:59.680 --> 13:41:05.560
sake of humanity. This monster has done much harm already, in the narrow scope where he

13:41:05.560 --> 13:41:10.520
had found himself, and in the short time when as yet he was only as a body groping

13:41:10.520 --> 13:41:17.840
his so small measure in darkness, and not knowing. All this have I told these others.

13:41:18.220 --> 13:41:24.160
You, my dear Madame Mina, will learn it in the phonograph of my friend John, or in that

13:41:24.160 --> 13:41:30.900
of your husband. I have told them how the measure of leaving his own barren land, barren

13:41:30.900 --> 13:41:36.400
of peoples, and coming to a new land where life of man teems till they are like the multitude

13:41:36.400 --> 13:41:43.820
of standing corn, was the work of centuries. Were another of the undead, like him, to try

13:41:43.820 --> 13:41:49.260
to do what he has done, perhaps not all the centuries of the world that have been or that

13:41:49.260 --> 13:41:56.460
will be could aid him. With this one all the forces of nature that are occult and deep

13:41:56.460 --> 13:42:03.740
and strong must have worked together in some wondrous way. The very place where he have

13:42:03.740 --> 13:42:10.200
been alive, undead for all these centuries, is full of strangeness of the geologic and

13:42:10.200 --> 13:42:17.260
chemical world. There are deep caverns and fissures that reach none know whither. There

13:42:17.260 --> 13:42:23.080
have been volcanoes, some of whose openings still send out waters of strange properties,

13:42:23.380 --> 13:42:31.080
and gases that kill or make to vivify. Doubtless there is something magnetic or electric in

13:42:31.080 --> 13:42:36.800
some of these combinations of occult forces which work for physical life in strange way,

13:42:37.300 --> 13:42:44.300
and in himself were from the first some great qualities. In a hard and warlike time he was

13:42:44.300 --> 13:42:50.720
celebrate that he have more iron nerve, more subtle brain, more braver heart than any man.

13:42:52.160 --> 13:42:59.300
In him some vital principle have in strange way found their utmost, and as his body keeps

13:42:59.300 --> 13:43:07.520
strong and grow and thrive, so his brain grow too. All this without that diabolic aid which

13:43:07.520 --> 13:43:13.160
is surely to him, for it have to yield to the powers that come from and are symbolic

13:43:13.160 --> 13:43:20.440
of good, and now this is what he is to us. He have infect you, oh forgive me, my dear,

13:43:20.440 --> 13:43:27.080
that I must say such, but it is for good of you that I speak. He infect you in such wise,

13:43:27.600 --> 13:43:33.300
that even if he do know more, you have only to live, to live in your own old sweet way,

13:43:33.580 --> 13:43:40.480
and so in time death, which is of man's common lot, and with God's sanction, shall make you

13:43:40.480 --> 13:43:48.880
like to him. This must not be. We have sworn together that it must not. Thus we are ministers

13:43:48.880 --> 13:43:55.820
of God's own wish, that the world, and men for whom his son die, will not be given over

13:43:55.820 --> 13:44:02.460
to monsters whose very existence would defame him. He have allowed us to redeem one soul

13:44:02.460 --> 13:44:08.660
already, and we go out as the old knights of the cross to redeem more. Like them we

13:44:08.660 --> 13:44:15.400
shall travel towards the sunrise, and like them, if we fall, we fall in good cause.

13:44:16.480 --> 13:44:23.940
He paused, and I said, But will not the count take his rib off wisely? Since he has been

13:44:23.940 --> 13:44:28.920
driven from England, will he not avoid it, as a tiger does the village from which he

13:44:28.920 --> 13:44:29.720
has been hunted?

13:44:31.060 --> 13:44:39.320
Aha, he said, your simile of the tiger good for me, and I shall adopt him. Your man-eater,

13:44:39.320 --> 13:44:45.640
as they of India call the tiger, who has once tasted blood of the human, care no more for

13:44:45.640 --> 13:44:52.160
the other prey, but prowl unceasing till he get him. This that we hunt from our village

13:44:52.160 --> 13:44:59.460
is a tiger too, a man-eater, and he never cease to prowl. Nay, in himself he is not

13:44:59.460 --> 13:45:05.640
one to retire and stay afar. In his life, his living life, he go over the turkey frontier,

13:45:05.640 --> 13:45:13.260
and attack his enemy on his own ground. He be beaten back, but did he stay? No. He come

13:45:13.260 --> 13:45:21.900
again and again and again. Look at his persistence and endurance. With the child brain that was

13:45:21.900 --> 13:45:28.100
to him, he have long since conceive the idea of coming to a great city. What does he do?

13:45:28.580 --> 13:45:34.820
He find out the place of all the world most of promise for him. Then he deliberately set

13:45:34.820 --> 13:45:40.500
himself down to prepare for the task. He find in patience just how is his strength,

13:45:40.760 --> 13:45:47.880
and what are his powers. He study new tongues. He learn new social life, new environment

13:45:47.880 --> 13:45:55.700
of old ways, the politics, the law, the finance, the science, the habit of a new land, and

13:45:55.700 --> 13:46:02.400
a new people who have come to be since he was. His glimpse that he have had, whet his

13:46:02.400 --> 13:46:09.560
appetite only, and in keen his desire, nay, it help him to grow as to his brain. For it

13:46:09.560 --> 13:46:15.640
all prove to him how right he was at the first in his surmises. He have done this alone,

13:46:16.080 --> 13:46:24.200
all alone, from a ruined tomb in a forgotten land. What more may he not do when the greater

13:46:24.200 --> 13:46:31.380
world of thought is open to him, he that can smile at death as we know him, who can flourish

13:46:31.380 --> 13:46:37.420
in the midst of diseases that kill off whole peoples. Oh, if such an one was to come from

13:46:37.420 --> 13:46:43.540
God and not the devil, what a force for good might he not be in this old world of ours.

13:46:44.380 --> 13:46:51.020
But we are pledged to set the world free. Our toil must be in silence and our efforts

13:46:51.020 --> 13:46:58.060
all in secret. For in this enlightened age, when men believe not even what they see, the

13:46:58.060 --> 13:47:03.080
quoting of wise men would be his greatest strength. It would be at once his sheath and

13:47:03.080 --> 13:47:08.640
his armour and his weapons to destroy us his enemies who are willing to peril even our

13:47:08.640 --> 13:47:14.920
own souls for the safety of one we love, for the good of mankind and for the honour and

13:47:14.920 --> 13:47:16.360
glory of God.

13:47:17.820 --> 13:47:22.900
After a general discussion it was determined that for to-night nothing be definitely settled,

13:47:22.900 --> 13:47:29.560
that we should all sleep on the facts and try to think out the proper conclusions. Tomorrow

13:47:29.560 --> 13:47:34.580
at breakfast we are to meet again, and after making our conclusions known to one another

13:47:34.580 --> 13:47:37.780
we shall decide on some definite cause of action.

13:47:39.200 --> 13:47:45.840
I feel a wonderful peace and rest to-night. It is as if some haunting presence were removed

13:47:45.840 --> 13:47:49.340
from me. Perhaps—

13:47:49.340 --> 13:47:55.600
My surmise was not finished, could not be, for I caught sight in the mirror of the red

13:47:55.600 --> 13:48:00.400
mark upon my forehead, and I knew that I was still unclean.

13:48:02.120 --> 13:48:05.800
Dr. Seward's Diary. 5 October.

13:48:07.440 --> 13:48:14.160
We all arose early, and I think that sleep did much for each and all of us. When we met

13:48:14.160 --> 13:48:18.940
at early breakfast there was more general cheerfulness than any of us had ever expected

13:48:18.940 --> 13:48:25.580
to experience again. It is really wonderful how much resilience there is in human nature.

13:48:26.280 --> 13:48:32.380
Let any obstructing cause, no matter what, be removed in any way, even by death, and

13:48:32.380 --> 13:48:36.040
we fly back to first principles of hope and enjoyment.

13:48:37.820 --> 13:48:43.400
More than once as we sat around the table my eyes opened in wonder whether the whole

13:48:43.400 --> 13:48:49.080
of the past days had not been a dream. It was only when I caught sight of the red blotch

13:48:49.080 --> 13:48:55.580
on Mrs. Harker's forehead that I was brought back to reality. Even now, when I am gravely

13:48:55.580 --> 13:49:01.300
revolving the matter, it is almost impossible to realize that the cause of all our trouble

13:49:01.300 --> 13:49:02.980
is still existent.

13:49:04.760 --> 13:49:10.860
Even Mrs. Harker seems to lose sight of her trouble for whole spells. It is only now and

13:49:10.860 --> 13:49:18.560
again, when something recalls it to her mind, that she thinks of her terrible scar. We are

13:49:18.560 --> 13:49:24.560
to meet here in my study in half an hour and decide on our course of action. I see only

13:49:24.560 --> 13:49:31.220
one immediate difficulty. I know it by instinct rather than reason. We shall all have to speak

13:49:31.220 --> 13:49:39.020
frankly, and yet I fear that in some mysterious way poor Mrs. Harker's tongue is tied. I know

13:49:39.020 --> 13:49:44.400
that she forms conclusions of her own, and from all that has been I can guess how brilliant

13:49:44.400 --> 13:49:51.980
and how true they must be, but she will not or cannot give them utterance. I have mentioned

13:49:51.980 --> 13:49:59.080
this to Van Helsing, and he and I are to talk it over when we are alone. I suppose it is

13:49:59.080 --> 13:50:04.560
some of that horrid poison which has got into her veins beginning to work. The Count had

13:50:04.560 --> 13:50:11.080
his own purposes when he gave her what Van Helsing called the vampire's baptism of blood.

13:50:12.000 --> 13:50:18.480
Well there may be a poison that distills itself out of good things. In an age when the existence

13:50:18.480 --> 13:50:24.940
of tomains is a mystery we should not wonder at anything. One thing I know that if my instinct

13:50:24.940 --> 13:50:31.580
be true regarding poor Mrs. Harker's silences, then there is a terrible difficulty and unknown

13:50:31.580 --> 13:50:38.800
danger in the work before us. The same power that compels her silence may compel her speech.

13:50:39.420 --> 13:50:44.260
I dare not think further, for so I showed in my thoughts dishonour a noble woman.

13:50:46.100 --> 13:50:52.560
Later. When the Professor came in we talked over the state of things. I could see that

13:50:52.560 --> 13:50:58.380
he had something on his mind which he wanted to say, but felt some hesitancy about broaching

13:50:58.380 --> 13:51:05.480
the subject. After beating about the bush a little he said, Friend John, there is something

13:51:05.480 --> 13:51:11.860
that you and I must talk of alone, just at the first, at any rate. Later we may have

13:51:11.860 --> 13:51:20.860
to take the others into our confidence. Then he stopped, so I waited. He went on, Madam

13:51:20.860 --> 13:51:25.740
Mina, our poor dear Madam Mina, is changing.

13:51:27.620 --> 13:51:35.020
A cold shiver ran through me to find my worst fears thus endorsed. Van Helsing continued.

13:51:36.300 --> 13:51:42.780
With the sad experience of Miss Lucy we must this time be warned before things go too far.

13:51:44.180 --> 13:51:49.900
Our task is now in reality more difficult than ever, and this new trouble makes every

13:51:49.900 --> 13:51:55.880
power of the direst importance. I can see the characteristics of the vampire coming

13:51:55.880 --> 13:52:03.540
in her face. It is now but very, very slight, but it is to be seen if we have eyes to notice

13:52:03.540 --> 13:52:11.140
without prejudge. Her teeth are sharper, and at times her eyes are more hard, but these

13:52:11.140 --> 13:52:18.020
are not all. There is to her the silence now often, as so it was with Miss Lucy. She did

13:52:18.020 --> 13:52:23.840
not speak, even when she wrote that which she wished to be known later. Now my fear

13:52:23.840 --> 13:52:31.660
is this. If it be that she can, by our hypnotic trance, tell what the Count see and hear,

13:52:32.540 --> 13:52:38.240
is it not more true that he who have hypnotized her first, and who have drink of her very

13:52:38.240 --> 13:52:44.940
blood and make her drink of his, should, if he will, compel her mind to disclose to him

13:52:44.940 --> 13:52:54.880
that which she know? I nodded acquiescence. He went on. Then what we must do is to prevent

13:52:54.880 --> 13:53:01.060
this. We must keep her ignorant of our intent, and so she cannot tell what she know not.

13:53:01.840 --> 13:53:07.700
This is a painful task. Oh, so painful that it heartbreak me to think of it, but it must

13:53:07.700 --> 13:53:14.300
be. When to-day we meet, I must tell her that for reason which we will not to speak, she

13:53:14.300 --> 13:53:21.940
must not more be of our counsel, but be simply guarded by us. He wiped his forehead, which

13:53:21.940 --> 13:53:26.780
had broken out in profuse perspiration at the thought of the pain which he might have

13:53:26.780 --> 13:53:34.680
to inflict upon the poor soul already so tortured. I knew that it would be some sort of comfort

13:53:34.680 --> 13:53:41.240
to him if I told him that I also had come to the same conclusion, for at any rate it

13:53:41.240 --> 13:53:48.520
would take away the pain of doubt. I told him, and the effect was as I expected. It

13:53:48.520 --> 13:53:54.420
is now close to the time of our general gathering. Van Helsing has gone away to prepare for the

13:53:54.420 --> 13:54:00.540
meeting and his painful part of it. I really believe his purpose is to be able to pray

13:54:00.540 --> 13:54:09.980
alone. Later. At the very outset of our meeting a great personal relief was experienced by

13:54:09.980 --> 13:54:16.860
both Van Helsing and myself. Mrs. Harker had sent a message by her husband to say that

13:54:16.860 --> 13:54:22.100
she would not join us at present, as she thought it better that we should be free to discuss

13:54:22.100 --> 13:54:28.800
our movements without her presence to embarrass us. The Professor and I looked at each other

13:54:28.800 --> 13:54:35.700
for an instant, and somehow we both seemed relieved. For my own part, I thought that

13:54:35.700 --> 13:54:42.500
if Mrs. Harker realized the danger herself, it was much pain as well as much danger averted.

13:54:43.420 --> 13:54:49.900
Under the circumstances we agreed, by a questioning look and answer, with finger on lip, to preserve

13:54:49.900 --> 13:54:56.700
silence in our suspicions until we should have been able to confer alone again. We went at

13:54:56.700 --> 13:55:04.520
once into our plan of campaign. Van Helsing roughly put the facts before us. The Tsarina

13:55:04.520 --> 13:55:09.900
Catherine left the Thames yesterday morning. It will take her at the quickest speed she

13:55:09.900 --> 13:55:16.560
has ever made, at least three weeks to reach Varna. But we can travel overland to the same

13:55:16.560 --> 13:55:23.740
place in three days. Now, if we allow for two days less for the ship's voyage, owing

13:55:23.740 --> 13:55:29.600
to such weather influences as we know that the count can bring to bear, and if we allow

13:55:29.600 --> 13:55:35.840
a whole day and night for any delays which may occur to us, then we have a margin of

13:55:35.840 --> 13:55:42.920
nearly two weeks. Thus, in order to be quite safe, we must leave here on seventeenth at

13:55:42.920 --> 13:55:50.180
latest. Then we shall at any rate be in Varna a day before the ship arrives, and able to

13:55:50.180 --> 13:55:57.060
make such preparations as may be necessary. Of course, we shall all go armed, armed against

13:55:57.060 --> 13:56:05.580
evil things, spiritual as well as physical. Here Quincey Morris added,—I understand

13:56:05.580 --> 13:56:10.320
that the count comes from a wolf country, and it may be that he shall get there before

13:56:10.320 --> 13:56:16.720
us. I propose that we add Winchesters to our armament. I have a kind of belief in a Winchester

13:56:16.720 --> 13:56:22.160
when there is any trouble of that sort around. Do you remember, Art, when we had the pack

13:56:22.160 --> 13:56:27.460
after us at Tobolsk? What wouldn't we have given then for a repeater apiece?

13:56:28.300 --> 13:56:34.860
Good, said Van Helsing. Winchesters it shall be. Quincey's head is level at times, but

13:56:34.860 --> 13:56:40.660
most so when there is to hunt. Metaphor be more dishonour to science than wolves be of

13:56:40.660 --> 13:56:47.900
danger to man. In the meantime we can do nothing here, and as I think that Varna is not familiar

13:56:47.900 --> 13:56:55.620
to any of us, why not go there more soon? It is as long to wait here as there. To-night

13:56:55.620 --> 13:57:02.020
and to-morrow we can get ready, and then if all be well, we four can set out on our journey.

13:57:03.500 --> 13:57:17.880
We four, said Harker, interrogatively, looking from one to another of us. Of course, answered

13:57:17.880 --> 13:57:25.700
Harker. Harker was silent for a while, and then said in a hollow voice, Let us talk of

13:57:25.700 --> 13:57:31.800
that part of it in the morning. I want to consult with Mina. I thought that now was

13:57:31.800 --> 13:57:37.260
the time for Van Helsing to warn him not to disclose our plan to her, but he took no notice.

13:57:37.980 --> 13:57:44.480
I looked at him significantly and coughed. For answer he put his finger to his lips and

13:57:44.480 --> 13:57:45.440
turned away.

13:57:47.660 --> 13:57:52.480
Jonathan Harker's Journal. 5th October. Afternoon.

13:57:53.860 --> 13:57:59.820
For some time after our meeting this morning I could not think. The new phases of things

13:57:59.820 --> 13:58:07.700
leave my mind in a state of wonder which allows no room for active thought. Mina's determination

13:58:07.700 --> 13:58:14.920
not to take any part in the discussions set me thinking. And as I could not argue the

13:58:14.920 --> 13:58:21.980
matter with her I could only guess. I am as far as ever from a solution now. The way the

13:58:21.980 --> 13:58:28.140
others received it, too, puzzled me. The last time we talked of the subject we agreed that

13:58:28.140 --> 13:58:35.240
there was to be no more concealment of anything amongst us. Mina is sleeping now, calmly and

13:58:35.240 --> 13:58:41.340
sweetly, like a little child. Her lips are curved, and her face beams with happiness.

13:58:42.240 --> 13:58:46.040
Thank God there are such moments still for her.

13:58:47.420 --> 13:58:48.080
Later.

13:58:49.140 --> 13:58:56.220
How strange it all is! I sat watching Mina's happy sleep, and I came as near to being happy

13:58:56.220 --> 13:59:03.400
myself as I suppose I shall ever be. As the evening drew on, and the earth took its shadows

13:59:03.400 --> 13:59:09.360
from the sun sinking lower, the silence of the room grew more and more solemn to me.

13:59:10.800 --> 13:59:15.420
All at once Mina opened her eyes, and, looking at me tenderly, said,

13:59:16.460 --> 13:59:22.360
Jonathan, I want you to promise me something on your word of honour. A promise made to

13:59:22.360 --> 13:59:27.380
me, but made holily, in God's hearing, and not to be broken, though I should go down

13:59:27.380 --> 13:59:32.740
my knees and implore you with bitter tears. Quick, you must make it to me at once.

13:59:34.240 --> 13:59:40.660
Mina, I said, a promise like that I cannot make at once. I may have no right to make

13:59:40.660 --> 13:59:41.060
it.

13:59:42.580 --> 13:59:49.680
But dear one, she said, with such spiritual intensity that her eyes were like pole-stars.

13:59:50.740 --> 13:59:57.360
It is I who wish it, and it is not for myself. You can ask Dr. Van Helsing if I am not right.

13:59:58.940 --> 14:00:06.200
If he disagrees, you may do as you will. Nay, more if you all agree, later you are absolved

14:00:06.200 --> 14:00:07.060
from the promise.

14:00:08.460 --> 14:00:15.360
I promise, I said, and for a moment she looked supremely happy, though to me all happiness

14:00:15.360 --> 14:00:20.580
for her was denied by the red scar on her forehead. She said,

14:00:21.560 --> 14:00:27.160
Promise me that you will not tell me anything of the plans formed for the campaign against

14:00:27.160 --> 14:00:35.860
the Count, not by word, or inference, or implication, not at any time, whilst this remains to me.

14:00:36.380 --> 14:00:42.500
And she solemnly pointed to the scar. I saw that she was in earnest, and said solemnly,

14:00:43.240 --> 14:00:51.120
I promise. And as I said it, I felt that from that instant a door had been shut between

14:00:51.120 --> 14:00:51.880
us.

14:00:53.400 --> 14:01:00.600
Later, midnight, Mina has been bright and cheerful all the evening, so much so that

14:01:00.600 --> 14:01:07.380
all the rest seemed to take courage, as if infected somewhat with her gaiety. As a result,

14:01:07.500 --> 14:01:13.100
even I myself felt as if the pall of gloom which weighs us down were somewhat lifted.

14:01:14.440 --> 14:01:22.540
We all retired early. Mina is now sleeping like a little child. It is a wonderful thing

14:01:22.540 --> 14:01:28.200
that her faculty of sleep remains to her in the midst of her terrible trouble. Thank God

14:01:28.200 --> 14:01:34.900
for it, for then at least she can forget her care. Perhaps her example may affect me as

14:01:34.900 --> 14:01:40.640
her gaiety did to-night. I shall try it. Oh, for a dreamless sleep!

14:01:43.100 --> 14:01:50.160
Next of October, morning. Another surprise. Mina woke me early, about the same time as

14:01:50.160 --> 14:01:56.480
yesterday, and asked me to bring Dr. Van Helsing. I thought that it was another occasion for

14:01:56.480 --> 14:02:03.360
hypnotism, and without question went for the Professor. He had evidently expected some

14:02:03.360 --> 14:02:09.260
such call, for I found him dressed in his room. His door was ajar, so that he could hear the

14:02:09.260 --> 14:02:15.620
opening of the door of our room. He came at once. As he passed into the room, he asked

14:02:15.620 --> 14:02:18.000
Mina if the others might come, too.

14:02:19.200 --> 14:02:25.400
No, she said quite simply. It will not be necessary. You can tell them just as well.

14:02:25.940 --> 14:02:28.120
I must go with you on your journey.

14:02:29.940 --> 14:02:35.360
Dr. Van Helsing was as startled as I was. After a moment's pause he asked,

14:02:36.080 --> 14:02:37.180
But why?

14:02:38.580 --> 14:02:43.880
You must take me with you. I am safer with you, and you shall be safer, too.

14:02:45.440 --> 14:02:52.840
But why, dear Madam Mina? You know that your safety is our solemnest duty. We go into danger,

14:02:52.880 --> 14:03:01.540
to which you are, or may be, more liable than any of us from, from circumstances, things

14:03:01.540 --> 14:03:02.580
that have been.

14:03:03.620 --> 14:03:10.300
He paused, embarrassed. As she replied, she raised her finger and pointed to her forehead.

14:03:11.360 --> 14:03:17.920
I know. That is why I must go. I can tell you now, whilst the sun is coming up, I may

14:03:17.920 --> 14:03:24.980
not be able again. I know that when the Count wills me, I must go. I know that if he tells

14:03:24.980 --> 14:03:31.440
me to come in secret, I must, by while, by any device to hoodwink, even Jonathan.

14:03:32.940 --> 14:03:38.460
God saw the look that she turned on me as she spoke, and if there be indeed a recording

14:03:38.460 --> 14:03:45.060
angel, that look is noted to her everlasting honour. I could only clasp her hand. I could

14:03:45.060 --> 14:03:49.940
not speak. My emotion was too great for even the relief of tears.

14:03:51.860 --> 14:03:53.220
She went on.

14:03:54.360 --> 14:03:59.640
You men are brave and strong. You are strong in your numbers, for you can defy that which

14:03:59.640 --> 14:04:05.140
would break down the human endurance of one who had to guard alone. Besides, I may be

14:04:05.140 --> 14:04:10.960
of service, since you can hypnotise me, and so learn that which even I myself do not know.

14:04:13.400 --> 14:04:15.700
Dr. Van Helsing said gravely,

14:04:16.380 --> 14:04:24.400
Madam Mina, you are, as always, most wise. You shall with us come, and together we shall

14:04:24.400 --> 14:04:26.840
do that which we go forth to achieve.

14:04:28.240 --> 14:04:34.440
When he had spoken, Mina's long spell of silence made me look at her. She had fallen

14:04:34.440 --> 14:04:39.780
back on her pillow asleep. She did not even wake when I had pulled up the blind and let

14:04:39.780 --> 14:04:41.820
in the sunlight which flooded the room.

14:04:43.160 --> 14:04:49.720
Van Helsing motioned to me to come with him quietly. We went to his room, and within a

14:04:49.720 --> 14:04:58.380
minute Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, and Mr. Morris were with us also. He told them what

14:04:58.380 --> 14:05:00.120
Mina had said, and went on.

14:05:01.120 --> 14:05:06.640
In the morning we shall leave for Varna. We have now to deal with a new factor, Madam

14:05:06.640 --> 14:05:13.840
Mina. Oh, but her soul is true. It is to her an agony to tell us so much as she has done.

14:05:14.400 --> 14:05:20.900
But it is most right, and we are warned in time. There must be no chance lost, and in

14:05:20.900 --> 14:05:24.800
Varna we must be ready to act the instant when that ship arrives.

14:05:26.540 --> 14:05:31.320
What shall we do exactly? asked Mr. Morris, laconically.

14:05:32.180 --> 14:05:35.320
The Professor paused before replying.

14:05:36.300 --> 14:05:42.560
We shall at the first board that ship. Then, when we have identified the box, we shall

14:05:42.560 --> 14:05:49.060
place a branch of the wild rose on it. This we shall fasten, for when it is there none

14:05:49.060 --> 14:05:57.160
can emerge, so that at least says the superstition. And to superstition must we trust at the first.

14:05:57.160 --> 14:06:04.080
It was man's faith in the early, and it have its root in faith still. Then, when we get

14:06:04.080 --> 14:06:11.380
the opportunity that we seek, when none are near to see, we shall open the box, and, and

14:06:11.380 --> 14:06:12.680
all will be well.

14:06:13.700 --> 14:06:20.380
I shall not wait for any opportunity, said Morris. When I see the box I shall open it

14:06:20.380 --> 14:06:25.660
and destroy the monster, though there were a thousand men looking on, and if I am to

14:06:25.660 --> 14:06:27.740
be wiped out for it the next moment.

14:06:29.160 --> 14:06:35.020
I grasped his hand instinctively, and found it as firm as a piece of steel. I think he

14:06:35.020 --> 14:06:37.820
understood my look. I hope he did.

14:06:39.060 --> 14:06:46.160
Good boy, said Dr. Van Helsing. Brave boy. Quincy is all man. God bless him for it.

14:06:46.820 --> 14:06:53.560
My child, believe me, none of us shall lag behind or pause from any fear. I do but say

14:06:53.560 --> 14:07:01.080
what we may do, what we must do. But indeed, indeed, we cannot say what we may do. There

14:07:01.080 --> 14:07:07.140
are so many things which may happen, and their ways and their ends are so various, that until

14:07:07.140 --> 14:07:08.880
the moment we may not say.

14:07:10.120 --> 14:07:16.500
We shall all be armed in all ways, and when the time for the end has come, our effort

14:07:16.500 --> 14:07:23.280
shall not be lack. Now let us today put all our affairs in order. Let all things which

14:07:23.280 --> 14:07:29.700
touch on others dear to us, and who on us depend, be complete. For none of us can tell

14:07:29.700 --> 14:07:39.040
what or when or how the end may be. As for me, my own affairs are regulate, and as I

14:07:39.040 --> 14:07:44.240
have nothing else to do, I shall go make arrangements for the travel. I shall have all tickets

14:07:44.240 --> 14:07:46.220
and so forth for our journey.

14:07:48.260 --> 14:07:54.880
There was nothing further to be said, and we parted. I shall now settle up all my affairs

14:07:54.880 --> 14:07:58.080
of earth, and be ready for whatever may come.

14:08:00.320 --> 14:08:09.600
Later. It is done. My will is made, and all complete. Mina, if she survive, is my sole

14:08:09.600 --> 14:08:16.340
care. If it should not be so, then the others who have been so good to us, shall have remainder.

14:08:17.980 --> 14:08:24.460
It is now drawing towards the sunset. Mina's uneasiness calls my attention to it. I am

14:08:24.460 --> 14:08:30.840
sure that there is something on her mind which the time of exact sunset will reveal. These

14:08:30.840 --> 14:08:36.780
occasions are becoming harrowing times for us all, for each sunrise and sunset opens

14:08:36.780 --> 14:08:43.840
up some new danger, some new pain, which, however, may in God's will be means to a good

14:08:43.840 --> 14:08:51.260
end. I write all these things in the diary, since my darling must not hear them now. But

14:08:51.540 --> 14:08:58.280
if it may be that she can see them again, they shall be ready. She is calling to me.

14:09:06.780 --> 14:09:10.320
2005. In Oceanside, California.

14:09:34.100 --> 14:09:36.660
Dracula by Bram Stoker

14:09:40.700 --> 14:09:44.840
Dr. Seward's Diary, 11th October, evening.

14:09:45.820 --> 14:09:52.700
Jonathan Harker has asked me to note this, as he says he is hardly equal to the task, and he wants an exact record kept.

14:09:53.440 --> 14:09:59.120
I think that none of us were surprised when we were asked to see Mrs. Harker a little before the time of sunset.

14:09:59.520 --> 14:10:05.280
We have of late come to understand that sunrise and sunset are to her times of peculiar freedom,

14:10:05.280 --> 14:10:12.920
when her old self can be manifest without any controlling force subduing or restraining her, or inciting her to action.

14:10:13.660 --> 14:10:18.780
This mood or condition begins some half hour or more before actual sunrise or sunset,

14:10:19.340 --> 14:10:25.480
and lasts till either the sun is high, or whilst the clouds are still aglow with the rays streaming above the horizon.

14:10:26.160 --> 14:10:33.020
At first there is a sort of negative condition, as if some tie were loosened, and then the absolute freedom quickly follows.

14:10:33.020 --> 14:10:40.380
When, however, the freedom ceases, the change back or relapse comes quickly, preceded only by a spell of warning silence.

14:10:41.460 --> 14:10:46.660
Tonight, when we met, she was somewhat constrained, and bore all the signs of an internal struggle.

14:10:47.100 --> 14:10:51.820
I put it down myself to her making a violent effort at the earliest instant she could do so.

14:10:52.940 --> 14:10:56.160
A very few minutes, however, gave her complete control of herself.

14:10:56.160 --> 14:11:04.120
Then, motioning her husband to sit beside her on the sofa where she was half reclining, she made the rest of us bring chairs up close.

14:11:05.180 --> 14:11:07.780
Taking her husband's hand in hers, she began,

14:11:08.380 --> 14:11:14.680
We are all here together in freedom for perhaps the last time. I know that you will always be with me to the end.

14:11:15.100 --> 14:11:19.360
This was to her husband, whose hand had, as we could see, tightened upon her.

14:11:19.920 --> 14:11:25.500
In the morning we go out upon our task, and God alone knows what may be in store for any of us.

14:11:25.500 --> 14:11:28.660
You are going to be so good to me to take me with you.

14:11:28.660 --> 14:11:34.560
I know that all that brave, earnest men can do for a poor, weak woman, whose soul perhaps is lost.

14:11:34.700 --> 14:11:39.000
No, no, not yet, but is at any rate at stake, you will do.

14:11:39.200 --> 14:11:41.840
But you must remember that I am not as you are.

14:11:42.280 --> 14:11:50.140
There is a poison in my blood, in my soul, which may destroy me, which must destroy me unless some relief comes to us.

14:11:50.500 --> 14:11:54.600
Oh, my friends, you know as well as I do that my soul is at stake.

14:11:54.600 --> 14:11:59.900
And though I know there is one way out for me, you must not and I must not take it.

14:12:00.300 --> 14:12:04.880
She looked appealing to us all in turn, beginning and ending with her husband.

14:12:06.260 --> 14:12:11.960
What is that way? asked Van Helsing in a hoarse voice. What is that way which we must not, may not take?

14:12:13.140 --> 14:12:19.740
That I may die now, either by my own hand or that of another, before the greater evil is entirely wrought.

14:12:19.740 --> 14:12:27.980
I know and you know that were I once dead you could and would set free my immortal spirit, even as you did my poor Lucy's.

14:12:28.380 --> 14:12:35.780
Were death or the fear of death the only thing that stood in the way, I would not shrink to die here now amidst the friends who love me.

14:12:36.480 --> 14:12:38.280
But death is not all.

14:12:38.860 --> 14:12:45.640
I cannot believe that to die in such a case, when there is hope before us and a bitter task to be done, is God's will.

14:12:46.180 --> 14:12:56.140
Therefore I am my part. Give up here the certainty of eternal rest, and go out into the dark where may be the blackest things that the world or the netherworld holds.

14:12:57.260 --> 14:13:01.420
We were all silent, for we knew instinctively that this was only a prelude.

14:13:02.480 --> 14:13:09.260
The faces of the others were set, and Harker's grew ash and gray. Perhaps he guessed better than any of us what was coming.

14:13:10.460 --> 14:13:11.500
She continued.

14:13:11.500 --> 14:13:14.840
This is what I can give into the hotchpot.

14:13:15.560 --> 14:13:20.560
I could not but note the quaint legal phrase which she used in such a place, and with all seriousness.

14:13:21.540 --> 14:13:32.740
What will each of you give? Your lives I know, she went on quickly. That is easy for brave men. Your lives are God's, and you can give them back to him. But what will you give to me?

14:13:33.200 --> 14:13:37.400
She looked again questioningly, but this time avoided her husband's face.

14:13:38.240 --> 14:13:42.340
Quincy seemed to understand. He nodded, and her face lit up.

14:13:42.420 --> 14:13:56.020
Then I shall tell you plainly what I want, for there must be no doubtful matter in this connection between us now. You must promise me, one and all, even you, my beloved husband, that should the time come, you will kill me.

14:13:57.340 --> 14:14:01.900
What is that time? The voice was Quincy's, but it was low and strained.

14:14:02.680 --> 14:14:18.720
When you shall be convinced that I am so changed that it is better that I die than I may live. When I am thus dead in the flesh, then you will, without a moment's delay, drive a stake through me and cut off my head, or do whatever else may be wanting to give me rest.

14:14:19.960 --> 14:14:47.660
Quincy was the first to rise after the pause. He knelt down before her, and taking her hand in his said solemnly, I am only a rough fellow who hasn't perhaps lived as a man should to win such a distinction. But I swear to you by all that I hold sacred and dear that, should the time ever come, I shall not flinch from the duty that you have set us. And I promise you too that I shall make all certain, for if I am only doubtful, I shall take it that the time has come.

14:14:48.420 --> 14:14:54.900
My true friend was all she could say, amid her fast-falling tears, as bending over she kissed his hand.

14:14:55.620 --> 14:14:59.020
I swear the same might the amount of Mina, said Van Helsing.

14:14:59.440 --> 14:15:05.000
And I, said Lord Godalming, each of them in turn kneeling to her to take the oath, I followed myself.

14:15:05.760 --> 14:15:12.660
Then her husband turned to her wan-eyed, and with a greenish pallor, which subdued the snowy whiteness of his hair, and asked,

14:15:12.660 --> 14:15:16.240
And must I too make such a promise, oh my wife?

14:15:17.480 --> 14:15:24.620
You too, my dearest, she said, with infinite yearning of pity in her voice and eyes, you must not shrink.

14:15:25.240 --> 14:15:32.060
You are nearest and dearest in all the world to me. Our souls are knit into one for all life and all time.

14:15:32.820 --> 14:15:40.580
Think, dear, that there have been times when brave men have killed their wives and their womankind to keep them from falling into the hands of the enemy.

14:15:40.580 --> 14:15:46.420
Their hands did not falter any the more because those that they love implored them to slay them.

14:15:46.840 --> 14:15:51.760
It is men's duty towards those whom they love in such times of sore trial.

14:15:52.420 --> 14:15:59.180
And, oh my dear, if it is to be that I must meet death at any hand, let it be at the hand of him that loves me best.

14:16:00.160 --> 14:16:05.120
Dr. Van Helsing, I have not forgotten your mercy in poor Lucy's case to him who loved.

14:16:05.120 --> 14:16:11.380
She stopped with a flying blush and changed her phrase, to him who had best right to give her peace.

14:16:12.240 --> 14:16:21.940
If that time shall come again, I look to you to make it a happy memory of my husband's life that it was his loving hand which set me free from the awful thrall upon me.

14:16:22.580 --> 14:16:25.720
Again, I swear, came the professor's resonant voice.

14:16:26.740 --> 14:16:32.260
Mrs. Harker smiled, positively smiled, as with a sigh of relief she leaned back and said,

14:16:32.260 --> 14:16:37.300
And now one word of warning, a warning which you must never forget.

14:16:38.100 --> 14:16:45.980
This time, if it ever come, may come quickly and unexpectedly, and in such case you must lose no time in using your opportunity.

14:16:46.580 --> 14:16:54.400
At such a time I myself might be, nay, at the time ever come shall be, lead with your enemy against you.

14:16:54.980 --> 14:16:58.740
One more request, she became very solemn as she said this.

14:16:58.740 --> 14:17:04.840
It is not vital and necessary like the other, but I want you to do one thing for me, if you will.

14:17:05.540 --> 14:17:09.020
We all acquiesced, but no one spoke. There was no need to speak.

14:17:10.160 --> 14:17:12.340
I want you to read the burial service.

14:17:12.820 --> 14:17:15.260
She was interrupted by a deep groan from her husband.

14:17:15.900 --> 14:17:19.720
Taking his hand in hers, she held it over her heart and continued.

14:17:20.520 --> 14:17:22.960
You must read it over me some day.

14:17:23.200 --> 14:17:29.220
Whatever may be the issue of all this fearful state of things, it will be a sweet thought to all or some of us.

14:17:29.780 --> 14:17:35.640
You, my dearest, will I hope read it, for then it will be in your voice in my memory for ever, come what may.

14:17:36.760 --> 14:17:41.080
But, oh, my dear one, he pleaded, death is afar off from you.

14:17:41.920 --> 14:17:49.320
Nay, she said, holding up a warning hand, I am deeper in death at this moment than if the weight of an earthly grave lay heavy upon me.

14:17:50.360 --> 14:17:53.980
Oh, my wife, must I read it, he said before he began.

14:17:54.460 --> 14:18:00.680
It would comfort me, my husband, was all she said, and he began to read when she had got the book ready.

14:18:01.860 --> 14:18:12.100
How can I, how could anyone, tell of that strange scene, its solemnity, its gloom, its sadness, its horror, and with all its sweetness?

14:18:12.840 --> 14:18:18.820
Even a skeptic, who can see nothing but a travesty of bitter truth in anything holy or emotional,

14:18:19.360 --> 14:18:27.020
would have been melted to the heart had he seen that little group of loving and devoted friends kneeling round that stricken and sorrowing lady,

14:18:27.400 --> 14:18:33.840
or heard the tender passion of her husband's voice, as intoned so broken and emotional that often he had to pause.

14:18:34.320 --> 14:18:37.560
He read the simple and beautiful service from the burial of the dead.

14:18:37.560 --> 14:18:42.720
I cannot go on, words and voices fail me.

14:18:43.920 --> 14:18:45.560
She was right in her instinct.

14:18:46.680 --> 14:18:54.360
Strange as it was, bizarre as it may hereafter seem, even to us who felt its potent influence at the time, it comforted us much.

14:18:55.160 --> 14:19:03.860
And the silence which showed Mrs. Harker's coming relapse from her freedom of soul did not seem so full of despair to any of us as we had dreaded.

14:19:06.800 --> 14:19:10.400
Jonathan Harker's Journal, 15 October, Varna

14:19:11.440 --> 14:19:19.120
We left Charing Cross on the morning of the 12th, got to Paris the same night, and took the places secured for us in the Orient Express.

14:19:19.900 --> 14:19:23.200
We traveled night and day, arriving here at about five o'clock.

14:19:24.060 --> 14:19:30.980
Lord Goodalming went to Consulate to see if any telegram had arrived for him, while the rest of us came on to this hotel, the Odessus.

14:19:31.560 --> 14:19:36.720
The journey may have had incidents, I was however too eager to get on to care for them.

14:19:37.360 --> 14:19:43.100
Until the Tsarina Catherine comes into port there will be no interest for me in anything in the wide world.

14:19:43.900 --> 14:19:46.680
Thank God Mina is well and looks to be getting stronger.

14:19:47.180 --> 14:19:50.100
Her color is coming back, she sleeps a great deal.

14:19:50.700 --> 14:19:53.240
Throughout the journey she slept nearly all the time.

14:19:53.920 --> 14:20:02.180
Before sunrise and sunset, however, she is very wakeful and alert, and it has become a habit for Van Helsing to hypnotize her at such times.

14:20:02.800 --> 14:20:11.460
At first some effort was needed and he had to make many passes, but now she seems to yield at once, as if by habit, and scarcely any action is needed.

14:20:12.040 --> 14:20:17.080
He seems to have power at those particular moments to simply will, and her thoughts obey him.

14:20:17.540 --> 14:20:19.900
He always asks her what she can see and hear.

14:20:19.900 --> 14:20:22.080
She answers to the first,

14:20:39.660 --> 14:20:45.240
It is evident that the Tsarina Catherine is still at sea, hastening on her way to Varna.

14:20:45.780 --> 14:20:47.700
Lord Godalming has just returned.

14:20:47.940 --> 14:20:56.360
He had four telegrams, one each day since we started, and all to the same effect, that the Tsarina Catherine had not been reported to the Lloyds from anywhere.

14:20:57.220 --> 14:21:03.620
He had arranged before leaving London that his agent should send him every day a telegram saying if the ship had been reported.

14:21:04.120 --> 14:21:11.260
He was to have a message even if she were not reported, so that he might be sure that there was a watch being kept at the other end of the wire.

14:21:12.620 --> 14:21:14.540
We had dinner and went to bed early.

14:21:15.000 --> 14:21:21.580
Tomorrow we are to see the vice-consul, and to arrange, if we can, about getting on board the ship as soon as she arrives.

14:21:22.600 --> 14:21:26.940
Van Helsink says that our chance will be to get on the boat between sunrise and sunset.

14:21:27.680 --> 14:21:34.840
The Count, even if he takes the form of a bat, cannot cross the running water of his own volition, and so cannot leave the ship.

14:21:35.320 --> 14:21:41.900
As he dare not change to man's form without suspicion, which he evidently wishes to avoid, he must remain in the box.

14:21:42.520 --> 14:21:51.760
If then we can come on board after sunrise, he is at our mercy, for we can open the box and make sure of him as we did of poor Lucy before he wakes.

14:21:53.020 --> 14:21:56.500
What mercy he shall get from us all will not count for much.

14:21:57.020 --> 14:22:00.640
We think that we shall not have much trouble with officials or the seamen.

14:22:00.720 --> 14:22:06.060
Thank God, this is the country where bribery can do anything, and we are well supplied with money.

14:22:06.060 --> 14:22:14.660
We have only to make sure that the ship cannot come into port between sunset and sunrise without our being warned, and we shall be safe.

14:22:15.340 --> 14:22:18.020
Judge Moneybag will settle this case, I think.

14:22:20.500 --> 14:22:21.540
16th October.

14:22:22.000 --> 14:22:27.180
Mina's report still the same. Lapping waves and rushing water, darkness and favoring winds.

14:22:27.780 --> 14:22:32.500
We are evidently in good time, and when we hear of the Tsarina Catherine, we shall be ready.

14:22:32.500 --> 14:22:36.080
As she must pass the Dardanelles, we are sure to have some report.

14:22:38.440 --> 14:22:39.380
17th October.

14:22:39.900 --> 14:22:44.520
Everything is pretty well fixed now, I think, to welcome the Count on his return from his tour.

14:22:45.120 --> 14:22:54.500
Godalming told the shippers that he fancied that the box sent aboard might contain something stolen from a friend of his, and got a half consent that he might open it at his own risk.

14:22:55.060 --> 14:23:05.240
The owner gave him a paper telling the captain to give him every facility in doing whatever he chose on board the ship, and also a similar authorization to his agent at Varna.

14:23:06.140 --> 14:23:15.000
We have seen the agent, who is much impressed with Godalming's kindly manner to him, and we are all satisfied that whatever he can do to aid our wishes will be done.

14:23:16.180 --> 14:23:19.700
We have also arranged what to do in case we get the box open.

14:23:19.700 --> 14:23:25.580
If the Count is there, Van Helsing and Seward will cut off his head at once and drive a stake through his heart.

14:23:26.220 --> 14:23:31.860
Morris and Godalming and I shall prevent interference, even if we have to use the arms which we shall have ready.

14:23:32.400 --> 14:23:38.100
The Professor says that if we can so treat the Count's body, it will soon after fall into dust.

14:23:38.660 --> 14:23:43.900
In such case, there would be no evidence against us, in case any suspicion of murder were aroused.

14:23:43.900 --> 14:23:53.320
But even if it were not, we should stand or fall by our act, and perhaps some day this very script may be evidence to come between some of us and a rope.

14:23:54.300 --> 14:23:58.060
For myself, I should take the chance only too thankfully if it were to come.

14:23:58.480 --> 14:24:01.800
We mean to leave no stone unturned to carry out our intent.

14:24:02.400 --> 14:24:09.100
We have arranged with certain officials that the instant the Tsarina Catherine is seen, we are to be informed by a special messenger.

14:24:11.280 --> 14:24:18.820
24th October. A whole week of waiting. Daily telegrams to Godalming, but only the same story. Not yet reported.

14:24:19.580 --> 14:24:26.100
Mina's morning and evening hypnotic answer is unvaried. Lapping waves, rushing water, and creaking masts.

14:24:29.520 --> 14:24:36.960
Telegram. October 24th. Rufus Smith, Lloyds, London. To Lloyd Godalming, care of HBM Vice Consul Varna.

14:24:36.960 --> 14:24:40.600
Tsarina Catherine reported this morning from Dardanelles.

14:24:42.740 --> 14:24:45.460
Dr. Seward's Diary. 25th October.

14:24:46.340 --> 14:24:53.220
How I miss my phonograph. To write a diary with a pen is irksome to me. But Van Helsing says I must.

14:24:53.820 --> 14:25:02.320
We were all wild with excitement yesterday when Godalming got his telegram from Lloyds. I know now what men feel in battle when the call to action is heard.

14:25:02.860 --> 14:25:17.540
Mrs. Harker, alone of our party, did not show any signs of emotion. After all, it is not strange that she did not, for we took special care not to let her know anything about it, and we all tried not to show any excitement when we were in her presence.

14:25:18.480 --> 14:25:23.600
In old days she would, I am sure, have noticed, no matter how we might have tried to conceal it.

14:25:23.600 --> 14:25:38.060
But in this way she has greatly changed during the past three weeks. The lethargy grows upon her, and though she seems strong and well and is getting back some of her color, Van Helsing and I are not satisfied. We talk of her often.

14:25:38.820 --> 14:25:47.880
We have not, however, said a word to the others. It would break poor Harker's heart, certainly his nerve, if he knew that we had even a suspicion on the subject.

14:25:48.560 --> 14:25:59.860
Van Helsing examines, he tells me, her teeth very carefully, while she is in the hypnotic condition, for he says that so long as they do not begin to sharpen, there is no active danger of a change in her.

14:26:00.520 --> 14:26:09.480
If this change should come, it would be necessary to take steps. We both know what those steps would have to be, though we do not mention our thoughts to each other.

14:26:09.480 --> 14:26:19.240
We should neither of us shrink from the task, awful though it may be, to contemplate. Euthanasia is an excellent and comforting word, and I am grateful to whoever invented it.

14:26:20.560 --> 14:26:37.980
It is only about 24 hours' sail from the Dardanelles to here, at the rate that Zarina Catherine has come from London. She should therefore arrive sometime in the morning, but as she cannot possibly get in before noon, we are all about to retire early. We shall get up at one o'clock, so as to be ready.

14:26:40.240 --> 14:26:51.580
25th October, noon. No news yet of the ship's arrival. Mrs. Harker's hypnotic report this morning was the same as usual, so it is possible that we may get news at any moment.

14:26:52.200 --> 14:27:04.900
We men are all in a fever of excitement, except Harker, who is calm. His hands are cold as ice, and an hour ago I found him wetting the edge of the great Gurkha knife which he now always carries with him.

14:27:04.900 --> 14:27:12.060
It will be a bad lookout for the Count if the edge of that kukri ever touches his throat, driven by that stern, ice-cold hand.

14:27:13.480 --> 14:27:21.180
Van Helsing and I were a little alarmed about Mrs. Harker today. About noon she got into a sort of lethargy which we did not like.

14:27:21.840 --> 14:27:30.920
Although we kept silence to the others, we were neither of us happy about it. She had been restless all the morning, so that we were at first glad to know that she was sleeping.

14:27:31.360 --> 14:27:39.200
When, however, her husband mentioned casually that she was sleeping so soundly that he could not wake her, we went to her room to see for ourselves.

14:27:40.000 --> 14:27:46.400
She was breathing naturally, and looked so well and peaceful that we agreed that the sleep was better for her than anything else.

14:27:47.220 --> 14:27:54.720
Poor girl. She has so much to forget that it is no wonder that sleep, if it brings oblivion to her, does her good.

14:27:56.340 --> 14:28:05.180
Later. Our opinion was justified, for when after a refreshing sleep of some hours she woke up, she seemed brighter and better than she had been for days.

14:28:05.580 --> 14:28:14.640
At sunset she made the usual hypnotic report. Wherever he may be in the Black Sea, the Count is hurrying to his destination. To his doom, I trust.

14:28:17.040 --> 14:28:29.920
26th October. Another day and no tidings of the Tsarina Catherine. She ought to be here by now, but she is still journeying somewhere as apparent, for Mrs. Harker's hypnotic report at sunrise was still the same.

14:28:30.400 --> 14:28:40.660
It is possible that the vessel may be lying by at times for fog. Some of the steamers which came in last evening reported patches of fog both to the north and south of the port.

14:28:40.660 --> 14:28:45.100
We must continue our watching as the ship may now be signaled any moment.

14:28:46.820 --> 14:28:48.880
27th October. Noon.

14:28:49.280 --> 14:29:00.400
Most strange. No news yet of the ship we wait for. Mrs. Harker reported last night and this morning, as usual, lapping waves and rushing water, though she added that the waves were very faint.

14:29:01.320 --> 14:29:04.660
The telegrams from London have been the same. No further report.

14:29:04.660 --> 14:29:12.140
Van Helsing is terribly anxious and told me just now that he fears the Count is escaping us. He added significantly.

14:29:12.900 --> 14:29:18.840
I did not like that lethargy of Madame Mina's. Souls and memories can do strange things during trance.

14:29:19.800 --> 14:29:29.720
I was about to ask him more, but Harker just then came in and he held up a warning hand. We must try tonight at sunset to make her speak more fully when in her hypnotic state.

14:29:31.580 --> 14:29:42.480
28th October. Telegram. Rufus Smith. London. To Lord Goodalming. Kara HBM Vice Consul Varna. Zarina Catherine reported entering Galatz at 1 o'clock today.

14:29:44.360 --> 14:29:46.980
Dr. Seward's Diary. 28th October.

14:29:47.640 --> 14:29:54.040
When the telegram came announcing the arrival in Galatz, I do not think it was such a shock to any of us as might have been expected.

14:29:54.040 --> 14:30:01.360
True, we did not know whence or how or when the bolt would come, but I think we all expected that something strange would happen.

14:30:02.040 --> 14:30:11.260
The day of arrival at Varna made us individually satisfied that things would not be just as we had expected. We only waited to learn where the change would occur.

14:30:12.680 --> 14:30:24.680
Nonetheless, however, it was a surprise. I suppose that nature works on such a hopeful basis that we believe against ourselves that things will be as they ought to be, not as we should know that they will be.

14:30:25.460 --> 14:30:29.940
Transcendentalism is a beacon to the angels, even if it be a will of the wisp to man.

14:30:30.840 --> 14:30:40.760
Van Helsing raised his hand over his head for a moment, as though in remonstrance with the Almighty, but he said not a word, and in a few seconds stood up with his face sternly set.

14:30:41.600 --> 14:30:49.380
Lord Goodalming grew very pale and sat breathing heavily. I was myself half stunned and looked in wonder at one after another.

14:30:49.980 --> 14:30:56.540
Quincy Morris tightened his belt with that quick movement which I knew so well. In our old wandering days it meant action.

14:30:57.260 --> 14:31:04.760
Mrs. Harker grew ghastly white so that the scar on her forehead seemed to burn, but she folded her hands meekly and looked up in prayer.

14:31:05.460 --> 14:31:19.400
Harker smiled, actually smiled, the dark, bitter smile of one who is without hope, but at the same time his action belied his words, for his hands instinctively sought the hilt of the great Kukri knife and rested there.

14:31:35.940 --> 14:31:42.640
You forget, or perhaps you do not know, though Jonathan does, and so does Dr. Van Helsing, that I am the train fiend.

14:31:43.040 --> 14:31:52.720
At home in Exeter I always used to make up the timetables so as to be helpful to my husband. I found it so useful sometimes that I always make a study of the timetables now.

14:31:53.160 --> 14:32:01.540
I knew that if anything were to take us to Castle Dracula we should go by Galatz, or at any rate through Bucharest, so I learned the times very carefully.

14:32:02.180 --> 14:32:06.480
Unhappily there are not many to learn, as the only train to-morrow leaves as I say.

14:32:07.420 --> 14:32:09.540
Wonderful woman, murmured the professor.

14:32:10.680 --> 14:32:13.000
Can't we get a special? asked Orgedalming.

14:32:14.080 --> 14:32:15.400
Van Helsing shook his head.

14:32:15.900 --> 14:32:24.900
I fear not. This land is very different from yours or mine. Even if we did have a special, it would probably not arrive as soon as our regular train.

14:32:25.500 --> 14:32:28.520
Moreover, we have something to prepare. We must think.

14:32:29.300 --> 14:32:36.240
Now let us organize. Your friend Arthur, go to the train and get the tickets and arrange that all be ready for us to go in the morning.

14:32:37.080 --> 14:32:46.340
Through your friend Jonathan, go to the agent of the ship and get from him letters to the agent in Galatz, with authority to make a search of the ship just as it was here.

14:32:47.320 --> 14:32:57.580
Quincy Morris, you see the vice-counsel, and get his aid with his fellow in Galatz, and all he can do to make our way smooth, so that no times be lost when over the Danube.

14:32:58.380 --> 14:33:09.060
John will stay with Madame Mina and me, and we shall consult. For so, if time be long, you may be delayed, and it will not matter when the sun sets, since I am here with Madame to make report.

14:33:09.940 --> 14:33:25.300
And I, said Mrs. Harker brightly, and more like her old self than she had been for many a long day, shall try to be of use in all ways, and shall think and write for you as I used to do. Something is shifting from me in some strange way, and I feel freer than I have been of late.

14:33:26.540 --> 14:33:39.520
The three younger men looked happier at the moment, as they seemed to realize the significance of her words. But Van Helsing and I, turning to each other, met each a grave and troubled glance. We said nothing at the time, however.

14:33:41.040 --> 14:33:51.940
When the three men had gone out to their tasks, Van Helsing asked Mrs. Harker to look up the copy of the diaries, and find him the part of Harker's journal at the castle. She went away to get it.

14:33:52.520 --> 14:33:56.660
When the door was shut upon her, he said to me, We mean the same. Speak out.

14:33:57.700 --> 14:34:02.340
Here is some change. It is a hope that makes me sick, for it may deceive us.

14:34:02.620 --> 14:34:05.960
Quite so. Do you know why I asked her to get the manuscript?

14:34:06.700 --> 14:34:10.940
No, said I, unless it was to get an opportunity of seeing me alone.

14:34:11.600 --> 14:34:22.040
You are in part right, friend John, but only in part. I want to tell you something, and, oh my friend, I am taking a terrible risk. But I believe it is right.

14:34:22.940 --> 14:34:28.980
In the moment when Madame Mina said those words that arrest both our understanding, an inspiration came to me.

14:34:29.360 --> 14:34:33.880
In the trance of three days ago, the Count sent her his spirit to read her mind.

14:34:33.880 --> 14:34:42.540
Or more like he took her to see him in his earth box in the ship with water rushing, just as it got free at rise and set of sun.

14:34:43.360 --> 14:34:58.560
He learned then that we are here, for she have more to tell in her open life with eyes to see, ears to hear than he, shut as he is, in his coffin box. Now he make his most effort to escape us. At present he want her not.

14:34:59.320 --> 14:35:09.000
He is sure with his so great knowledge that she will come at his call. But he cut her off, take her as he can do, out of his own power, that so she come not to him.

14:35:09.720 --> 14:35:24.860
Ah, there I have hoped that our man-brains that have been of man so long, and that have not lost the grace of God, will come higher than his child-brain that lie in his tomb for centuries, that grow not yet to our stature, and that do only work selfish and therefore small.

14:35:24.860 --> 14:35:47.880
Here comes Madame Mina, not a word to her of her trance. She knows it not. And it would overwhelm her and make despair just when we want all her hope, all her courage, when most we want all her great brain which is trained like man's brain, but is of sweet woman and have a special power which the Count give her, and which he may not take away altogether, though he think not so.

14:35:47.880 --> 14:36:00.360
Hush, let me speak and you shall learn. John, my friend, we are in awful straits. I fear as I never feared it before. We can only trust the good God. Silence, here she comes.

14:36:00.980 --> 14:36:17.900
I thought that the Professor was going to break down and have hysterics, just as he had when Lucy died, but with a great effort he controlled himself, and was at perfect nervous poise when Mrs. Harker tripped into the room, bright and happy-looking, and in the doing of work seemingly forgetful of her misery.

14:36:17.900 --> 14:36:30.740
As she came in, she handed a number of sheets of typewriting to Van Helsing. He looked over them gravely, his face brightening up as he read. Then, holding the pages between his finger and thumb, he said,

14:36:30.740 --> 14:36:54.420
Friend John, to you with so much experience already, and you too, dear Madam Mina, that are young, here is a lesson. Do not fear ever to think. A half-thought has been buzzing often in my brain, but I fear to let him loose his wings. Here now, with more knowledge, I go back to where that half-thought come from and I find that he be no half-thought at all.

14:36:54.420 --> 14:37:14.540
That be a whole thought, though so young that he is not yet strong to use his little wings. Nay, like the ugly duck of my friend Hans Anderson, he be no dark thought at all, but a big swan thought to sail nobly on big wings when the time come for him to try them. See, I read here what Jonathan hath written.

14:37:15.740 --> 14:37:35.100
That other of his ways who, in a later age, again and again, brought his forces over the great river in the Turkland, who, when he was beaten back, came again and again and again, though he had come alone from the bloody field where his troops were being slaughtered, since he knew that he alone could ultimately triumph.

14:37:35.780 --> 14:37:56.900
What does this tell us? Not much? No. The celt's child thought see nothing, therefore he speaks so free. Your man thought see nothing. My man thought see nothing till just now. No. But there comes another word from someone who speak without thought, because she too know not what it mean, what it might mean.

14:37:56.900 --> 14:38:14.000
Just as there are elements which rest, yet when in nature's course they move on their way and they touch the poof, and there comes a flash of light heaven-wide that blind and kill and destroy some, but that show up all earth below for leagues and leagues. Is it not so?

14:38:14.780 --> 14:38:27.740
Well, I shall explain. To begin, have you ever studied the philosophy of crime? Yes and no. You drawn yes, for it is a study of insanity. You know, Madame Mina, for crime touch you not, not but once.

14:38:27.740 --> 14:38:49.540
Still, your mind works true and argues not, a particularly odd universal. There is this peculiarity in criminals. It is so constant in all countries and at all times that even police, who know not much from philosophy, come to know it empirically that it is. That is to be empiric.

14:38:49.540 --> 14:39:08.300
The criminal always works at one crime. That is the true criminal who seems predestinate to crime and who will of none other. This criminal has not full man brain. He is clever and cunning and resourceful, but he be not of man's stature as to brain. He be of child brain in much.

14:39:08.860 --> 14:39:28.380
Now, this criminal of ours is predestinate to crime also. He too have child brain, and it is of the child to do what he have done. The little bird, the little fish, the little animal, not by principle but empirically. And when he learn to do, then there is to him the ground to start from to do more.

14:39:29.220 --> 14:39:56.020
Das puh sto, said Archimedes. Give me a fulcrum and I shall move the world. To do once is the fulcrum whereby child brain become man brain. And until he have the purpose to do more, he continue to do the same, again, every time, just as he have done before. Oh, my dear, I see that your eyes are opened and that to you the lightning flash show all the leagues. For Mrs. Harker began to clap her hands and her eyes sparkled.

14:39:56.540 --> 14:40:11.940
He went on. Now you shall speak. Tell us, two dry men of science, what you see with those so bright eyes. He took her hand and held it whilst he spoke. His fingers and thumb closed on her pulse, as I thought instinctively and unconsciously, as she spoke.

14:40:12.920 --> 14:40:41.920
The Count is a criminal and a criminal type. Norda and Lombroso would so classify him, and quote criminal, he is of an imperfectly formed mind. Thus, in a difficulty, he has to seek resource in habit. His past is a clue, and the one page of it that we know, and that from his own lips, tells that once before, when in what Mr. Morris would call a tight place, he went back to his own country from the land he had tried to invade, and thence,

14:40:41.920 --> 14:41:03.960
without losing purpose, prepared himself for a new effort. He came again better equipped for his work, and won. So he came to London to invade a new land. He was beaten, and when all hope of success was lost, and his existence in danger, he fled back over the sea to his home, just as formerly he had fled back over the Danube from Turkey-land.

14:41:04.680 --> 14:41:33.640
"'Good, good! Oh, you're so clever, lady,' said Van Helsink, enthusiastically, as he stooped and kissed her hand. A moment later he said to me, as calmly as though we had been having a sickroom consultation, "'Seventy-two only, and in all this excitement, I have hope.'" Turning to her again, he said with keen expectation, "'But go on, go on! There is more to tell, if you will. Be not afraid. John and I know. I do in any case, and shall tell you, if you are right.'

14:41:33.640 --> 14:41:45.640
"'Speak without fear. I will try to, but you will forgive me if I seem too egotistical. Nah, fear not. You must be egotist, for it is of you that we think.'"

14:41:46.420 --> 14:42:07.020
Then, as he is criminal, he is selfish. And as his intellect is small, and his action is based on selfishness, he confines himself to one purpose. That purpose is remorseless. As he fled back over the Danube, leaving his forces to be cut to pieces, so now he is intent on being safe, careless of all.

14:42:07.020 --> 14:42:28.960
So his own selfishness frees my soul somewhat from the terrible power which he acquired over me on that dreadful night. I felt it! Oh, I felt it! Thank God for his great mercy! My soul is freer than it has been since that awful hour, and all that haunts me is a fear, lest in some trance or dream he may have used my knowledge for his ends.

14:42:29.900 --> 14:42:48.420
The professor stood up. He has, so used your mind. And by it he has left us here in Varna, whilst the ship that carried him rushed through enveloping fog up to Glatz, where doubtless he had made preparation for escaping from us. But his child-mind only saw so far.

14:42:48.420 --> 14:43:04.400
And it may be that as ever is in God's providence, the very thing that the evildoer most reckoned on for his selfish good turns out to be his chiefest harm. The hunter is taken in his own snare, as the great psalmist says.

14:43:04.400 --> 14:43:22.900
For now that he thinks he is free from every trace of us all, and that he has escaped us with so many hours to him, then his selfish child-brain will whisper him to sleep. He thinks, too, that as he cuts himself off from knowing your mind, there can be no knowledge of him to you, and that is where he fails.

14:43:22.900 --> 14:43:42.880
That terrible baptism of blood which he gave you makes you free to go to him in spirit, as you have yet yet done in your times of freedom when the sun rise and set. At such times you go by my volition and not by his. And this power to good of you and others you have won from your suffering at his hands.

14:43:43.360 --> 14:43:57.780
This is now all more precious that he know it not, and to God himself have even cut himself off from his knowledge of our where. We, however, are not selfish, and we believe that God is with us through all this blackness and these many dark hours.

14:43:58.380 --> 14:44:17.680
We shall follow him, and we shall not flinch, even if we peril ourselves that we become like him. Friend John, this has been a great hour, and it have done much to advance us on our way. You must prescribe and write him all down, so that when the others return from their work you can give it to them, then they shall know as we do.

14:44:18.380 --> 14:44:27.480
And so I have written it, whilst we wait their return, and Mrs. Harker has written with the typewriter all since she brought the manuscript to us.

14:44:54.740 --> 14:44:58.320
Dracula by Bram Stoker

14:45:05.780 --> 14:45:07.860
Dr. Seward's Diary

14:45:07.860 --> 14:45:09.360
29 October

14:45:10.600 --> 14:45:13.720
This is written in the train from Varna to Galatz.

14:45:14.460 --> 14:45:17.720
Last night we all assembled a little before the time of sunset.

14:45:18.460 --> 14:45:23.680
Each of us has done his work as well as he could, as far as thought and endeavor and opportunity go.

14:45:24.300 --> 14:45:29.360
We are prepared for the whole of our journey and for our work when we get to Galatz.

14:45:30.440 --> 14:45:35.260
When the usual time came round Mrs. Harker prepared herself for her hypnotic effort

14:45:35.260 --> 14:45:39.200
and after a longer and more serious effort on the part of Van Helsing

14:45:39.200 --> 14:45:43.540
than had been usually necessary she sank into the trance.

14:45:43.820 --> 14:45:48.140
Usually she speaks on a hint but this time the professor had to ask her questions

14:45:48.140 --> 14:45:52.040
and had to ask them pretty resolutely before we could learn anything.

14:45:52.720 --> 14:45:55.100
At last her answer came.

14:45:55.920 --> 14:45:58.320
I can see nothing. We are still.

14:45:58.920 --> 14:46:04.580
There are no waves lapping but only a steady swirl of water running softly against the hauser.

14:46:05.740 --> 14:46:12.100
I can hear men's voices calling near and far and the roll and creak of oars in the rowlocks.

14:46:13.040 --> 14:46:17.520
A gun is fired somewhere. The echo of it seems far away.

14:46:17.520 --> 14:46:23.140
There is trampling of feet overhead and ropes and chains are dragged along.

14:46:24.440 --> 14:46:30.340
What is this? There is a gleam of light. I can feel the air blowing upon me.

14:46:31.440 --> 14:46:36.920
Here she stopped. She had risen as if impulsively from where she lay on the sofa

14:46:36.920 --> 14:46:41.580
and raised both her hands palms upwards as if lifting a weight.

14:46:42.360 --> 14:46:45.080
Van Helsing and I looked at each other with understanding.

14:46:46.380 --> 14:46:50.220
Quincy raised his eyebrows slightly and looked at her intently

14:46:50.220 --> 14:46:55.040
whilst Harker's hand instinctively closed round the hilt of his kukri.

14:46:58.120 --> 14:46:59.700
There was a long pause.

14:47:00.620 --> 14:47:03.700
We all knew that the time when she could speak was passing

14:47:03.700 --> 14:47:06.200
but we felt that it was useless to say anything.

14:47:07.540 --> 14:47:12.180
Suddenly she sat up and as she opened her eyes said sweetly

14:47:12.900 --> 14:47:14.760
Would none of you like a cup of tea?

14:47:15.760 --> 14:47:17.600
You must all be so tired.

14:47:19.400 --> 14:47:22.540
We could only make her happy and so Aqua asked.

14:47:24.280 --> 14:47:26.380
She bustled off to get tea.

14:47:26.920 --> 14:47:29.100
When she had gone Van Helsing said

14:47:29.100 --> 14:47:32.260
You see my friends he is close to land.

14:47:32.900 --> 14:47:36.340
He has left his earth chest but he is yet to get on shore.

14:47:36.820 --> 14:47:38.840
In the night he may lie hidden somewhere

14:47:38.840 --> 14:47:42.120
but if he be not carried on shore or if the ship do not touch it

14:47:42.120 --> 14:47:43.620
he cannot achieve the land.

14:47:44.200 --> 14:47:49.260
In such case he can if it be in the night change his form and jump or fly on shore.

14:47:49.500 --> 14:47:51.800
Then unless he be carried he cannot escape

14:47:51.800 --> 14:47:56.140
and if he be carried then the customs man may discover what the box contain.

14:47:57.160 --> 14:48:00.780
Thus and fine if he escaped not on shore tonight or before dawn

14:48:00.780 --> 14:48:03.060
there will be the whole day lost to him.

14:48:03.600 --> 14:48:05.560
We may then arrive in time

14:48:05.560 --> 14:48:08.800
For he escaped not at night we shall come on him in day time

14:48:08.800 --> 14:48:10.380
boxed up and at our mercy

14:48:10.380 --> 14:48:13.520
for he dare not be his true self awake and visible

14:48:13.520 --> 14:48:14.840
lest he be discovered.

14:48:16.420 --> 14:48:17.980
There was no more to be said

14:48:17.980 --> 14:48:20.440
so he waited in patience until the dawn

14:48:20.440 --> 14:48:23.660
at which time we might learn more from Mrs. Harker.

14:48:24.660 --> 14:48:27.540
Early this morning we listened with breathless anxiety

14:48:27.540 --> 14:48:29.800
for her response in her trance.

14:48:30.040 --> 14:48:33.060
The hypnotic stage was even longer in coming than before

14:48:33.060 --> 14:48:38.140
and when it came the time remaining until full sunrise was so short that we began to despair.

14:48:39.240 --> 14:48:42.280
Van Helsing seemed to throw his whole soul into the effort.

14:48:42.800 --> 14:48:46.020
At last in obedience to his will she made reply.

14:48:47.100 --> 14:48:48.260
All is dark.

14:48:48.800 --> 14:48:51.660
I hear lapping water level with me

14:48:51.660 --> 14:48:54.620
and some creaking as of wood on wood.

14:48:55.500 --> 14:48:58.420
She paused and the red sun shot up.

14:48:59.020 --> 14:49:00.600
We must wait till tonight.

14:49:01.600 --> 14:49:06.640
And so it is that we are travelling towards Galatzin in agony of expectation.

14:49:07.340 --> 14:49:10.460
We are due to arrive between two and three in the morning

14:49:10.460 --> 14:49:13.820
but already at Bucharest we are three hours late

14:49:13.820 --> 14:49:17.1000
so we cannot possibly get in till well after sun up.

14:49:18.420 --> 14:49:21.840
Thus we shall have two more hypnotic messages from Mrs. Harker.

14:49:23.020 --> 14:49:26.320
Either or both may possibly throw some light on what is happening.

14:49:30.060 --> 14:49:30.540
Later.

14:49:31.280 --> 14:49:32.620
Sunset is come and gone.

14:49:33.340 --> 14:49:36.060
Fortunately it came at a time when there was no distraction

14:49:36.060 --> 14:49:41.600
for had it occurred whilst we were in the station we might not have secured the necessary calm and isolation.

14:49:42.460 --> 14:49:46.640
Mrs. Harker yielded to the hypnotic influence even less readily than this morning.

14:49:47.120 --> 14:49:51.200
I am in fear that her power of reading the count sensations may die away

14:49:51.200 --> 14:49:52.920
just when we want it most.

14:49:52.920 --> 14:49:56.400
It seems to me that her imagination is beginning to work.

14:49:57.100 --> 14:50:01.940
While she has been in the trance hitherto she has confined herself to the simplest of facts.

14:50:02.680 --> 14:50:05.740
If this goes on it may ultimately mislead us.

14:50:06.020 --> 14:50:10.600
If I thought that the count's power over her would die away equally with her power of knowledge

14:50:10.600 --> 14:50:12.280
it would be a happy thought.

14:50:12.600 --> 14:50:14.940
But I am afraid that it may not be so.

14:50:16.620 --> 14:50:19.500
When she did speak her words were ignomadical.

14:50:20.620 --> 14:50:22.400
Something is going out.

14:50:22.1000 --> 14:50:25.680
I can feel it pass me like a cold wind.

14:50:26.540 --> 14:50:32.480
I can hear far off confused sounds as if men talking in strange tongues.

14:50:33.360 --> 14:50:36.340
Fierce falling water and the howling of wolves.

14:50:37.460 --> 14:50:41.280
She stopped and a shudder ran through her.

14:50:41.500 --> 14:50:47.540
Increasing in intensity for a few seconds till at the end she shook as though in a palsy.

14:50:47.540 --> 14:50:52.120
She said no more, even an answer to the professor's imperative questioning.

14:50:52.940 --> 14:50:57.180
When she woke from the trance she was cold and exhausted and languid

14:50:57.180 --> 14:50:59.160
but her mind was all alert.

14:50:59.800 --> 14:51:02.940
She could not remember anything but asked what she had said.

14:51:03.520 --> 14:51:08.740
When she was told she pondered over it deeply for a long time and in silence.

14:51:10.980 --> 14:51:13.900
30 October 7 a.m.

14:51:15.160 --> 14:51:19.460
We are near Galatz now and I may not have time to write later.

14:51:19.960 --> 14:51:26.840
Sunrise this morning was anxiously looked for by us all knowing of the increasing difficulty of procuring the hypnotic trance.

14:51:27.500 --> 14:51:30.440
Van Helsing began his passes earlier than usual.

14:51:30.740 --> 14:51:35.920
They produced no effect however until the regular time when she yielded with a still greater difficulty

14:51:35.920 --> 14:51:38.900
only a minute before the sun rose.

14:51:39.540 --> 14:51:41.1000
The professor lost no time in his questioning.

14:51:42.780 --> 14:51:45.020
Her answer came with equal quickness.

14:51:45.500 --> 14:51:46.600
All is dark.

14:51:47.160 --> 14:51:52.940
I hear water swirling by level with my ears and the creaking of wood on wood.

14:51:54.040 --> 14:51:55.720
Cattle low far off.

14:51:57.060 --> 14:52:00.420
There is another sound, a queer one like.

14:52:01.560 --> 14:52:04.780
She stopped and grew white and whiter still.

14:52:04.780 --> 14:52:11.540
Go on, go on, speak, I command you said Van Helsing in an agonized voice.

14:52:12.040 --> 14:52:18.900
At the same time there was despair in his eyes for the risen sun was reddening even Mrs. Harker's pale face.

14:52:19.500 --> 14:52:26.140
She opened her eyes and we all started as she said sweetly and seemingly with the utmost unconcern.

14:52:27.160 --> 14:52:30.800
Oh professor, why ask me to do what you know I can't?

14:52:30.840 --> 14:52:32.280
I don't remember anything.

14:52:34.320 --> 14:52:40.760
Then seeing the look of amazement on our faces she said turning from one to the other with a troubled look.

14:52:41.800 --> 14:52:43.800
What have I said? What have I done?

14:52:44.300 --> 14:52:49.920
I know nothing only that I was lying here half asleep and heard you say go on, speak, I command you.

14:52:50.400 --> 14:52:54.300
It seems so funny to hear you order me about as if I were a bad child.

14:52:56.320 --> 14:52:58.1000
Oh Madame Mina he said sadly.

14:52:58.1000 --> 14:53:10.460
It is proof, if proof be needed, of how I love and honor you when a word for your good spoken more earnest than ever can seem so strange because it is to order her whom I am proud to obey.

14:53:12.960 --> 14:53:19.640
The whistles are sounding. We are nearing Galatz. We are on fire with anxiety and eagerness.

14:53:23.200 --> 14:53:26.500
Mina Harker's Journal 30 October

14:53:27.240 --> 14:53:36.300
Mr. Morris took me to the hotel where our rooms have been ordered by telegraph, he being the one who could best be spared since he does not speak any foreign language.

14:53:37.340 --> 14:53:50.880
The forces were distributed much as they had been at Varna, except that Lord Galdeming went to the vice-consul, as his rank might serve as an immediate guarantee of some sort to the official, we being in extreme hurry.

14:53:51.960 --> 14:53:58.060
Jonathan and the two doctors went to the shipping agent to learn particulars of the arrival of the Tsarina Catherine.

14:53:59.660 --> 14:54:09.600
Later, Lord Galdeming has returned, the consul is away and the vice-consul sick, so the routine work has been attended to by a clerk.

14:54:10.360 --> 14:54:13.1000
He was very obliging and offered to do anything in his power.

14:54:17.540 --> 14:54:20.860
Jonathan Harker's Journal 30 October

14:54:20.860 --> 14:54:29.440
At nine o'clock Dr. Van Helsing, Dr. Seward Nye called on messengers Mackenzie and Steinkopf, the agents of the London firm of Hapgood.

14:54:30.040 --> 14:54:37.880
They had received a wire from London in answer to Lord Galdeming's telegraphed request, asking them to show us any civility in their power.

14:54:37.880 --> 14:54:45.640
They were more than kind and courteous and took us at once on board the Tsarina Catherine, which lay at anchor out in the river harbour.

14:54:46.100 --> 14:54:54.360
There we saw the captain, Donaldson by name, who told us of his voyage. He said that in all his life he had never had so favourable a run.

14:54:55.540 --> 14:55:02.960
Man, he said, but it made us go afraid, for we expected if we should have to pay for it with some rare piece of ill-luck so as to keep up the average.

14:55:03.340 --> 14:55:12.520
It's no candy to run from a London to the Black Sea with a wind, auntie, as though the Dale himself was blowing on your sail for any purpose, and at the time we came no spare thing.

14:55:12.960 --> 14:55:20.940
Again we were nigh a ship or pour a headland a fog fell on us and travelled with us till we were at a heavy lifted, and we looked out the Dale a thing could we see.

14:55:20.940 --> 14:55:28.880
We ran by Gibraltar with out be able to signal. Until we came to the Dardanelles we had to wait to get our permit to pass, we never were within hail o'odd.

14:55:29.180 --> 14:55:38.480
At first I inclined a slack off the sail and beat about till the fog was lifted, but whilst I thought that the Dale was mine to get us to the Black Sea quick he was like to do it, well, if he were or no.

14:55:38.780 --> 14:55:47.400
And if we had a quick voyage it would be no to our miscredit with the owners and no hurt to our traffic, and the old man who served us on purpose would be graceful to us for no hindering him.

14:55:48.340 --> 14:55:54.740
This mixture of simplicity and cunning, of superstition and commercial reasoning aroused Van Helsing, who said,

14:55:55.100 --> 14:56:00.100
Mine friend, that devil is more clever than he is thought by some, and he know when we meet his match.

14:56:01.240 --> 14:56:04.240
The skipper was not displeased with the compliment, and went on,

14:56:04.940 --> 14:56:15.500
When we got past the both thrifts the man began to grumble, some of them the Romanians came and asked me to heave overboard a big box to put on board by a queer looking old man just before we had started free in London.

14:56:15.500 --> 14:56:21.240
I hadn't seen them spare the fellow and put out the twelfth fingers when they saw him to guard them against the evil eye.

14:56:21.720 --> 14:56:24.920
Man, but the superstition of foreigners is perfectly ridiculous.

14:56:25.240 --> 14:56:33.620
I sent them about their business pretty quick, but just after the fog closed in on us I felt a wee bit as they did on our something, though I wouldn't say it was again the big box.

14:56:33.980 --> 14:56:44.460
Well on we went, and as the fog didn't let up for five days I just let the wing carry us, for if the dealer wanted us to go somewheres well he'd fetch it up a right, as if he didn't well we'd keep a sharp look out anyhow.

14:56:44.900 --> 14:56:53.340
Sure enough we had our fire away in a deep water all the time, and two days ago when the morning sun came through the fog we found ourselves just in the river opposite Calise.

14:56:53.820 --> 14:57:01.040
The Romanians went wild and wanted me right or wrong to take out the box and fling it in the river. I had to argue with them about it with a hap spike.

14:57:02.440 --> 14:57:10.980
And when the last of them rose off the deck with his head in his hand I convinced them that evil eye or no evil eye the property and the trust of my owners are better in my hands than in the river Danube.

14:57:10.980 --> 14:57:19.860
They had, mind you, taken the box and the deck ready to fling in and as if they were marked to Calise via Varna, I thought it'd lie to be to start in the port and we'd get rid of it all together.

14:57:20.160 --> 14:57:25.240
We didn't do much clearing that day and had to remain the night at anchor, but in the morning, brah, ah, re the world.

14:57:25.660 --> 14:57:31.880
An hour before sun up a man came aboard with an order written to him from England to receive a box for one Count Dracula.

14:57:31.880 --> 14:57:37.980
Sure enough the honor was all ready for his hand. He had his papers at a rate and glad I was to be rid of the darn thing.

14:57:38.360 --> 14:57:44.800
For I was beginning myself to feel uneasy about it. If the Dale did have a luggage aboard the ship I'm thinking it was not neither of them at the same.

14:57:46.240 --> 14:57:50.920
What was the name of the man who took it? asked Van Helsing with restrained eagerness.

14:57:51.980 --> 14:57:58.920
I'll be telling you quick, he answered, and stepped down to his cabin producing a receipt signed Immanuel Hiddlesliem.

14:58:00.060 --> 14:58:06.540
Burgenstraße 16 was the address. We found out this was all the captain knew, so with thanks we came away.

14:58:07.880 --> 14:58:14.840
We found Hiddlesliem in his office, a Hebrew of rather the Adelphi theta type with a nose like a sheep and a fez.

14:58:15.540 --> 14:58:21.920
His arguments were pointed with specie, we doing the punctuation, and with a little bargaining he told us what he knew.

14:58:21.920 --> 14:58:32.040
This turned out to be simple but important. He had received a letter from Mr. Deville of London telling him to receive, if possible before sunrise so as to avoid customs,

14:58:32.640 --> 14:58:42.380
a box which would arrive at Galatz and the Zarina Catherine. This he was to give in charge to a certain Petrov Skintki who dealt with the Slovaks who traded down the river to the port.

14:58:42.920 --> 14:58:48.820
He had been paid for his work by an English banknote which had been duly cashed for gold at the Danube International Bank.

14:58:48.820 --> 14:58:56.480
When Skintki had come to him he had taken him to the ship and handed over the box so as to save porterage. That was all he knew.

14:58:57.880 --> 14:59:08.480
We then sought for Skintki but weren't able to find him. One of his neighbors, who did not seem to bear him any affection, said that he had gone away two days before, no one knew whither.

14:59:08.940 --> 14:59:16.620
This was collaborated by his landlord who had received by messenger the key of the house together with the rent due, in English money.

14:59:16.620 --> 14:59:22.460
This had been between ten and eleven o'clock last night. We were at a standstill again.

14:59:23.820 --> 14:59:34.940
Whilst we were talking, one came running and breathlessly gasped out that the body of Skintki had been found inside the well of the churchyard of St. Peter and that the throat had been torn open as if by some wild animal.

14:59:35.780 --> 14:59:41.200
Those we had been speaking with ran off to see the horror, the women crying out, this is the work of a Slovak.

14:59:42.120 --> 14:59:50.440
We hurried away, lest we should have been in some way drawn into the affair and so detained. As we came home we could arrive at no definite conclusion.

14:59:51.200 --> 15:00:02.020
We were all convinced that the box was on its way by water to somewhere, but where that might be we would have to discover. With heavy hearts we came home to the hotel, to Mina.

15:00:02.020 --> 15:00:08.280
When we met together the first thing was to consult as to taking Mina again into our confidence.

15:00:09.060 --> 15:00:19.100
Things are getting desperate, and it is at least a chance, though a hazardous one, as a preliminary step, I was released from my promise to her.

15:00:22.900 --> 15:00:27.540
Mina Harker's Journal. 30 October. Evening.

15:00:28.400 --> 15:00:39.460
They were so tired and worn out and dispirited that there was nothing to be done till they had some rest, so I asked them all to lie down for a half hour whilst I should enter everything up to the moment.

15:00:40.200 --> 15:00:47.040
I feel so grateful to the man who invented the Traveller's Typewriter, and to Mr. Morris for getting this one for me.

15:00:47.600 --> 15:00:52.020
I should have felt quite astray doing the work if I had to write with a pen.

15:00:53.540 --> 15:01:01.080
It is all done. Poor, dear, dear Jonathan, what he must have suffered, what he must be suffering now.

15:01:01.700 --> 15:01:10.200
He lies on the sofa, hardly seeming to breathe, and his whole body appears in collapse. His brows are knit, his face is drawn with pain.

15:01:11.020 --> 15:01:17.940
Poor fellow. Maybe he is thinking, and I can see his face all wrinkled up with the concentration of his thoughts.

15:01:18.960 --> 15:01:23.500
Oh, if only I could help at all. I shall do what I can.

15:01:24.180 --> 15:01:28.960
I have asked Dr. Van Helsing, and he has gotten me all the papers that I have not yet seen.

15:01:29.720 --> 15:01:34.380
Whilst they are resting, I shall go over all carefully, and perhaps I may arrive at some conclusion.

15:01:34.380 --> 15:01:40.160
I shall try to follow the Professor's example and think without prejudice and the facts before me.

15:01:40.760 --> 15:01:47.220
I do believe that under God's providence I shall have made a discovery. I shall get the maps and look over them.

15:01:47.720 --> 15:01:54.1000
I am more than ever sure that I am right. My new conclusion is ready, so I shall get our party together and read it.

15:01:55.120 --> 15:01:59.760
They can judge it. It is well to be accurate, and every minute is precious.

15:02:03.060 --> 15:02:04.760
Mina Harker's Memorandum

15:02:05.460 --> 15:02:06.860
Entered in her journal

15:02:07.440 --> 15:02:12.560
Ground of inquiry. Count Dracula's problem is to get back to his own place.

15:02:13.220 --> 15:02:23.380
A. He must be brought back by someone. This is evident, for he had power to move himself as he wished he could go either as man or wolf or bat, or in some other way.

15:02:23.380 --> 15:02:33.380
B. He evidently fears discovery or interference in the state of helplessness in which he must be, confined as he is between dawn and sunset in his wooden box.

15:02:35.480 --> 15:02:44.880
B. How is he to be taken? Here a process of exclusions may help us, by road, by rail, by water.

15:02:45.800 --> 15:02:52.040
1. By road. There are endless difficulties, especially in leaving the city.

15:02:53.520 --> 15:03:04.480
X. There are people, and people are curious and investigate. A hint, a surmise, a doubt as to what might be in the box would destroy him.

15:03:05.760 --> 15:03:12.820
Y. There are, or there may be, customs and octroy officers to pass.

15:03:14.320 --> 15:03:26.460
Z. His pursuers might follow. This is his highest fear, and in order to prevent his being betrayed he has repelled, so far as he can, even his victim, me.

15:03:28.680 --> 15:03:38.960
2. By rail. There is no one in charge of the box. It would have to take its chance of being delayed and delay would be fatal with enemies on the track.

15:03:39.760 --> 15:03:51.440
True, he might escape at night. What would he be if left in a strange place with no refuge that he could fly to? This is not what he intends, and he does not mean to risk it.

15:03:52.220 --> 15:04:06.980
3. By water. Here is the safest way in one respect, but with most danger in another. On the water he is powerless, except at night. Even then he can only summon fog and storm and snow and his wolves.

15:04:06.980 --> 15:04:22.880
But were he wrecked, the living water would engulf him, helpless, and he would indeed be lost. He could have the vessel drive to land, but if it were unfriendly land wherein he was not free to move, his position would still be desperate.

15:04:24.360 --> 15:04:39.840
We know from the record that he was on the water, so what we have to do is to ascertain what water. The first thing is to realize exactly what he has done as yet. We may, then, get a light on what his task is to be.

15:04:41.320 --> 15:04:50.960
Firstly, we must differentiate between what he did in London as part of his general plan of action, when he was pressed for moments and had to arrange as best he could.

15:04:52.420 --> 15:05:09.720
Secondly, we must see, as well as we can surmise it from the facts we know of, what he has done here. As to the first, he evidently intended to arrive at Galatz, and sent invoice to Varna to deceive us lest we should ascertain his means of exit from England.

15:05:09.720 --> 15:05:28.180
His immediate and sole purpose, then, was to escape. The proof of this is the letter of instructions sent to Immanuel Heldeschim to clear and take away the box before sunrise. There is also the instruction to Petrovskinsky. These we must only guess at.

15:05:29.020 --> 15:05:46.360
But there must have been some letter or message since Ginsky came to Heldeschim, that, so far, his plans were successful, we know. The Tsarina Catherine made a phenomenally quick journey, so much, though, that Captain Donaldson's suspicions were aroused.

15:05:46.360 --> 15:06:14.200
But his superstition, united with his canniness, played the Count's game for him, and he ran with his favoring wind through fogs and all, till he brought up blindfold at Galatz. That the Count's arrangements were well made has been proved. Heldeschim cleared the box, took it off, and gave it to Skinsky. Skinsky took it, and here we lose the trail. We only know that the box is somewhere on the water, moving along. The customs and the oktroy.

15:06:14.840 --> 15:06:17.240
If there be any, have been avoided.

15:06:19.020 --> 15:06:36.180
Now we have come to what the Count must have done after his arrival, on land, at Galatz. The box was given to Skinsky before sunrise. At sunrise the Count would appear in his own form. Here we ask why Skinsky was chosen at all to aid in the work.

15:06:36.180 --> 15:06:50.740
In my husband's diary Skinsky is mentioned as dealing with the Slovaks who trade down the river to the port, and the man's remark that the murder was the work of a Slovak showed the general feeling against his class. The Count wanted isolation.

15:06:52.160 --> 15:07:15.400
My surmise is this, that in London the Count decided to get back to his castle by water, as the most safe and secret way. He was brought from the Canskill by Skizgani, and probably they delivered their cargo to Slovaks who took the boxes to Varna, for there they were shipped to London, lest the Count had knowledge of the persons who could arrange the service.

15:07:15.400 --> 15:07:33.380
When the box was on land before sunrise or after sunset, he came out from his box, met Skinsky and instructed him what to do as to arranging the carriage of the box up some river. When this was done and he knew that all was in train, he blotted out his traces, as he thought, by murdering his agent.

15:07:35.280 --> 15:07:52.960
I have examined the map and find that the river most suitable for the Slovaks to have ascended is either the Pruth or the Sarath. I read in the typescript that in my trance I heard cows low and water swirling level with my ears in the creaking of wood.

15:07:52.960 --> 15:08:06.900
The Count, in his box then, was on a river in an open boat, propelled probably either by oars or poles, for the banks were near and was working it against stream. There would be no such a floating downstream.

15:08:06.900 --> 15:08:30.160
Of course, it may not be either the Sarath or the Pruth, but we may possibly investigate further. Now of these two, the Pruth is the most easily navigated, but the Sarath is, at Fundu, joined by the Bistritza, which runs up round the Borgo Pass. The loop it makes is manifestly as close to Dracula's castle as can be got by water.

15:08:33.460 --> 15:08:36.480
Mina Harker's Journal

15:08:36.480 --> 15:08:37.1000
Continued

15:08:38.560 --> 15:09:04.300
When I had done reading, Jonathan took me in his arms and kissed me. The others kept shaking me by both hands, and Dr. Van Helsing said, Our dear Madam Mina is once more our teacher. Her eyes have been where we were blinded. Now we are on the track once again, and this time we may succeed. Our enemy is at his most helpless, and if we can come on him by day, on the water, our task will be over.

15:09:04.300 --> 15:09:26.120
He has a start, but he is powerless to hasten, as he may not leave his box lest those who carry him may suspect. For them to suspect would be to prompt them to throw him in this stream where he perish. This he knows and will not. Now, men, to our council of war, for here and now we must plan what each and all shall do.

15:09:27.060 --> 15:09:31.880
I shall get a steam-launch, and follow him, said Lord Galdeming.

15:09:33.340 --> 15:09:38.660
And I, horses to follow on the bank, lest he chance to land, said Mr. Morris.

15:09:39.460 --> 15:09:59.280
Good, said the professor. Both good, but neither must go alone. There must be force to overcome force if need be. The Slovak is strong and rough, and he carries rude arms. All the men smiled, for amongst them they carried a small arsenal, said Mr. Morris.

15:09:59.280 --> 15:10:16.540
I have brought some Winchesters. They are pretty, handy in a crowd, and there may be wolves. The Count, if you remember, took some other precautions. He made some requisitions on others that Mrs. Harker could not quite hear or understand. We must be ready at all points.

15:10:17.780 --> 15:10:19.240
Dr. Seward said,

15:10:20.540 --> 15:10:22.680
I think I had better go with Quincy.

15:10:23.640 --> 15:10:28.820
We have been accustomed to hunt together, and we too, well armed, will be a match for whatever may come along.

15:10:28.820 --> 15:10:47.980
You must not be alone, Art. It may be necessary to fight the Slovaks, and a chance thrust, for I don't suppose these fellows carry guns, would undo all our plans. There must be no chances this time. We shall not rest until the Count's head and body have been separated, and we are sure that he cannot reincarnate.

15:10:48.740 --> 15:11:12.380
He looked at Jonathan as he spoke, and Jonathan looked at me. I could see that the poor dear was torn about in his mind. Of course he wanted to be with me, but then the Boat Service would, most likely, be the one that would destroy the, the vampire. Why did I hesitate to write the word?

15:11:14.080 --> 15:11:18.740
He was silent a while, and during his silence Dr. Van Helsing spoke,

15:11:19.780 --> 15:11:42.180
Friend Jonathan, this is to you for twice reasons. First because you are young and brave and can fight, and all the energies may be needed at the last. And again that it is your right to destroy him, that which has wrought such a row to you and others. Be not afraid for Madame Mina. She will be my care, if I may. I am old.

15:11:42.380 --> 15:11:58.120
My legs are not so quick to run as once, and I am not used to ride so long or pursue as need be, or to fight with lethal weapons. But I can be of other service. I can fight another way, and I can die if need be as well as younger men.

15:11:58.900 --> 15:12:16.920
Now let me say that what I would is this. While you, my Lord Galdeming, and Friend Jonathan go in your so swift little steamboat up the river, and whilst John and Quincy guard the bank where perchance he might be landed, I will take Madame Mina right into the heart of the enemy's country.

15:12:16.920 --> 15:12:36.540
Whilst the old fox is tied in his boat, floating on the running stream whence he cannot escape to land, where he dares not raise the lid of his coffin box lest his Slovak carrier should in fear leave him to perish, we shall go in the track where Jonathan went, from bestriets over the Borgo and find our way to the Castle of Dracula.

15:12:36.540 --> 15:12:55.540
Here Madame Mina's hypnotic power will surely help, and we shall find our way. All dark and unknown otherwise, after the first sunset we are near that fateful place. There is much to be done and other places to be made sanctified so that the nest of the vipers be obliterated.

15:12:56.280 --> 15:12:59.1000
Here, Jonathan interrupted him hotly.

15:13:00.120 --> 15:13:13.100
Do you mean to say, Professor Van Helsing, that you would bring Mina, in her sad case and tainted as she is with the devil's illness, right into the jaws of his death trap? Not for the world, not for heaven or hell.

15:13:14.260 --> 15:13:18.180
He became almost speechless for a minute, and then went on.

15:13:19.760 --> 15:13:21.960
Do you know what that place is?

15:13:22.920 --> 15:13:41.060
Have you seen that awful den of hellish infamy, with the very moonlight alive with grisly shapes and every speck of dust that whirls in the wind a devouring monster and embryo? Have you felt the vampire's lips upon your throat?

15:13:43.160 --> 15:13:49.940
Here he turned to me, and as his eyes lit on my forehead he threw up his arms with a cry.

15:13:50.920 --> 15:13:55.440
Oh my God! What have we done to have this terror upon us?

15:13:56.280 --> 15:13:59.600
And he sank down on the sofa in a collapse of misery.

15:14:01.940 --> 15:14:09.340
The professor's voice, as he spoke in clear sweet tones which seemed to vibrate in the air, calmed us all.

15:14:09.980 --> 15:14:23.920
Oh my friend, it is because I would save Madame Mina from this awful place that I would go. God forbid that I should take her into that place. There is work, wild work, to be done before that place can be purified.

15:14:24.760 --> 15:14:45.540
Remember that we are in terrible straits. If the Count escape us this time, and he is strong and subtle and cunning, he may choose to sleep him for a century, and then at that time our dear one, he took my hand, would come to him to keep him company, and would be as those others that you, Jonathan, saw.

15:14:45.540 --> 15:15:01.700
You have told us of their gloating lips. You heard their ribald laugh as they clutched the moving bag that the Count threw to them. You shudder, and well may it be. Forgive me that I make you so much pain, but it is necessary.

15:15:01.700 --> 15:15:15.920
My friend, is it not a dire need for that which I am giving, possibly my life? If it were that anyone went into that place to stay, it is I who would have to go to keep them company.

15:15:18.140 --> 15:15:26.260
Do as you will, said Jonathan, with a sob that shook him all over. We are in the hands of God.

15:15:28.760 --> 15:15:30.160
Later.

15:15:31.020 --> 15:15:49.420
Oh, it did me good to see the way that these brave men worked. How can women help loving men when they were so earnest and so true and so brave? And, too, it made me think of the wonderful power of money. What can it not do when basely used?

15:15:49.420 --> 15:16:07.680
I felt so thankful that Lord Galdiming is rich, and both he and Mr. Morris, who also has plenty of money, are willing to spend it so freely, for if they did not our little expedition could not start, either so promptly or so well equipped as it will within another hour.

15:16:07.680 --> 15:16:30.160
It is not three hours since it was arranged what part each of us was to do, and now Lord Galdiming and Jonathan have a lovely steam-launch with steam up ready to start at a moment's notice. Dr. Seward and Mr. Morris have half a dozen good horses, well appointed. We all have the maps and appliances of various kinds that can be had.

15:16:31.120 --> 15:16:51.400
Professor Van Helsing and I are to leave by the eleven-forty train tonight for Fresti, where we are to get a carriage to drive to the Borgo Pass. We are bringing a great deal of ready money, as we are to buy a carriage and horses. We shall drive ourselves, for we have no one whom we can trust in the matter.

15:16:51.980 --> 15:17:13.500
The Professor knows something of a great many languages, so we shall get on all right. We have all got arms, even for me a large bore revolver. Jonathan would not be happy unless I was armed like the rest. Alas, I cannot carry one arm that the rest do. The scar on my forehead forbids that.

15:17:15.540 --> 15:17:28.080
Dear Dr. Van Helsing comforts me by telling me that I am fully armed as there may be wolves. The weather is getting colder every hour, and there are snow flurries which come and go as warnings.

15:17:30.240 --> 15:17:37.340
Later. It took all my courage to say goodbye to my darling. We may never meet again.

15:17:39.260 --> 15:17:51.340
Courage, Mina. The Professor is looking at you keenly. His look is a warning. There must be no tears now, lest it may be that God will let them fall in gladness.

15:17:55.260 --> 15:17:59.760
Jonathan Harker's Journal. 30 October. Night.

15:18:00.820 --> 15:18:14.680
I am writing this in the light from the furnace door of the steam-launch. Lord Galdeming is firing up. He is an experienced hand at the work, as he has had for years a launch of his own on the Thames and another on the Norfolk broads.

15:18:14.680 --> 15:18:27.500
Regarding our plans, we finally decided that Mina's guess was correct, and that if any waterway was chosen for the Count's escape back to his castle, the Sareth, and then the Bistritzad, its junction, would be the one.

15:18:28.320 --> 15:18:37.680
We took it, that somewhere about the 47th degree north latitude would be the place chosen for the crossing, the country between the river and the Carpathians.

15:18:38.340 --> 15:18:47.1000
We have no fear in running a good speed up the river at night. There is plenty of water, and the banks are wide enough apart to make steaming, even in the dark, easy enough.

15:18:48.880 --> 15:19:03.100
Lord Galdeming tells me to sleep for a while, as it is enough for the present for one to be on watch. But I cannot sleep. How can I with the terrible danger hanging over my darling, and her going out into that awful place?

15:19:04.060 --> 15:19:13.120
My only comfort is that we are in the hands of God. Only for that faith it would be easier to die than to live, and so be quit of all the trouble.

15:19:14.340 --> 15:19:26.440
Mr. Morris and Dr. Steward were off on their long ride before we started. They are to keep up the right bank, far enough off to get on higher lands where they can see a good stretch of river and avoid the following of its curves.

15:19:27.300 --> 15:19:34.940
They have, for the first stages, two men to ride and lead their spare horses, four in all, so as not to excite curiosity.

15:19:37.460 --> 15:19:54.660
When they dismiss the men, which shall be shortly, they shall themselves look after the horses. It may be necessary for us to join forces. If so, they can mount our whole party. One of the saddles has a movable horn and can be easily adapted for Mina, if required.

15:19:56.440 --> 15:20:11.440
It is a wild adventure we are on. Here, as we are rushing on through the darkness, with the cold from the river seeming to rise up and strike us, with all the mysterious voices of the night around us, it all comes home.

15:20:12.160 --> 15:20:22.600
We seem to be drifting into unknown places and unknown ways, into a whole world of dark and dreadful things. Valdeming is shutting the furnace door.

15:20:25.400 --> 15:20:26.940
31. October

15:20:27.920 --> 15:20:33.900
Still hurrying along. The day has come and Valdeming is sleeping. I am on watch.

15:20:34.800 --> 15:20:48.500
The morning is bitterly cold. The furnace heat is grateful, though we have heavy fur coats. As yet we have passed only a few open boats, but none of them had on board any box or package of anything like the size of the one we seek.

15:20:49.620 --> 15:20:56.080
The men were scared every time we turned our electric lamp on them, and fell on their knees and prayed.

15:20:58.620 --> 15:20:59.920
1. November

15:21:01.420 --> 15:21:12.860
Evening. No news all day. We have found nothing of the kind we seek. We have now passed into the Bistritza, and if we are wrong in our surmise, our chance is gone.

15:21:13.800 --> 15:21:32.840
We have overhauled every boat, big and little. Early this morning one crew took us for a government boat and treated us accordingly. We saw in this a way of smoothing matters, so at Fundu, where the Bistritza runs into the Sareth, we got a Romanian flag which we now fly conspicuously.

15:21:33.880 --> 15:21:44.440
With every boat which we have overhauled since then, this trick has succeeded. We have had every deference shown to us, and not once any objection to whatever we chose to ask or do.

15:21:45.140 --> 15:21:59.120
Some of the Slovaks tell us that a big boat passed them, going at more than usual speed as she had a double crew on board. This was before they came to Fundu, so they could not tell us whether the boat turned into the Bistritza or continued up on the Sareth.

15:21:59.880 --> 15:22:13.940
At Fundu we could not hear of any such boat, so she must have passed there in the night. I am feeling very sleepy. The cold is perhaps beginning to tell upon me, and nature must have rest some time.

15:22:15.760 --> 15:22:23.080
Galdeming insists that he shall keep the first watch. God bless him for all his goodness to poor dear Mina and me.

15:22:25.260 --> 15:22:37.160
2. November. Morning. It is broad daylight. That good fellow would not wake me. He says it would have been a sin too, for I slept peacefully and was forgetting my trouble.

15:22:38.120 --> 15:22:45.920
It seems brutally selfish to me to have slept so long and let him watch all night, but he was quite right. I am a new man this morning.

15:22:45.920 --> 15:22:57.680
And as I sit here and watch him sleeping, I can do all that is necessary both as to minding the engines, steering and keeping watch. I can feel that my strength and energy are coming back to me.

15:22:58.440 --> 15:23:13.620
I wonder where Mina is now, and Van Helsing. They should have got to Varetsi about noon on Wednesday. It would take them some time to get the carriage and the horses, so if they had started and travelled hard, they would be about now at the Borgo Pass.

15:23:14.440 --> 15:23:29.940
God guide and help them. I am afraid to think what may happen. If we could only go faster, but we cannot. The engines are throbbing and doing the rut most. I wonder how Dr. Steward and Mr. Morris are getting on.

15:23:30.420 --> 15:23:41.360
There seem to be endless streams running down the mountains into this river, but as none of them are very large, at present, at all events, though they are doubtless terrible in winter and when the snow melts.

15:23:42.660 --> 15:23:56.360
The horsemen may not have met much obstruction. I hope that before we get to Straspa, we may see them, for if by that time we have not overtaken the count, it may be necessary to take counsel together what to do next.

15:23:59.240 --> 15:24:02.340
Dr. Steward's Diary

15:24:02.340 --> 15:24:03.920
2 November

15:24:04.720 --> 15:24:24.1000
Three days on the road. No news and no time to write it if there had been, for every moment is precious. We have had only the rest needful for the horses, but we are bearing it wonderfully. Those adventurous days of ours are turning up useful. We must push on. We shall never feel happy till we get the launch in sight again.

15:24:27.300 --> 15:24:28.340
3 November

15:24:28.340 --> 15:24:43.600
We heard at Fundu that the launch had gone up the Bistritsa. I wish it wasn't so cold. There are signs of snow coming, and if it falls heavy it will stop us. In such case we must get a sledge and go on, Russian fashion.

15:24:45.840 --> 15:24:46.880
4 November

15:24:47.640 --> 15:25:06.620
Today we heard of the launch having been detained by an accident when trying to force away up the rapids. The Slovak boats get up all right by aid of a rope and steering with knowledge. Some went up only a few hours before. Guldeming is an amateur fitter himself and evidently it was he who put the launch in trim again.

15:25:08.280 --> 15:25:28.1000
Finally they got up the rapids all right with local help and are off on the chase afresh. I fear that the boat is not any better for the accident. Peasantry tell us that after she got upon the smooth water again she kept stopping every now and again, so long as she was in sight. We must push on harder than ever. Our help may be wanted soon.

15:25:31.480 --> 15:25:34.360
Minna Harker's Journal

15:25:34.500 --> 15:25:36.300
31 October

15:25:37.220 --> 15:26:02.620
Arrived at Varetsy at noon. The professor tells me that this morning at dawn he could hardly hypnotize me at all, and all that I could say was dark and quiet. He is off now buying a carriage and horses. He says that he will later on try to buy additional horses that we may be able to change them on the way. We have something more than seventy miles before us.

15:26:03.560 --> 15:26:32.280
The country is lovely and most interesting. If only we were under different conditions how delightful it would be to see it all. If Jonathan and I were driving through it alone what a pleasure it would be to stop and see people and learn something of their life and to fill our minds and memories with all the color and picturesqueness of the whole wide beautiful country and the quaint people.

15:26:32.620 --> 15:26:34.840
But alas!

15:26:36.240 --> 15:26:36.760
Later.

15:26:37.880 --> 15:26:53.320
Dr. Van Helsing has returned. He has got the carriage and horses. We are to have some dinner and to start in an hour. The landlady is putting us up a huge basket of provisions. It seems enough for a company of soldiers.

15:26:54.060 --> 15:27:10.520
The professor encourages her and whispers to me that it may be a week before we get any food again. He has been shopping too and has sent home such a wonderful lot of fur coats and wraps and all sorts of warm things. There will not be any chance of our being cold.

15:27:11.900 --> 15:27:29.700
We shall soon be off. I am afraid to think what may happen to us. We are truly in the hands of God. He alone knows what may be and I pray him with all the strength of my sad and humble soul that he will watch over my beloved husband.

15:27:29.700 --> 15:27:41.160
That whatever may happen, Jonathan may know that I loved him and honored him more than I can say and that my latest and truest thought will always be for him.

15:27:59.700 --> 15:28:02.460
Biscuit West, Prince Edward Island

15:28:30.100 --> 15:28:33.380
DRACULA by Bram Stoker

15:28:41.040 --> 15:28:43.180
Mina Harker's Journal

15:28:43.180 --> 15:28:44.980
1. November

15:28:46.280 --> 15:28:48.600
All day long we have traveled,

15:28:49.640 --> 15:28:51.020
and at a good speed.

15:28:52.120 --> 15:28:58.080
The horses seem to know that they are being kindly treated, for they go willingly their full stage at best speed.

15:28:58.780 --> 15:29:06.760
We have now had so many changes and find the same thing so constantly that we are encouraged to think that the journey will be an easy one.

15:29:08.180 --> 15:29:10.200
Dr. Van Helsing is laconic.

15:29:11.480 --> 15:29:14.660
He tells the farmers that he is hurrying to Bistritz,

15:29:15.680 --> 15:29:18.160
and pays them well to make the exchange of horses.

15:29:19.340 --> 15:29:23.000
We get hot soup, or coffee, or tea, and off we go.

15:29:23.920 --> 15:29:25.780
It is a lovely country,

15:29:26.700 --> 15:29:29.820
full of beauties of all imaginable kinds,

15:29:31.000 --> 15:29:34.480
and the people are brave and strong and simple,

15:29:35.620 --> 15:29:37.560
and seem full of nice qualities.

15:29:38.560 --> 15:29:41.700
They are very, very superstitious.

15:29:42.900 --> 15:29:47.580
In the first house where we stopped when the woman who served us saw the scar on my forehead,

15:29:48.720 --> 15:29:53.380
she crossed herself and put out two fingers toward me to keep off the evil eye.

15:29:54.080 --> 15:29:58.640
I believe they went to the trouble of putting an extra amount of garlic into our food,

15:29:59.220 --> 15:30:01.240
and I can't abide garlic.

15:30:02.540 --> 15:30:06.340
Ever since then I have taken care not to take off my hat or veil,

15:30:07.360 --> 15:30:09.240
and so have escaped their suspicions.

15:30:10.780 --> 15:30:14.620
We are traveling fast, and as we have no driver with us to carry tails,

15:30:15.420 --> 15:30:16.820
we go ahead of scandal,

15:30:17.740 --> 15:30:22.760
but I dare say that fear of the evil eye will follow hard behind us all the way.

15:30:24.200 --> 15:30:26.320
The professor seems tireless.

15:30:27.400 --> 15:30:31.540
All day he would not take any rest, though he made me sleep for a long spell.

15:30:32.940 --> 15:30:36.820
At sunset time he hypnotized me, and he says I answered as usual.

15:30:38.160 --> 15:30:41.020
Darkness, lapping water, and creaking wood.

15:30:42.860 --> 15:30:44.660
So our enemy is still on the river.

15:30:45.400 --> 15:30:47.840
I am afraid to think of Jonathan,

15:30:49.020 --> 15:30:53.500
but somehow I have now no fear for him or for myself.

15:30:54.680 --> 15:30:58.500
I write this whilst we wait in a farmhouse for the horses to be ready.

15:30:59.720 --> 15:31:01.540
Dr. Van Helsing is sleeping.

15:31:02.680 --> 15:31:07.120
Poor dear, he looks very tired and old and gray,

15:31:08.480 --> 15:31:11.860
but his mouth is set as firmly as a conqueror's.

15:31:12.620 --> 15:31:15.660
Even in his sleep he is intense with resolution.

15:31:17.120 --> 15:31:20.340
When we have started I must make him rest whilst I drive.

15:31:21.840 --> 15:31:24.120
I shall tell him that we have days before us,

15:31:24.120 --> 15:31:28.000
and he must not break down when most of all his strength will be needed.

15:31:29.340 --> 15:31:30.460
All is ready.

15:31:31.440 --> 15:31:33.040
We are off shortly.

15:31:36.320 --> 15:31:38.540
2. November. Morning.

15:31:40.240 --> 15:31:44.960
I was successful, and we took turns driving all night.

15:31:45.820 --> 15:31:49.920
Now the day is on us, bright though cold.

15:31:51.140 --> 15:31:54.640
There is a strange heaviness in the air.

15:31:55.780 --> 15:31:58.520
I say heaviness for one of a better word.

15:31:59.880 --> 15:32:01.960
I mean that it oppresses us both.

15:32:03.100 --> 15:32:06.820
It is very cold, and only our warm furs keep us comfortable.

15:32:07.700 --> 15:32:10.840
At dawn Van Helsing hypnotized me.

15:32:11.800 --> 15:32:16.820
He says I answered darkness, creaking wood and roaring water,

15:32:18.140 --> 15:32:20.480
so the river is changing as they ascend.

15:32:22.120 --> 15:32:25.700
I do hope that my darling will not run any chance of danger,

15:32:26.720 --> 15:32:30.740
more than need be, but we are in God's hands.

15:32:34.340 --> 15:32:36.900
2. November. Night.

15:32:38.960 --> 15:32:40.440
All day long driving.

15:32:41.780 --> 15:32:46.400
The country gets wilder as we go, and the great spurs of the Carpathians,

15:32:47.780 --> 15:32:52.160
which at Varetsi seem so far from us and so low on the horizon,

15:32:53.300 --> 15:32:56.320
now seem to gather round us and tower in front.

15:32:57.760 --> 15:32:59.720
We both seem in good spirits.

15:33:00.280 --> 15:33:03.000
I think we make an effort to cheer the other.

15:33:03.220 --> 15:33:05.280
In the doing so, we cheer ourselves.

15:33:06.820 --> 15:33:10.780
Dr. Van Helsing says that by morning we shall reach the Borgo Pass.

15:33:12.380 --> 15:33:16.840
The houses are very few here now, and the Professor says that the last horse we got

15:33:16.840 --> 15:33:21.540
will have to go on with us, as we may not be able to change.

15:33:23.020 --> 15:33:28.060
He got two in addition to the two we changed, so that now we have a rude four in hand.

15:33:29.060 --> 15:33:32.820
The dear horses are patient and good and give us no trouble.

15:33:34.420 --> 15:33:37.880
We are not worried with other travelers, and so even I can drive.

15:33:39.360 --> 15:33:41.220
We shall get to the pass in daylight.

15:33:42.200 --> 15:33:44.020
We do not want to arrive before.

15:33:45.440 --> 15:33:48.640
So we take it easy and have each a long rest in turn.

15:33:50.340 --> 15:33:52.300
Oh, what will tomorrow bring us?

15:33:53.120 --> 15:33:57.400
We go to seek the place where my poor darling suffered so much.

15:33:58.520 --> 15:34:02.880
God grant that we may be guided aright and he will deign to watch over my husband

15:34:02.880 --> 15:34:07.500
and those dear to us both, and who are in such deadly peril.

15:34:09.160 --> 15:34:13.240
As for me, I am not worthy in his sight.

15:34:14.920 --> 15:34:20.960
Alas, I am unclean to his eyes and shall be until he may dine

15:34:20.960 --> 15:34:27.400
and let me stand forth in his sight as one of those who have not incurred his wrath.

15:34:38.940 --> 15:34:43.040
This to my old and true friend John Seward M.D.

15:34:44.240 --> 15:34:48.480
Of Purefeet London, in case I may not see him, it may explain.

15:34:48.480 --> 15:34:54.980
It is morning and I write by a fire which all night I have kept alive Madam Mina aiding me.

15:34:55.880 --> 15:35:02.020
It is cold, cold, so cold that the gray heavy sky is full of snow

15:35:02.020 --> 15:35:07.600
which when it falls will settle for all winter as the ground is hardening to receive it.

15:35:08.120 --> 15:35:10.400
It seems to have affected Madam Mina.

15:35:10.940 --> 15:35:15.200
She has been so heavy of head all day. She is not like herself.

15:35:15.200 --> 15:35:22.600
She sleeps and sleeps and sleeps. She who is usual so alert have done literally nothing all the day.

15:35:23.040 --> 15:35:27.580
She even have lost her appetite. She make no entry into her little diary.

15:35:28.300 --> 15:35:31.100
She who writes so faithful every pause.

15:35:32.400 --> 15:35:35.220
Something whisper to me that all is not well.

15:35:36.040 --> 15:35:42.920
However, tonight she is more vee. Her long sleep all day have refreshed and restore her.

15:35:42.920 --> 15:35:46.300
For now she is all sweet and bright as ever.

15:35:46.760 --> 15:35:52.900
At sunset I try to hypnotize her, but alas with no effect.

15:35:54.540 --> 15:36:00.380
The power has grown less and less with each day and tonight it fail me altogether.

15:36:01.800 --> 15:36:07.920
Well, God's will be done whatever it may be and with so ever it may lead.

15:36:10.180 --> 15:36:16.000
Now, to the historical. For as Madam Mina write not in her stenography,

15:36:16.560 --> 15:36:22.600
I must in my coolest old fashion so that each day of us may not go unrecorded.

15:36:23.960 --> 15:36:28.380
We got to the Borgo Pass just after sunrise yesterday morning.

15:36:29.520 --> 15:36:33.340
When I saw the signs of the dawn I got ready for the hypnotism.

15:36:34.220 --> 15:36:38.240
We stopped our carriage and got down so that there might be no disturbance.

15:36:39.600 --> 15:36:45.360
I made a couch of furs and Madam Mina, lying down, yielded herself as usual,

15:36:45.840 --> 15:36:49.720
but more slow and more short time than ever to the hypnotic sleep.

15:36:50.660 --> 15:36:56.280
As before came the answer. Darkness and the swirling of water.

15:36:57.320 --> 15:37:04.120
Then she awoke, bright and radiant, and we go on our way and soon reach the pass.

15:37:05.120 --> 15:37:11.400
At this time and place she became on fire with zeal, some new guiding power being her manifested,

15:37:12.160 --> 15:37:16.320
for she point to a road and say, This is the way.

15:37:17.520 --> 15:37:24.400
How you know it, I ask. Of course I know it, she answer, and with a pause add,

15:37:24.400 --> 15:37:28.620
Have not my Jonathan travelled it and wrote of his travel?

15:37:29.800 --> 15:37:35.620
At first I think somewhat strange, but soon I see there be only one such by-road.

15:37:36.260 --> 15:37:41.620
It is used by little and very different from the couch-road from the book Vainat de Bistrich,

15:37:42.200 --> 15:37:44.860
which is more wide and hard and more of use.

15:37:45.920 --> 15:37:52.500
So we come down this road, where we meet other ways not always where we sure that there are roads at all,

15:37:52.500 --> 15:37:58.440
for they be neglect and light snow fall, the horses know and they only.

15:37:59.160 --> 15:38:02.100
I give rein to them and they go on so patient.

15:38:03.360 --> 15:38:08.620
By and by we find all the things which Jonathan have note in that wonderful diary of him.

15:38:09.680 --> 15:38:13.620
Then we go on for long, long hours and hours.

15:38:14.620 --> 15:38:20.340
At the first I tell Madame Mina to sleep. She try and she succeed.

15:38:21.060 --> 15:38:28.920
She sleep all the time, till at last I feel myself too suspicious grow and attempt to wake her.

15:38:29.400 --> 15:38:33.700
But she sleep on, and I may not wake her, though I try.

15:38:34.680 --> 15:38:44.040
I do not wish to try too hard, lest I harm her, for I know that she suffer much, and sleep at times be all in all to her.

15:38:45.580 --> 15:38:52.760
I think I drowse myself, for all the sudden I feel guilt, as though I have done something.

15:38:53.680 --> 15:39:02.320
I find myself bolt up with the reins in my hand, and the good horses go along, jog, jog, just as ever.

15:39:03.780 --> 15:39:07.460
I look down and find Madame Mina still asleep.

15:39:08.620 --> 15:39:16.960
It is now not far off since that time, and o'er the snow the light of the snow and follow in big yellow flood,

15:39:17.800 --> 15:39:22.380
so that we throw great long shadow on where the mountain rise so steep.

15:39:23.560 --> 15:39:31.380
For we are going up and up, and all is so wild and rocky, as though it were the end of the world.

15:39:33.720 --> 15:39:35.960
Then I arouse Madame Mina.

15:39:37.280 --> 15:39:42.540
This time she wake with not much trouble, and then I try to put her to hypnotic sleep.

15:39:43.240 --> 15:39:46.540
But she sleep not, being as though I were not.

15:39:47.320 --> 15:39:52.460
Still I try and try, till all at once I find her and myself in the dark.

15:39:53.340 --> 15:39:56.880
Still I look round and find that the sun has gone down.

15:39:58.080 --> 15:40:01.560
Madame Mina laugh, and I turn and look at her.

15:40:02.360 --> 15:40:11.940
She is now quite awake, and looks so well as I never saw her since that night at Carfax, when we first enter the Count's house.

15:40:14.420 --> 15:40:24.000
I am amazed, and all is then, but she is so bright and tender and thoughtful to me, that I forget all fear.

15:40:24.000 --> 15:40:28.340
I lie afire, for we have brought supply of wood with us.

15:40:28.720 --> 15:40:34.300
She prepare food while I undo the horses and set them tether and shelter to feed.

15:40:35.540 --> 15:40:39.060
Then, when I return to the fire, she have my supper ready.

15:40:39.800 --> 15:40:47.400
I go to help her, but she smile and tell me that she have eaten already, that she was so hungry that she would not wait.

15:40:49.080 --> 15:40:52.560
I lack it not, and I have grave doubts.

15:40:53.240 --> 15:40:57.920
But I fear to fright her, and so am silent of it.

15:40:59.960 --> 15:41:09.840
She help me, and I eat alone, and then we wrap in fur and lie beside the fire, and I tell her to sleep while I watch.

15:41:12.340 --> 15:41:26.300
But presently, I forget all of washing, and when I sudden remember that I wash, I hide her, lying quiet but awake, and looking me with sober eyes.

15:41:27.320 --> 15:41:34.040
Once, twice more the same occur, and I get much sleep to before morning.

15:41:35.940 --> 15:41:44.780
When I wake, I try to hypnotize her, but alas, though she shut her eyes obedient, she may not sleep.

15:41:47.340 --> 15:41:56.380
The sun rise up, and up, and up, and then sleep come to her too late, but so heavy that she will not wake.

15:41:57.160 --> 15:42:05.610
I have to lift her up, and face her sleeping in the carriage where I've harnessed the horses and made all ready.

15:42:08.340 --> 15:42:17.320
Madam still sleep, and she look in her sleep more healthy and more redder than before, and I lack it not.

15:42:18.400 --> 15:42:28.560
And I am afraid, afraid, afraid, I am afraid of all the things, even to think that I must go on my way.

15:42:29.880 --> 15:42:37.420
The stake we pay floor is life and death, or more than these, and we must not flinch.

15:42:41.720 --> 15:42:44.520
5. November, morning

15:42:45.900 --> 15:43:03.620
Let me be accurate in everything, for though you and I have seen strange things together, you may first think that I, then Helsing, am mad, that the many horrors and the so long strain on nerves had at last turned my brain.

15:43:04.740 --> 15:43:14.950
All yesterday we travel, always getting closer to the mountains, and moving into a more and more wild and desert land,

15:43:15.730 --> 15:43:24.950
where are great frowning precipices, and mush falling water, and nature seemed to have held some time her carnival.

15:43:26.770 --> 15:43:36.730
Madam Mina still sleep and sleep, and though I did not have hunger and appeased it, I could not wake her, even for food.

15:43:38.630 --> 15:43:48.870
I began to fear the fatal spell of the place was upon her, tainted as she is with a vampire baptism.

15:43:50.810 --> 15:44:00.850
Well, said I to myself, if it be that she sleep all day, it shall also be that I do not sleep at night.

15:44:01.970 --> 15:44:12.070
As we travel on the rough road, for a road of an ancient and imperfect kind there was, I held down my head and slept.

15:44:13.870 --> 15:44:28.450
Again I wake with a sense of guilt, and of time pass, and found Madam Mina still sleeping, and the sun low down, but all was indeed changed.

15:44:29.330 --> 15:44:42.250
The frowning mountains seemed further away, and we were near the top of a steep rising hill, on summit of which was such a castle that Jonathan told of in his diary.

15:44:43.390 --> 15:44:53.550
At once I exhausted and feared. For now, for good or ill, the end was near.

15:44:55.010 --> 15:45:02.650
I woke Madam Mina and again tried to hypnotize her, but alas, unavailing till too late.

15:45:03.990 --> 15:45:17.750
Then, e'er the dark come upon us, for even after down the sun the heavens reflected the golden sun on the snow, and all was for a time in a great twilight.

15:45:19.070 --> 15:45:24.390
I shook out the horses and fed them in what shelter I could.

15:45:24.970 --> 15:45:34.850
Then I make a fire, and near it I make Madam Mina, now awake and more charming than ever, sit comfortable amid her rugs.

15:45:35.830 --> 15:45:41.750
I had ready food, but she would not eat, simply saying that she had not hunger.

15:45:41.750 --> 15:45:51.990
I did not press her, knowing her unavailingness, but I myself eat, for I must needs now be strong for all.

15:45:53.370 --> 15:46:02.950
Then, with the fear on me of what might be, I drew a ring so big for her comfort, around where Madam Mina sat.

15:46:04.310 --> 15:46:11.590
And o'er the ring I passed some of the weafer, in baroque fine, so that all was well guarded.

15:46:12.550 --> 15:46:16.730
She sat still all the time, so still as one dead.

15:46:18.350 --> 15:46:25.390
And she grew whiter and whiter till the snow was not more pale, and no water, she said.

15:46:25.390 --> 15:46:36.170
But when I drew near she clung to me, and I could know that the poor soul shook her from head to feet with a tremor that was pain to feel.

15:46:38.790 --> 15:46:49.110
I said to her presently, when she had grown more quiet, Will you not come over to the fire, for I wished to make a test of what she could.

15:46:49.110 --> 15:46:56.190
She rose obedient, but when she made a step she stopped, and stood as one stricken.

15:46:58.130 --> 15:47:05.650
Why not go on, I asked. She shook her head, and coming back sat down in her place.

15:47:06.530 --> 15:47:16.370
Then, looking at me with open eyes, as of one waked from sleep, I cannot, and remained silent.

15:47:16.370 --> 15:47:23.570
I rejoiced, for I knew that what she could not, none of those that we dreaded could.

15:47:24.430 --> 15:47:28.810
Though there might be danger to her body, yet her soul was safe.

15:47:31.190 --> 15:47:38.650
Presently the horses began to scream, and tore at their tethers till I came to them and quieted them.

15:47:39.390 --> 15:47:48.970
When they did feel my hands on them, they whinnied low as in joy, and licked at my hands and were quiet for a time.

15:47:50.350 --> 15:48:02.430
Many times, through the night, I come to them, till they arrive at the cold hour when all nature is at its lowest, and every time my coming was quiet to them.

15:48:02.430 --> 15:48:17.370
In the cold hour the fire began to die, and I was the best stepping forth to replenish it, for now the snow came in flying sweeps, and with it a chill mist.

15:48:20.450 --> 15:48:35.610
Even in the dark there was light of some kind, as the river is over snow, and it seemed as though the snow flurries and the wreaths of mist took shape as of women with trailing garments.

15:48:36.970 --> 15:48:45.430
All was in dead grim silence, only that the horses whinnied and cowered as if in terror of the worst.

15:48:46.450 --> 15:48:58.910
I began to fear, horrible fears, but then came to me this sense of safety in the ring wherein I stood.

15:49:00.510 --> 15:49:11.710
I began, too, to think that my imaginings were of the nights and the gloom and the unrest that I had gone through, and all the terrible anxiety.

15:49:11.710 --> 15:49:25.010
It was as though my memories of all of Jonathan's horrid experience were befooling me, for the snowflakes and the mist began to wheel and circle round,

15:49:25.990 --> 15:49:39.210
till I could get as though a shadowy glimpse of those women that would have kissed him, and then the horses cowered lower and lower and moaned in terror as men do in pain.

15:49:40.030 --> 15:49:44.930
Even the madness of fright was not to them, so they could not break away.

15:49:45.810 --> 15:49:52.310
I feared for my dear Madame Mina when these weird figures drew nearer and circled round.

15:49:54.130 --> 15:49:59.310
I looked at her, but she sat calm and smiled at me.

15:49:59.310 --> 15:50:11.210
When I would have stepped to defy her to replenish it, she caught me and held me back, and whispered, like a voice that one hears in a dream so low it was,

15:50:12.610 --> 15:50:17.550
No, no, do not go without. Here you are safe.

15:50:20.050 --> 15:50:26.590
I turned to her, and looking in her eyes said, But you, it is for you that I fear.

15:50:29.430 --> 15:50:42.130
Whereat she laughed, and laughed low and unreal, and said, Fear for me. Why fear for me? None safer in all the world from them than I am.

15:50:42.870 --> 15:50:52.190
And as I wondered the meaning of her words, a puff of wind made the flame leap up, and I see the red scar on her forehead.

15:50:53.290 --> 15:50:56.070
Then, alas, I knew.

15:50:58.330 --> 15:51:07.270
Did I not, I would soon have learned, for the wheeling figures of mist and snow came closer, but keeping ever without the holy circle.

15:51:08.290 --> 15:51:15.810
They began to materialize till, if God had not taken away my reason, for I saw it through my eyes.

15:51:18.150 --> 15:51:28.650
There were before me in actual flesh the same three women that Jonathan saw in the room, when they would have kissed his throat.

15:51:29.430 --> 15:51:40.090
I knew the swaying round forms, the bright hard eyes, the white teeth, the ruddy color, the voluptuous lips.

15:51:40.090 --> 15:51:52.210
They smiled ever at poor dear Madame Mina, and as their laugh came through the silence of the night, they twined their arms and pointed to her,

15:51:52.610 --> 15:52:05.410
and said in those so sweet tingling tones that Jonathan said were of the intolerable sweetness of the water glasses, Come sister, come to us, come.

15:52:07.770 --> 15:52:15.530
In fear I turned to my poor Madame Mina, and my heart with gladness leapt like flame.

15:52:16.090 --> 15:52:24.610
For oh, the terror in her sweet eyes, the repulsion, the horror, told a story to my heart that was all of hope.

15:52:25.270 --> 15:52:28.410
God be thanked that she was not yet of them.

15:52:28.410 --> 15:52:37.410
I seized some of the firewood which was by me, and holding out some of the wafer, advanced on them towards the fire.

15:52:37.990 --> 15:52:42.470
They drew back before me and laughed their low horrid laugh.

15:52:43.050 --> 15:52:52.830
I fed the fire and feared them not, for I knew that we were safe within the ring, which she could not leave no more than they could enter.

15:52:52.830 --> 15:52:57.330
The horses had ceased to moan and lay still on the ground.

15:52:57.890 --> 15:53:01.470
The snow fell on them softly and they grew whiter.

15:53:02.290 --> 15:53:06.550
I knew that there was for the poor beast no more of terror.

15:53:08.210 --> 15:53:14.150
And so it remained till the red of the dawn began to fall through the snow gloom.

15:53:15.430 --> 15:53:20.870
I was desolate and afraid and full of woe and terror.

15:53:21.870 --> 15:53:29.270
For when that beautiful sun began to climb the horizon, life was to me again.

15:53:30.510 --> 15:53:37.810
At the first coming of the dawn, the horrid figures melted in the whirling mist and snow.

15:53:39.450 --> 15:53:46.350
The wreaths of transparent gloom moved away towards the castle and were lost.

15:53:48.990 --> 15:53:55.890
Instinctively, with the dawn coming, I turned to Madame Inna, intending to hypnotize her.

15:53:56.330 --> 15:54:01.430
But she lay in a deep and sudden sleep from which I could not wake her.

15:54:02.090 --> 15:54:09.790
I tried to hypnotize her through sleep, but she made no response, none at all, and the day broke.

15:54:09.790 --> 15:54:18.350
I fear yet to stir. I have made my fire, and if seen the horses, they are all dead.

15:54:19.490 --> 15:54:27.670
Today I have much to do here, and I keep waiting till the sun is up high, for there may be places where I must go.

15:54:28.830 --> 15:54:34.550
Where there is sunlight, though snow and mist obscure it, will be to me a safety.

15:54:34.550 --> 15:54:40.870
I will strengthen me with breakfast, and then I will do my terrible work.

15:54:41.970 --> 15:54:47.890
Madame Inna still sleeps, and God be thanked, she is calm in her sleep.

15:54:51.490 --> 15:54:53.770
Jonathan Harker's Journal

15:54:54.470 --> 15:54:56.710
4 November, evening

15:54:57.870 --> 15:55:01.570
The accident to the launch has been a terrible thing for us.

15:55:02.130 --> 15:55:08.010
Only for it we should have overtaken the boat long ago, and by now my dear Mina would have been free.

15:55:08.790 --> 15:55:14.890
I fear to think of her, off on the wolds, near that horrid place.

15:55:16.370 --> 15:55:19.590
We have got horses, and we follow on the track.

15:55:19.590 --> 15:55:24.450
I note this while Galdeming is getting ready. We have our arms.

15:55:25.190 --> 15:55:27.630
The Sizgani must look out if they mean to fight.

15:55:28.730 --> 15:55:32.950
Oh, if only Morris and Seward were with us. We must only hope.

15:55:33.790 --> 15:55:39.030
If I write no more, good-bye Mina. God bless and keep you.

15:55:43.050 --> 15:55:44.680
Dr. Seward's Diary

15:55:46.390 --> 15:55:49.570
5 November, evening

15:55:49.590 --> 15:55:56.010
With the dawn we saw the body of Sizgani before us dashing away from the river with their leader-wagon.

15:55:57.250 --> 15:56:01.550
They surrounded it in a cluster and hurried along as though beset.

15:56:02.350 --> 15:56:06.470
The snow is falling lightly and there is strange excitement in the air.

15:56:07.170 --> 15:56:10.630
It may be our own feelings, but the depression is strange.

15:56:11.530 --> 15:56:14.150
Far off I hear the howling of wolves.

15:56:14.150 --> 15:56:21.290
The snow brings them down from the mountains, and there are dangers to all of us and from all sides.

15:56:22.030 --> 15:56:25.110
The horses are nearly ready and we are soon off.

15:56:25.750 --> 15:56:36.150
We ride to death of someone. God alone knows who, or where, or what, or when, or how it may be.

15:56:39.710 --> 15:56:42.650
Dr. Van Helsing's Memorandum

15:56:44.290 --> 15:56:46.730
5 November, afternoon

15:56:47.950 --> 15:56:55.630
I am at least sane. Thank God for that mercy at all events, though the proving it has been dreadful.

15:56:56.330 --> 15:57:02.310
When I left Madame Mina, sleeping within the holy circle, I took my way to the castle.

15:57:03.230 --> 15:57:07.610
The blacksmith-hammer which I took in the carriage from Varetsi was useful.

15:57:07.610 --> 15:57:19.570
Though the doors were all open, I broke them off the rusty hinges, lest some ill-intent or ill-chant should close them, so that being entered I might not get out.

15:57:20.270 --> 15:57:23.230
Jonathan's bitter experience served me here.

15:57:23.870 --> 15:57:30.630
By memory of his diary I found my way to the old chapel, for I knew that here my work lay.

15:57:30.630 --> 15:57:38.770
The air was oppressive. It seemed as if there were some sulfurous fume, which at times made me dizzy.

15:57:39.570 --> 15:57:44.870
Either there was a roaring in my ears, or I heard afar off the howl of wolves.

15:57:45.870 --> 15:57:54.210
Then I bethought me of my dear Madame Mina, and I was in terrible plight. The dilemma had me between his horns.

15:57:56.790 --> 15:58:06.230
Her I had dared not take into this place, but left safe from the vampire and that holy circle, and yet even there would be the wolf.

15:58:06.930 --> 15:58:13.230
I resolved me that my work lay here, and that as to the wolves we must submit if it were God's will.

15:58:14.090 --> 15:58:19.770
At any rate it was only death and freedom beyond, so I did choose for her.

15:58:20.850 --> 15:58:24.270
Had it but been for myself the choice had been easy.

15:58:24.690 --> 15:58:32.450
The maw of the wolf were better to rest in than the grave of the vampire, so I made my choice to go on with my work.

15:58:34.530 --> 15:58:44.150
I knew that there were at least three graves to find, graves that are inhabit, so I search and search and I find one of them.

15:58:44.150 --> 15:58:53.270
She lay in her vampire sleep, so full of life and voluptuous beauty that I shudder as though I have come to do murder.

15:58:54.450 --> 15:59:06.450
I doubt not that in the old time, when such things were, many a man who set forth to do such a task as mine, found at the last his heart fail him, and then his nerve.

15:59:06.450 --> 15:59:22.650
So he delay and delay and delay till the mere beauty and the fascination of the wanting undead have hypnotized him, and he remain on and on till sunset come and the vampire sleep be over.

15:59:22.650 --> 15:59:42.690
Then the beautiful eyes of the fair woman open and look love, and the voluptuous mouth present to a kiss, and the man is weak, and there remain one more victim in the vampire fold, one more to swell the grim and grisly ranks of the undead.

15:59:44.890 --> 16:00:03.510
There is some fascination, surely, when I am moved by the mere presence of such a one, even lying as she lay in a tomb threaded with age and heavy with the dust of centuries, though there be that horrid odor such as the lairs of the Count have had.

16:00:03.510 --> 16:00:19.690
Yes, I was moved. I, Van Helsing, with all my purpose and my motive for hate, I was moved to a yearning for delay which seemed to paralyze my faculties and to clog my very soul.

16:00:19.690 --> 16:00:35.690
It may have been that the need of natural sleep and the strange oppression of the air were beginning to overcome me. Certain it was that I was lapsing into sleep, the open-eyed sleep of one who yields to a sweet fascination.

16:00:35.690 --> 16:00:51.830
When there came through the window snow stilled a long low wail, so full of woe and pity that it woke me like the sound of a clarion, for it was the voice of my dear Madame Mina that I heard.

16:00:54.370 --> 16:01:12.130
Then I braced myself again to my horrid task and found by retching away tomb-tops one other of the sisters, the other dark one. I dared not pause to look on her as I had on her sister, thus once more I should begin to be enthralled.

16:01:12.130 --> 16:01:26.670
But I go on searching, until presently I find in a high great tomb as if made to be one such beloved that other fair sister. Like Jonathan I have seen to gather herself out of the atoms of the mist.

16:01:26.670 --> 16:01:44.770
She was so fairer to look on, so radiantly beautiful, so exquisitely voluptuous, that the very instinct of man in me, which calls some of my sex to love and to protect one of hers, made my head whirl with new emotion.

16:01:44.770 --> 16:02:03.710
But God be thanked, that so the wail of my dear Madame Mina had not died out of my ears, and before the spell could be wrought further upon me I had nerved myself to my wild work. By this time I had searched all the tombs in the chapel as far as I could tell.

16:02:04.830 --> 16:02:25.250
And as there had been only three of these undead phantoms around us in the night, I took it that there were no more of active undead existent. There was one great tomb more lordly than all the rest, huge it was and nobly proportioned. On it was but one word.

16:02:53.830 --> 16:02:55.230
DRACULA

16:02:57.930 --> 16:03:15.830
Then began my terrible task, and I dreaded it. Had it been but one, it would have been easy, comparative, but three, to begin twice more after I had been through a deed of horror. But it was terrible with the sweet Miss Lucy.

16:03:16.910 --> 16:03:29.970
What would it not be with these strange ones who had survived through centuries, and who would have been strengthened by the passing of the years? Who would, if they could, have fought for their foul lives?

16:03:32.590 --> 16:03:45.830
Oh, my friend Jean, it was bushier work. Had I not been nerved by thoughts of other dead, and of the living over whom hung such a pall of fear, I could not have gone on.

16:03:45.830 --> 16:04:08.050
I trembled and trembled even yet, though till all was over, God be thanked, my nerve did stand. Had I not seen the repose in the first place, and the gladness that stole over it just ere the final dissolution came, as realization that the soul had been won, I could not have gone farther with my bushery.

16:04:08.050 --> 16:04:18.310
I could not have endured the horrid screeching as the stake drove home, the plunging of writhing form and the lips of bloody foam.

16:04:20.010 --> 16:04:35.010
I should have fled in terror and left my work undone, but it is over, and the poor souls, I can pity them now and weep, as I think of them placid, each in her full sleep of death for a short moment there fading.

16:04:35.930 --> 16:04:55.130
For, friend Jean, hardly had my knife severed the head of each before the whole body began to melt away and crumble into its native dust, as though death that should have come centuries ago had at last asserted himself and say at once and loud, I am here.

16:04:56.650 --> 16:05:04.430
Before I left the castle I saw fixies' entrances that never more can the Count enter there undead.

16:05:06.730 --> 16:05:17.230
When I stepped into the circle where Madame Mina slept, she woke from her sleep, and seeing me cried out in pain that I had endured too much.

16:05:17.230 --> 16:05:27.030
Come, she said, come away from this awful place. Let us go to meet my husband, who is, I know, coming towards us.

16:05:27.570 --> 16:05:34.130
She was looking thin and pale and weak, but her eyes were pure and glowed with fervour.

16:05:34.570 --> 16:05:42.550
I was glad to see her paleness and her illness, for my mind was full of the fresh horror of that ruddy vampire sleep.

16:05:42.550 --> 16:05:55.590
And so with trust and hope and yet full of fear we go eastward to meet our friends, and him, will Madame Mina tell me that she know are coming to meet us.

16:05:59.490 --> 16:06:01.690
Mina Harker's Journal

16:06:03.670 --> 16:06:04.910
6 November

16:06:06.750 --> 16:06:15.010
It was late in the afternoon when the Professor and I took our way towards the east, whence I knew Jonathan was coming.

16:06:15.010 --> 16:06:23.350
We did not go fast, though the way was steeply downhill, for we had to take heavy rugs and wraps with us.

16:06:23.830 --> 16:06:29.030
We dare not face the possibility of being left without warmth in the cold and the snow.

16:06:30.070 --> 16:06:41.630
We had to take some of our provisions too, for we were in perfect desolation, and as far as we could see through the snowfall, there was not even the sign of habitation.

16:06:43.270 --> 16:06:49.430
When we had gone about a mile, I was tired with the heavy walking and sat down to rest.

16:06:50.270 --> 16:07:04.470
Then we looked back and saw where the clear line of Dracula's Castle cut the sky, for we were so deep under the hill whereon it was set, that the angle of perspective of the Carpathian Mountains was far below it.

16:07:04.470 --> 16:07:18.590
We saw it in all its grandeur, perched a thousand feet on the summit of a sheer precipice, and was seemingly a great gap between it and the steep of the adjacent mountain on any side.

16:07:20.350 --> 16:07:27.870
There was something wild and uncanny about the place. We could hear the distant howling of wolves.

16:07:27.870 --> 16:07:38.200
They were far off, but the sound, even though coming muffled through the deadening snowfall, was full of terror.

16:07:39.650 --> 16:07:50.310
I knew from the way Dr. Van Helsing was searching about that he was trying to seek some strategic point where we'd be less exposed in case of attack.

16:07:50.310 --> 16:07:57.210
The rough roadway still led downwards. We could trace it through the drifted snow.

16:07:59.870 --> 16:08:06.310
In a little while, the Professor signaled to me, so I got up and joined him.

16:08:06.310 --> 16:08:16.490
He had found a wonderful spot, a sort of natural hollow in a rock, with an entrance like a doorway between two boulders.

16:08:17.850 --> 16:08:20.490
He took me by the hand and drew me in.

16:08:21.410 --> 16:08:29.650
See, he said, here you will be in shelter, and if the wolves do come I can meet them one by one.

16:08:30.750 --> 16:08:38.890
He brought in our furs, and made a snug nest for me, and got out some provisions and forced them upon me.

16:08:40.430 --> 16:08:51.610
But I could not eat. To even try to do so was repulsive to me, and much as I would have liked to please him, I could not bring myself to the attempt.

16:08:52.750 --> 16:08:57.810
He looked very sad, but did not reproach me.

16:08:58.330 --> 16:09:06.030
Taking his field glasses from the case, he stood on top of the rock, and began to search the horizon.

16:09:08.490 --> 16:09:11.330
Suddenly, he called out,

16:09:12.090 --> 16:09:16.190
Look! Madam Nina, look, look!

16:09:16.930 --> 16:09:23.990
I sprang up, and stood beside him on the rock. He handed me his glasses and pointed.

16:09:25.390 --> 16:09:33.570
The snow was now falling more heavily, and swirled about fiercely, for a high wind was beginning to blow.

16:09:34.790 --> 16:09:42.390
However, there were times when there were pauses between the snow flurries, and I could see a long way round.

16:09:44.270 --> 16:10:01.510
From the height where we were, it was possible to see a great distance, and far off, beyond the white waste of snow, I could see the river lying like a black ribbon, in kinks and curls as it wound its way.

16:10:02.490 --> 16:10:14.930
Straight in front of us, and not far off, in fact so near that I wondered we had not noticed before, came a group of mounted men hurrying along.

16:10:16.330 --> 16:10:28.830
In the midst of them was a cart, a long leader-wagon, which swept from side to side like a dog's tail wagging, with each stern inequality of the road.

16:10:29.910 --> 16:10:38.050
Outlined against the snow as they were, I could see from the men's clothes that they were peasants or gypsies of some kind.

16:10:40.070 --> 16:10:49.790
On the cart was a great square chest. My heart leaped as I saw it, for I felt that the end was coming.

16:10:50.470 --> 16:11:04.890
The evening was now drawing close, and well I knew that at sunset, the Thing, which was till then imprisoned there, would take new freedom, and could in any of many forms elude pursuit.

16:11:05.590 --> 16:11:14.390
In fear, I turned to the Professor. To my consternation, however, he was not there.

16:11:15.470 --> 16:11:26.710
An instant later, I saw him below me. Round the rock, he had drawn a circle, such as we had found shelter in last night.

16:11:30.030 --> 16:11:38.970
When he had completed it, he stood beside me again, saying, At least you shall be safe from him.

16:11:40.450 --> 16:11:47.410
He took the glasses from me, and at the next lull of the snow swept the whole space below us.

16:11:49.290 --> 16:11:57.210
See, he said, they come quickly. They are flogging the horses and galloping as hard as they can.

16:11:58.790 --> 16:12:10.290
He paused, and went on in a hollow voice. They are racing for the sunset. We may be too late. God's will be done.

16:12:11.710 --> 16:12:19.150
Down came another blinding rush of driving snow, and the whole landscape was blotted out.

16:12:21.450 --> 16:12:26.950
It soon passed, however, and once more his glasses were fixed on the plain.

16:12:28.290 --> 16:12:41.010
Then came a sudden cry. Look, look, look. See, two horsemen follow fast, coming up from the south.

16:12:42.090 --> 16:12:48.610
It must be Quincy and John. Take the glass. Look before the snow blots it all out.

16:12:49.830 --> 16:12:57.210
I took it, and looked. The two men might be Dr. Seward and Mr. Morris.

16:12:58.010 --> 16:13:05.750
I knew at all events that neither of them was Jonathan. At the same time, I knew that Jonathan was not far off.

16:13:06.570 --> 16:13:15.030
Looking around, I saw on the north side of the coming party two other men, riding at breakneck speed.

16:13:16.250 --> 16:13:25.770
One of them, I knew, was Jonathan, and the other I took. Of course, to be Lord Galdiming.

16:13:26.730 --> 16:13:29.390
They too were pursuing the party with the cart.

16:13:31.750 --> 16:13:41.070
When I told the professor, he shouted in glee like a schoolboy, and after looking intently till a snowfall made sight impossible,

16:13:41.070 --> 16:13:49.070
he laid his Winchester rifle ready for use against the boulder at the opening of our shelter.

16:13:50.490 --> 16:13:57.510
They are all converging, he said. When the time comes, we shall have gypsies on all sides.

16:13:58.650 --> 16:14:06.490
I got out my revolver ready to hand, for whilst we were speaking the howling of wolves came louder and closer.

16:14:07.450 --> 16:14:11.690
When the snowstorm abated a moment, we looked again.

16:14:12.850 --> 16:14:17.670
It was strange to see the snow falling in such heavy flakes close to us.

16:14:18.650 --> 16:14:29.670
And beyond, the sun shining more and more brightly as it sank down towards the far mountaintops, sweeping the glass all around us.

16:14:29.670 --> 16:14:36.750
I could see here and there dots moving singly and in twos and threes in larger numbers.

16:14:38.050 --> 16:14:40.770
The wolves were gathering for their prey.

16:14:43.610 --> 16:14:56.670
Every instant seemed an age whilst we waited. The wind came now in fierce bursts, and the snow was driven with fury as it swept upon us in circling eddies.

16:14:59.090 --> 16:15:08.970
At times we could not see in arm's length before us, but at others, as the hollow sounding wind swept by us,

16:15:10.690 --> 16:15:15.690
it seemed to clear the airspace around us so that we could see afar off.

16:15:16.890 --> 16:15:25.730
We had of late become so accustomed to watch for sunrise and sunset that we knew with fair accuracy when it would be,

16:15:25.730 --> 16:15:29.230
and we knew that before long the sun would set.

16:15:30.870 --> 16:15:40.070
It was hard to believe that by our watches it was less than an hour that we waited in that rocky shelter

16:15:40.730 --> 16:15:45.450
before the various bodies began to converge close upon us.

16:15:46.910 --> 16:15:52.730
The wind came now with fiercer and more bitter sweeps and more steadily from the north.

16:15:52.730 --> 16:16:01.190
It seemingly had driven the snow clouds from us, for with only occasional bursts the snow fell.

16:16:02.450 --> 16:16:09.910
We could distinguish clearly the individuals of each party, the pursued and the pursuers.

16:16:11.750 --> 16:16:19.610
Strangely enough, those pursued did not seem to realize it, or at least to care that they were pursued.

16:16:21.190 --> 16:16:28.710
They seemed, however, to hasten with redoubled speed as the sun dropped lower and lower on the mountaintops.

16:16:30.350 --> 16:16:38.350
Closer and closer they drew. The professor and I crouched down behind our rock and held our weapons ready.

16:16:39.490 --> 16:16:42.970
I could see that he was determined that they should not pass.

16:16:44.470 --> 16:16:53.850
One and all were quite unaware of our presence. All at once two voices shouted out to halt.

16:16:55.270 --> 16:17:06.890
One was my Jonathan's, raised in a high key of passion, the other Mr. Morris's strong resolute tone of quiet command.

16:17:07.790 --> 16:17:17.010
The gypsies may not have known the language, but there was no mistaking the tone, in whatever tongue the words were spoken.

16:17:18.810 --> 16:17:29.990
Instinctively they reigned in, and at the instant Lord Galdeming and Jonathan dashed up at one side and Dr. Seward and Mr. Morris on the other.

16:17:31.150 --> 16:17:45.310
The leader of the gypsies, a splendid-looking fellow who sat his horse like a centaur, waved them back, and in a fierce voice gave to his companions some word to proceed.

16:17:46.370 --> 16:17:58.890
They lashed the horses which sprang forward, but the four men raised their Winchester rifles, and in an unmistakable way commanded them to stop.

16:17:58.890 --> 16:18:07.270
At the same moment Dr. Van Helsing and I arose behind the rock and pointed our weapons at them.

16:18:07.830 --> 16:18:12.950
Seeing that they were surrounded, the men tightened their reins and drew up.

16:18:14.370 --> 16:18:28.730
The leader turned to them and gave a word, at which every man of the gypsy party drew what weapon he carried, knife or pistol, and held himself in readiness to attack.

16:18:29.950 --> 16:18:32.090
Issue was joined in an instant.

16:18:33.870 --> 16:18:50.150
The leader, with a quick movement of his reins, threw his horse out in front and pointed first to the sun, now close down on the hilltops, and then to the castle, said something which I did not understand.

16:18:51.690 --> 16:18:58.550
For answer, all four men of our party threw themselves from their horses and dashed towards the cart.

16:18:59.270 --> 16:19:08.970
I should have felt terrible fear at seeing Jonathan in such danger, but that the ardor of battle must have been upon me as well as the rest of them.

16:19:10.190 --> 16:19:16.250
I felt no fear, but only a wild, surging desire to do something.

16:19:17.570 --> 16:19:22.650
Seeing the quick movement of our parties, the leader of the gypsies gave a command.

16:19:23.810 --> 16:19:34.730
His men instantly formed round the cart in a sort of undisciplined endeavor, each one shouldering and pushing the other in his eagerness to carry out the order.

16:19:36.470 --> 16:19:47.570
In the midst of this, I could see that Jonathan on one side of the ring of men, and Quincy on the other, were forcing away to the cart.

16:19:48.790 --> 16:19:53.210
It was evident that they were bent on finishing their task before the sun should set.

16:19:54.610 --> 16:19:57.690
Nothing seemed to stop or even to hinder them.

16:19:57.690 --> 16:20:09.880
Neither the leveled weapons, nor the flashing knives of the gypsies in front, nor the howling of the wolves behind, appeared to even attract their attention.

16:20:11.610 --> 16:20:20.110
Jonathan's impetuosity, and the manifest signalous of his purpose, seemed to overaw those in front of him.

16:20:21.090 --> 16:20:24.970
Instinctively, they cowered aside and let him pass.

16:20:25.570 --> 16:20:37.230
In an instant, he had jumped upon the cart, and with a strength which seemed incredible, raised the great box and flung it over the wheel to the ground.

16:20:39.050 --> 16:20:45.910
In the meantime, Mr. Morris had had to use force to pass through his side of the ring of sitsgani.

16:20:46.730 --> 16:20:51.190
All the time, I had been breathlessly watching Jonathan.

16:20:51.890 --> 16:21:04.710
I had, with the tail of my eye, seen him pressing desperately forward, and had seen the knives of the gypsies flash as he won away through them, and they cut at him.

16:21:05.450 --> 16:21:12.330
He had parried with his great bowie knife, and at first I thought that he too had come through in safety.

16:21:12.330 --> 16:21:26.810
But as he sprang beside Jonathan, who had by now jumped from the cart, I could see that his left hand he was clutching at his side, and that the blood was spurting through his fingers.

16:21:26.810 --> 16:21:44.110
He did not delay notwithstanding this, for as Jonathan, with desperate energy, attacked one end of the chest, attempting to prise off the lid with his great kukri knife, he attacked the other frantically with his bowie.

16:21:45.530 --> 16:21:49.970
Under the efforts of both men, the lid began to yield.

16:21:51.390 --> 16:21:56.790
The nails drew with a screeching sound, and the top of the box was thrown back.

16:21:58.210 --> 16:22:11.070
By this time, the gypsies, seeing themselves covered by the Winchesters, and at the mercy of Lord Galdeming and Dr. Seward, had given in and made no further resistance.

16:22:11.890 --> 16:22:19.610
The sun was almost down on the mountaintops, and the shadows of the whole group fell upon the snow.

16:22:20.850 --> 16:22:29.130
I saw the Count lying within the box upon the earth, some of which the rude falling from the cart had scattered over him.

16:22:29.130 --> 16:22:41.470
He was deathly pale, just like a waxen image, and the red eyes glared with the horrible, vindictive look which I knew so well.

16:22:42.330 --> 16:22:51.590
As I looked, the eyes saw the sinking sun, and the look of hate in them turned to triumph.

16:22:54.030 --> 16:23:01.310
But, on the instant, came the sweep and flash of Jonathan's great knife.

16:23:02.510 --> 16:23:12.350
I shrieked as I saw it shear through the throat, whilst at the same moment, Mr. Morris's bowie knife plunged into the heart.

16:23:13.590 --> 16:23:26.850
It was like a miracle, but before our very eyes, and almost in the drawing of a breath, the whole body crumbled into dust and passed from our sight.

16:23:28.590 --> 16:23:43.930
I shall be glad as long as I live, that even in that moment of final dissolution, there was in that face a look of peace, such as I never could have imagined might have rested there.

16:23:45.410 --> 16:23:57.830
The castle of Dracula now stood out against the red sky, and every stone of its broken battlements was articulated against the light of the setting sun.

16:24:00.010 --> 16:24:13.430
The gypsies, taking us in some way the cause of the extraordinary disappearance of the dead man, turned, without a word, and rode away as if for their lives.

16:24:14.210 --> 16:24:22.110
Those who were unmounted jumped upon the leader-wagon, and shouted to the horsemen not to desert them.

16:24:23.050 --> 16:24:31.510
The wolves, which had withdrawn to a safe distance, followed in their wake, leaving us alone.

16:24:33.430 --> 16:24:45.890
Mr. Morris, who had sunk to the ground, leaned on his elbow, holding his hand pressed to his side. The blood still gushed through his fingers.

16:24:46.690 --> 16:24:54.370
I flew to him, for the Holy Circle did not now keep me back. So did the two doctors.

16:24:55.650 --> 16:25:10.230
Jonathan knelt behind him, and the wounded man laid back his head on his shoulder. With a sigh he took, with a feeble effort, my hand and that of his own which was unstained.

16:25:12.330 --> 16:25:22.570
He must have seen the anguish of my heart and my face, for he smiled at me and said, I am only too happy to have been of service.

16:25:23.410 --> 16:25:38.030
Oh, God! he cried suddenly, struggling to a sitting posture and pointing to me. It was worth for this to die. Look! Look!

16:25:39.150 --> 16:25:50.230
The sun was now right down upon the mountaintop, and the red gleams fell upon my face, so that it was bathed in rosy light.

16:25:51.510 --> 16:26:02.630
With one impulse the men sank on their knees, and a deep and earnest amen broke from all as their eyes followed the pointing of his finger.

16:26:04.610 --> 16:26:20.290
The dying man spoke. Now God be thanked that all has not been in vain. See! the snow was not more stainless than her forehead. The curse has passed away.

16:26:20.290 --> 16:26:32.250
And to our bitter grief, with a smile and in silence, he died a gallant gentleman.

16:26:50.290 --> 16:27:04.610
I say to Mina and to me that our boy's birthday is the same day as that on which Quincy Morris died. His mother holds, I know, the secret belief that some of our brave friend's spirit has passed into him.

16:27:05.890 --> 16:27:11.810
His bundle of names links our little band of men together, but we call him Quincy.

16:27:13.190 --> 16:27:24.510
In the summer of this year we made a journey to Transylvania and went over the old ground which was and is to us so full of vivid and terrible memories.

16:27:25.190 --> 16:27:33.050
It is almost impossible to believe that the things which we had seen with our own eyes and heard with our own ears were living truths.

16:27:33.710 --> 16:27:43.550
Every trace of all that had been was blotted out. A castle stood as before, reared high above a waste of desolation.

16:27:45.270 --> 16:27:55.370
When we got home we were talking of the old time which we could all look back on without despair, for Galdeming and Seward are both happily married.

16:27:55.370 --> 16:28:01.250
I took the papers from the safe where they had been ever since our return so long ago.

16:28:02.090 --> 16:28:21.370
We were struck with the fact that in all the mass of material of which the record is composed there is hardly one authentic document, nothing but a mass of typewriting, except the later notebooks of Mina and Seward and myself, and Van Helsing's memorandum.

16:28:22.570 --> 16:28:30.710
We could hardly ask anyone, even did we wish to, to accept these as proofs of so wild a story.

16:28:32.450 --> 16:28:37.270
Van Helsing summed it all up as he said with our boy on his knee.

16:28:38.970 --> 16:28:49.310
We want no proofs. We ask none to believe us. This boy will someday know what the brave and gallant woman his mother is.

16:28:49.310 --> 16:29:01.430
Already he know her sweetness and loving care. Later on he will understand how some men so loved her that they did dare much for her sake.

16:29:19.950 --> 16:29:32.890
Marlowe Diane February 18-22 2006 Piscid West, Prince Edward Island
